<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Harvard Releases Plan for Workers  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS IVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- A Harvard University committee has devised a plan
to help its lowest-paid workers that includes increased health
coverage and workplace education.
</P>
<P>
   However the recommendations to be released Thursday in a
100-page report do not call for a $10-per-hour minimum wage pushed
by student activists and the city of Cambridge, where the school is
located.
</P>
<P>
   University President Neil L. Rudenstine is expected to approve
the plan with few changes, after a review process.
</P>
<P>
   The report, compiled over 13 months, calls on the university to
pay up to $1.5 million per year to provide literacy and GED
education for up to 500 employees who would be given paid time off
to take the courses.
</P>
<P>
   It also calls for the university to:
</P>
<P>
   -- Subsidize health insurance for all regular employees working
more than two days a week at a cost of about $500,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   -- Refuse contracts with companies that do not provide subsidized
health care.
</P>
<P>
   -- And enhance benefits to long-term part-time or temporary
employees at a cost of $333,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   The university has been under pressure from the city of
Cambridge and student activists to pay all of its workers at least
$10 per hour. The Progressive Student Labor Movement has led
several protests in favor of a ''living wage'' of $10.25. The City
Council last month passed a resolution urging the university to
adopt a minimum wage of $10.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that 2.9 percent of the university's workers
earn less than $10 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the Harvard Living Wage Campaign said it
welcomed Harvard's initiatives but was ''deeply disappointed'' by
the failure to address the wage issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
