<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Race Affects Justice  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new compilation of reports on racial
disparities in America's racial justice system concludes that
separate and unequal standards exist for the nation's minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''The results of this report are startling in their clarity,''
said Wade Henderson, executive director of the Leadership
Conference on Civil Rights, a civil rights coalition that planned
to release its report ''Justice on Trial'' at a news conference
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not suggesting that we establish laws that take it easy
on minorities,'' Henderson said. ''We want fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings in the 90-page report:
</P>
<P>
   --Nearly 74 percent of all those deported by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service are of Mexican origin even though Mexicans
are less than half of all undocumented people in the United States,
according to Immigration and Naturalization Service figures.
</P>
<P>
   --Hispanics are likely to be released in only 26 percent of their
cases while non-Hispanics are likely to be released before trial in
66 percent of their cases, according to the U.S. Bureau of Justice
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   --Blacks who killed a white were sentenced to death 22 times more
frequently than blacks who killed blacks and seven times more
frequently than whites who killed blacks, according to crime
researcher David C. Baldus.
</P>
<P>
   In pulling together the statistics, the civil rights coalition
hopes to start a public education and advocacy campaign to refocus
the attention of the public and lawmakers on the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ''For those who are concerned about civil rights and civil
liberties, criminal justice policies and practices must be analyzed
and challenged for their racially discriminatory effect,'' said
Laura Murphy, director of the American Civil Liberties Union's
Legislative Office.
</P>
<P>
   While the ''Justice on Trial'' report focuses on adults, other
information indicates the racial disparities extend to younger
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a national report from a leading criminal justice
think tank, the Youth Law Center, pointed to a ''cumulative
disadvantage'' for black and Latino youth in the nation's criminal
justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the findings was that a black youth is six times
more likely to be locked up than a white youth, even when charged
with a similar crime and when neither has a prior record.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say the skewed numbers could mean simply that
minority youth are committing more crimes or more serious crimes.
Todd Gaziano, a legal scholar at the conservative Heritage
Foundation believes many of the statistics used in such studies are
misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Mexicans cross back and forth (across the U.S. border) more
than other groups, it's more likely they are going to be picked
up,'' Gaziano said. ''So that statistic might not show any bias on
the part of immigration officials at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Others believe that racially discriminatory patterns of law
enforcement are behind the lopsided figures.
</P>
<P>
   ''There should not be a different level of justice for people
who are not white,'' Henderson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 0006 </TRAILER>
