<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disney, Time Warner Both Damaged  </HEADLINE>
By SETH SUTEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- One might think that huge companies whose main
form of business is entertaining people would be more conscientious
about keeping up a good public image.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is any one clear upshot from the bruising showdown
between Disney and Time Warner over carrying ABC and other Disney
programming on cable lines, it must be the public relations damage
each company has been willing to sustain to achieve its goals.
</P>
<P>
   Normally corporate spats remain in the business pages. But when
it's a matter of unplugging the top network from cable systems
serving millions of viewers, the issue was catapulted the issue to
the front pages of newspapers. ''Time Warner Caves on ABC,'' the
New York Post announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators, consumer groups and politicians were quick to react.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the two sides declared a cease-fire, the Federal
Communications Commission ruled Wednesday that Time Warner violated
agency rules in dropping ABC from its systems during the crucial
''sweeps'' ratings period. Penalties were pending.
</P>
<P>
   FCC chairman William Kennard had earlier accused the two
companies of holding consumer's TV sets ''hostage'' in their
dispute. New York's outspoken mayor Rudolph Giuliani also made his
objections known, saying the city's tall buildings rule out
antennas and satellite TV as options for many residents cut off
from programming. New York and Los Angeles were the largest markets
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups opposed to the concentration of media ownership
pointed to the hubbub as an example of what can happen when too
much power over what people see, hear and read is concentrated in
too few hands.
</P>
<P>
   In short, neither side won ground on the public relations front.
What's worse, this airing of dirty laundry comes at a highly
inopportune time for the media industry, just as CBS, Viacom,
America Online and Time Warner are seeking public approval of even
larger consolidations of power and industry titans are vying to
expand their reach to the Internet. The CBS-Viacom merger won final
approval Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both sides look bad,'' says Dennis McAlpine, a media analyst
at the brokerage Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. ''I think it's going to raise
some very interesting issues that aren't going to go away just
because the two sides have reached a truce.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got the whole issue of media control,'' McAlpine said.
''Can you allow Disney to use its ownership of ABC to force
carriage on cable systems of other channels like the Soap Opera
Channel?''
</P>
<P>
   Disney, for its part, says it is only seeking fair compensation
for its No. 1-rated ABC network. Time Warner says Disney's demands
would force it to incur significant costs that it would have to
pass along to subscribers. Disney had been asking, in part, that
Time Warner move the Disney channel from a premium service to the
basic cable package.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the dispute went so far as to result in a 39-hour
suspension of ABC from 3.5 million homes served by Time Warner
cable was what took aback many in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Chester, head of the Washington-based advocacy group Center
for Media Education, sees the incident as vindication of the
demands by his organization and others for greater scrutiny of
media giants. Chester was among several consumer advocates asking
the government to block AOL's pending merger with Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ironically, we owe these two warring, greedy conglomerates a
debt of thanks,'' Chester said Wednesday. ''It's taken a relatively
obscure issue -- open access to the Internet -- and placed it more
prominently among the public.''
</P>
<P>
   With the coaxial lines controlled by cable providers emerging as
a likely pipeline for carrying high-speed Internet and other
services into homes, consumer groups and others have been calling
for measures to ensure that the owners of those lines -- in this
case, Time Warner -- allow access to other providers of programming
and content.
</P>
<P>
   Cable providers and programmers have had other spats before.
News Corp.'s Fox network briefly pulled its signal from Cox
Communications in the opening days of this year in Dallas in a
dispute over adding other Fox channels.
</P>
<P>
   But the high profile and wide impact of the ABC dispute may have
permanently raised public awareness of the consequences of major
sparring matches between media giants.
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll see it again,'' said McAlpine, the analyst. ''It's all
about power, and who's willing to fight the hardest for the
principle. It also shows that cable operators are, under certain
circumstances, willing to cut their head off to spite themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
