<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate votes to ban guns in public buildings  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- An effort to ban loaded weapons from all
public buildings in Connecticut was shot down Wednesday when the
House failed to take up the measure approved by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which passed the Senate by a 24-12 vote, did not
make its way to the House before the midnight deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed legislation would require gun owners to check
loaded weapons at the door of public buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ''To be honest, I'd go for a tougher policy. I'd go for a
blanket ban-- loaded or unloaded,'' said Senate President Pro
Tempore Kevin Sullivan, D-West Hartford. ''I simply don't
understand why you would want to put people at harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Key Democratic lawmakers first proposed the legislation in
February to build on an executive order issued last year by Gov.
John G. Rowland banning state employees from bringing guns to work.
There is currently a prohibition against guns at the Capitol and
the Legislative Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said that many municipalities were unclear about how to
create local gun control policies, and this bill would give
authority to local and state police authority if they see a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said adding another gun control law to the books is
not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ''If all of these bills did what they were supposed to, we
wouldn't be here today,'' said Sen. Lou DeLuca, R-Woodbury. ''If
we're going to pass laws, they should be enforced.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLuca said there are currently 92 state laws pertaining to
firearms that do nothing to boost gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a nice bill, it's well-meaning, but I believe its
enforcement will be like those I mentioned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Nickerson, R-Greenwich, said such laws are
nonetheless needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lack of enforcement and public violation are not reasons not
to enact laws,'' he said. ''It's not a lofty goal. It's a very
practical goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Matthew Beck killed four of his superiors at the
Connecticut Lottery headquarters before committing suicide in March
1998, lawmakers have been pushing for tougher workplace safety and
gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, possession of a gun in any publicly owned or
operated building would be punishable by up to five years and
prison and a $5,000 fine. Law enforcement officers would be exempt
from the ban.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a law went into effect allowing police to confiscate
weapons from people determined to be a danger to themselves or
others.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 0027 </TRAILER>
