<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Eagles Trainer Davis Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Otho Davis, the trainer for the Philadelphia
Eagles for 23 years until retiring in 1995, has died of cancer. He
was 66.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a member of the National Athletic Trainers Association
Hall of Fame and the Eagles Honor Roll, died Tuesday night at St.
Agnes Medical Center in South Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't come any better than Otho,'' said close friend Rob
Incmikowski, 24. ''I'll never forget all he did for me and others
from all walks of life. He just loved watching people learn and
work to advance their careers, whatever it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Incmikowski became friends more than 10 years ago when
Incmikowski was working as a ballboy for the Eagles. Incmikowski
was the first recipient of the Otho Davis Scholarship at the Davis
Scholarship Foundation's inaugural dinner last November. More than
600 people attended the dinner to honor Davis two months after he
had been diagnosed with liver and pancreatic cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who was inducted into the Eagles Honor Roll last year, is
to be buried alongside his father in his hometown of Elgin, Texas,
with several of his favorite Eagles players as pallbearers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just as he cared for and carried the Eagles players through so
many injuries and tough times, it is only fitting that they now
honor him,'' said his wife, Mary Louise Davis.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Davis is survived by four sons, Mark
Davis, Harry Roy ''Duke'' Davis, Richard Davis and Thomas Davis; a
daughter, Denise Farrington, and six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral is Monday at First Presbyterian Church in
Moorestown, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
