<BODY>
<HEADLINE> John O'Connor Remembered by Many  </HEADLINE>
By DIEGO IBARGUEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cardinal John O'Connor was a man of fierce
conviction and unwavering faith. He was also a man remembered for
his compassion and sense of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cardinal O'Connor was a very religious, patriotic American who
served his country with pride and his God with great care, great
concern,'' said Raymond Flynn, the former mayor of Boston and U.S.
ambassador to the Vatican who was a longtime friend of O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor, 80, the oldest active bishop in the United States and
one of the country's most influential Catholics, died Wednesday
night. His health began to fail after he had a brain tumor removed
last August.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle DeHart, 24, went to St. Patrick's Cathedral following
O'Connor's death to mourn the man who enjoyed blessing the parades
that passed by its entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you think of St. Patrick's, you think of the cardinal. He
was their identity,'' she said, adding his replacement ''has got
some big shoes to fill''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop James Timlin of Scranton, Pa., where O'Connor served as
bishop before being appointed archbishop of New York in 1984,
remembered reporters asking about him at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ''They wanted to know what he was like, because they didn't know
who he was,'' Timlin said. ''I remember telling them, 'He eats very
little and he sleeps very little and he works very hard. So, look
out, New York.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi James Rudin, director of interreligious affairs for the
American Jewish Committee, said O'Connor left an ''indelible mark''
on Catholic-Jewish relations.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a prince. A lot of humor, and a lot of grace,'' Rudin
said. ''His contributions are really historic and indelible.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor earned the admiration of many Jews when last year he
expressed ''my own abject sorrow'' for any harm done to the Jewish
people by Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki praised O'Connor as ''a man of
remarkable faith and spirit who inspired New Yorkers of all
religions with his message of hope, compassion and love.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said the cardinal's public
stances were well known but that less known were his efforts to
help the poor, the sick and people suffering with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ''New Yorkers in particular are profoundly grateful for his
years of service to our city,'' Giuliani said. ''Cardinal O'Connor
made enormous contributions to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Reese, editor of the Jesuit magazine America, said
O'Connor would be remembered as ''the most powerful cardinal of
this generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''New York is a bully pulpit. He had talent and chutzpah, and he
was very close to the pope,'' Reese said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton honored the reach of O'Connor's influence.
</P>
<P>
   ''From his first Philadelphia parish to soldiers on the
battlefield, from the carnage of Bosnia to the tragedy of AIDS, he
also sought out and served those most in need,'' Clinton said.
''His lifelong journey of faith was our nation's blessing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 0031 </TRAILER>
