<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers 6, Braves 4  </HEADLINE>
By KEN PETERS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Atlanta's franchise-record 15-game winning
streak ended Wednesday night when the Los Angeles Dodgers beat the
Braves 6-4 and handed Greg Maddux his first loss of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' string was the longest in the majors since Minnesota
won 15 straight in 1991. The last time a National League team won
at least 15 in a row was 1951, when the New York Giants took 16
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Green and Todd Hollandsworth each homered and had three
hits off Maddux. Green hit a two-run homer in the fourth, his
sixth, and broke a 4-4 tie with a two-out, RBI single in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth hit a solo shot in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux (4-1) gave up nine hits and a season-high five earned
runs in a complete game.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had been 14-0 since reliever John Rocker returned
from his two-week suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Perez (2-1) gave up four runs on six hits in seven
innings. Mike Fetters worked the eighth and Jeff Shaw pitched the
ninth for his seventh save.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had not lost since April 15, falling 6-3 at
Milwaukee. The last team to win 16 in a row was Kansas City in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta shortstop Walt Weiss and catcher Eddie Perez and Los
Angeles shortstop Kevin Elster all left the game early with
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss went out after 4{ innings with a pulled left hamstring,
and Perez exited with a sore right shoulder and will undergo an MRI
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Elster left after 6{ innings with a right groin strain. There
was no immediate word on whether any of the three will miss more
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss' RBI single in the fourth drew Atlanta even after the
Dodgers had gone up 4-3 with three runs in the third. Third baseman
Adrian Beltre's throwing error on a grounder by Perez allowed
runners to advance to second and third before Weiss' hit.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Perez pitched out of a bases-loaded jam later in the
fourth, getting Chipper Jones to ground to Beltre for a forceout
for the final out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Green's homer and Gary Sheffield's run-scoring single brought
the Dodgers back from a 3-1 deficit in the third. The left-handed
Green hit a Maddux fastball on the outside part of the plate over
the fence in left field for his sixth homer.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta jumped off to 2-0 lead in the opening inning on RBI
singles by Jones and Brian Jordan. Los Angeles got one back in the
bottom half when Hollandsworth led off with a single and eventually
scored on Sheffield's groundout.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves extended their lead to 3-1 on Andres Galarraga's RBI
single in the third.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Los Angeles outfielder Devon White, who hurt his shoulder
trying to make a diving catch on Tuesday night, was not in the
lineup for Wednesday's game. Team doctors said White will under go
an MRI on Thursday on the shoulder, the same one he had surgery on
during the offseason. ... Since the Braves were behind going into
the ninth, Rocker got the night off. Rocker, who was mooned by a
fan in Monday's game, posted saves in both that game and Tuesday
night's win by Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 0036 </TRAILER>
