<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders outline $17.1 billion transportation plan  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Interstate 86, envisioned by supporters as
four modern lanes of prosperity and commerce for a struggling swath
of upstate New York, would be fully funded under a five-year
bridge- and road-building program outlined by state leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and legislative leaders said Wednesday some
$425 million would be provided by the state to transform Route 17
into Interstate 86. The necessary improvements would either be
completed or started within the next five years under the new
capital program and finished within about seven years, according to
state Department of Transportation spokesman Michael Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   The state money will make another $125 million from the federal
government and other sources available for Interstate 86, Fleischer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The $17.1 billion road- and bridge-building plan is designed for
implementation at the same time as a five-year, $17.1 billion,
program for mass transit. Both will coincide with adoption of a new
state budget for 2000-01, which could come later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Also with the new budget will come authorization to place a $3.8
billion transportation bond act before voters in November. Money
from the act would be applied toward both Interstate 86
construction as well as the centerpiece of the transportation
plan's transit phase -- the extension of the First Avenue subway
line to encompass the length of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The precise allocations from the bond act have not yet been
determined, Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   All told, some 4,000 transportation projects would be funded
through the five-year plan outlined Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A 177-mile stretch of Route 17, also known as the Southern Tier
Expressway, was renamed Interstate 86 recently when improvements
allowed it to meet federal standards for the designation. That
redesignated roadway is from Corning westward.
</P>
<P>
   A stretch of about 160 miles from Corning east to Harriman needs
improvements to win interstate designation.
</P>
<P>
   The roadway runs through a corridor which includes some of the
more economically disadvantaged parts of the state, from Sullivan
and Delaware counties to the Southern Tier. Residents have talked
for more than a generation about upgrading the roadway to improve
access to the corridor for tourists and commercial vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Thomas Libous, a Binghamton Republican, said it could
take another 15 years for Interstate 86 to be completed without the
infusion of state money, which state Senate Republicans pushed for.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic state Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said the
improvements were also a priority of his chamber, especially those
lawmakers from the financially struggling areas at the eastern end
of the roadway.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. Rep. Maurice Hinchey, a Democrat whose district include
parts of Interstate 86, questioned the need for the state funding
when $8 billion in federal transportation aid for 1999-2003 has
been set aside for New York.
</P>
<P>
   Hinchey said the cost of transforming Route 17 to a superhighway
would be ''just a tiny fraction'' of the federal money.
</P>
<P>
   ''One wonders why a bond issue is necessary is this context,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other 4,000 projects winning funding in the five-year
capital plan were:
</P>
<P>
   --$250 million to upgrade the Cross Westchester Expressway,
Interstate 287, from the Tappan Zee toll barrier to Interstate 684.
</P>
<P>
   --An additional $100 million to build Route 219 connecting
Springville and Salamanca in western New York.
</P>
<P>
   --$88.5 million to replace the Roslyn Viaduct in Nassau County.
</P>
<P>
   --$62 million to replace the Stutson Street Bridge and facilitate
access to the Lake Ontario waterfront in Monroe County.
</P>
<P>
   --$50 million to resurface and reconstruct Interstate 684 from
Harris Road to Interstate 84 in Westchester and Putnam counties.
</P>
<P>
   --$50 million to eliminate at-grade crossings on the Long Island
Railroad mainline.
</P>
<P>
   --$45 million to construct a new highway beginning at he
interchange between Routes 5, 12 and 8 and ending at the Judd
Road-Halsey Road interchange in Oneida County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
