<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton hits last of New York counties  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton, hoping to
convince New Yorkers everywhere that she cares about their
concerns, today visited the 62nd of New York's 62 counties since
she kicked off her Senate campaign in her adopted state 10 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's tour, which began last July on retiring Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan's farm near Oneonta, fittingly wound up in
the Clinton County city of Plattsburgh where she planned a
breakfast with supporters, a luncheon with local Democrats and a
rally at the State University of New York campus.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton made stops in three counties as she
combined a shopping trip with campaigning in Washington, Hamilton
and Franklin counties. Her campaign also unveiled its first
television advertisement, a 30-second biographical spot that was to
begin airing statewide today and promised she was ''more than a
first lady.'' The ad ends with the tag line: ''Hillary. Put her to
work for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton's Senate rival, New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, participated in a nationally televised college forum from
Rochester staged by MSNBC's ''Hardball'' show with Chris Matthews.
</P>
<P>
   In the first TV ad her campaign has paid for, Clinton doesn't
mention Giuliani, or even her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ''It never crossed my mind,'' she said when asked in Fort Edward
in Washington County about not having the president in her ad. She
then laughed. ''I'm using this opportunity to introduce myself and
what I've done for 30 years to the majority of New Yorkers. There's
so much that I want to communicate to people ... that the real
challenge was to put into 30 seconds everything that I wanted to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has been running TV ads off and on for several months
and the state Democratic Committee ran pro-Clinton TV ads late last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Both the first lady and her campaign aides have made it clear
that she believes she must establish her identity independent of
the president if she is to win the New York Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, she said Wednesday that it is still uncertain if
the president will attend New York's Democratic state convention on
May 16 when she will be nominated. Nonetheless, she said ''I hope
he'll be able to campaign with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's trip Wednesday took her to heavy Republican
country in Fort Edward and Hamilton County's Indian Lake in the
heart of the Adirondacks, and then for dinner in Malone in Franklin
County.
</P>
<P>
   But she picked up some Republican support along the way.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Edward, Leonard and Clara Bradway said that while they
were Republicans, they planned to vote for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she's a very great lady,'' Clara said. ''She's endured
a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans were not swayed.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a threat to New York state,'' said Dwayne Swanson, a
machine operator from South Glen Falls. ''She ought to go back to
Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Malone, another young Republican voter, Paula Dumas,
turned out to see Clinton and promised the first lady her vote come
November.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just because you're from the state doesn't mean you'll do the
best job,'' Dumas said. ''Giuliani doesn't even know where Malone
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who had never before lived or worked in New York, moved
to suburban Westchester County just north of New York City in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real joy that I'm having is to see this entire state in
all its beauty,'' she told more than 200 supporters at dinner in
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the dinner, a lone anti-abortion protester stood vigil
with a sign proclaiming ''Abortion kills children.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody cares,'' the woman, who refused to give her name,
bemoaned.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Giuliani are abortion rights supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The first made several stops along the way on Wednesday to
visits craft shops and antique stores. Among other things, she
spent $42 for a corner shelf cabinet she found at a shop in the
Adirondack village of Long Lake. She said it would be used at her
new house in Chappaqua.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 0048 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
