<DOCNO> APW20000504.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street analysts give cautious praise to debt deal  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- It is still too early to determine how a
deal among state leaders to curtail New York's borrowing would
affect the state's credit rating, Wall Street analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   It all depends on how well the state adheres to debt reform
guidelines imposed by lawmakers, said Colleen Woodell, director of
public finance at Standard and Poor's.
</P>
<P>
   ''Only time will determine if it works ultimately the way it was
designed to,'' Woodell said.
</P>
<P>
   The state's credit rating can directly affect taxpayers, who
save money when the credit rating goes up because interest rates on
state borrowing go down.
</P>
<P>
   ''An increase in the credit rating can mean better interest
rates for bonds, which means less cost to the taxpayer. The lower
the interest rate on the bond, the less we taxpayers have to
repay,'' said Michael McKeon, spokesman for Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday Gov. George Pataki, Senate Majority Leader Joseph
Bruno and Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver agreed to set a cap on
new debt at 4 percent of the state's personal income. The state
currently doesn't have any caps and borrows at a level of about 6
percent of personal income. The new cap would be phased in over the
next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The debt reforms will be approved along with a 2000-01 state
budget, the state leaders said. Aides in both the Senate and
Assembly said they expected their chambers today to begin adopting
the 11 bills constituting the new budget for the fiscal year which
began April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers agreed to pass a bill retroactive to April 1 that
would establish the debt cap. Pataki had advocated approval of the
legislation while a constitutional amendment was moving toward
passage by November 2001. During negotiations, the amendment idea
was put on hold and the idea of a statutory cap taken up because it
would make a more immediate impression on Wall Street credit
raters.
</P>
<P>
   ''An acting debt reform would be a positive step for the state,
but it would be more meaningful if it is enduring,'' said Robert
Kurtter of Moody's Investor Service. ''A statute could be amended
and altered by another bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodell agreed, saying that while the legislation ''shows a
level of commitment we've never seen from the state,'' it could
easily be undone statutorily.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno conceded Tuesday that the Legislature could abandon the
limits in the future if the state got into fiscal straits, but he
said he did not foresee that happening.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtter also said a statue alone would not work when it comes to
instituting other debt-reform changes like eliminating ''backdoor''
borrowing. A constitutional amendment is necessary to make those
changes, Kurtter said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first step, but more could be done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New York's highest-in-the-nation debt of $37.5 billion and its
poor borrowing practices have put it near the bottom in credit
worthiness among states.
</P>
<P>
   Standard and Poor's raised New York's credit rating from an ''A
to an ''A-plus'' in November 1999, but that still puts New York
tied with Hawaii for second-to-last place, with only Louisiana
doing worse. Moody's gave the state's bonds an A2 rating, tying New
York with Louisiana for the worst rating among the 40 states it
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Woodell said by setting a borrowing cap, New York is taking its
first step toward a better credit rating. A cap is common among
states with more highly rated credits, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not to suggest there's an upgrade around the corner,''
she said. ''How willing (legislators) are to live under it is going
to determine their success.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, Kurtter tried to spur legislative leaders and Pataki
to enact debt reform by putting out a report suggesting that a
credit rating boost could be the result.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 0050 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
