<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 00:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Acid rain bill only incremental step in long journey  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Amid considerable fanfare, lawmakers and
environmentalists this week said the state Legislature has
committed New York to the last big step the state can take alone to
combat acid rain pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate gave final legislative approval to a bill
prohibiting New York's utilities from selling leftover sulfur
dioxide pollution credits to power companies and industries in 14
Midwestern and Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   If signed by Gov. George Pataki, the law is the last unilateral
move left in New York to fight acid rain, proponents said.
</P>
<P>
   From here on out, New York would have to band together with
other states or, more ideally, compel Congress to substantially
reduce smokestack emissions nationally. That pollution is blamed
for killing fish, aquatic plants and trees in the Adirondacks and
other regions of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a federal problem and we would hope -- not passing the
buck -- we would hope that we'd get cooperation from Congress,''
state Sen. Ronald Stafford, a Plattsburgh Republican, said. ''We do
need this on a federal level.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the pollution credit bill say its importance lies
in what preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has said the state will stick by its plan to institute
tougher emission standards for vehicles sold in New York and he has
decreed that power plants in the state must reduce sulfur dioxide
and nitrogen oxide emissions to far below federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer has sued power
plants and electric utilities in Indiana, Ohio, Virginia and West
Virginia, seeking a reduction in their acid rain-causing emissions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It used to be that New York state would point its finger at
Ohio, and Ohio would point back at New York and say, 'See, look at
all the cars you drive, look at the emissions from your own power
plants,''' said Peter Bauer, executive director of the Residents'
Committee to Protect the Adirondacks. ''In the last year New York
has really done an about-face.''
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of the pollution blamed for acid rain is
generated within New York state and 80 percent comes from outside
the state. With the state's emissions on schedule to be reduced,
environmentalists say the focus on future acid rain-fighting
efforts must be on the federal level.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our hope is that the precedent-setting steps taken by New York
will serve as a wake-up call to Congress and provide them with the
motivation to find the federal solution that we have all been
seeking,'' said Robert Foster, legislative director for the
Citizens Campaign for the Environment.
</P>
<P>
   New York's efforts in Washington to fight acid rain are centered
around legislation sponsored by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and
Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, a bill which is stalled in committee.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would rein in allowable nitrogen and sulfur
emissions and is opposed by smog-producing states in the Midwest.
Previous attempts by New York lawmakers to push acid rain
legislation through in Congress have failed.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Richard Brodsky, a Westchester County Democrat
who chairs his chamber's environmental conservation committee, said
New York's pollution credit bill will create a ''huge who-ha''
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is promising that Washington will be spurred to
action by New York's unilateral anti-acid rain steps. Nor is anyone
holding out hope for an immediate payoff in terms of ''dead''
Adirondack lakes and streams suddenly springing back to life if
significant gains are won against emissions.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of this is about reducing acid rain,'' Brodsky said. ''It
is about stopping the increase in emissions.''
</P>
<P>
   Reversing the ecological problems caused by acid rain --
pollution which has been occurring ever since American factories
started burning high-sulfur coal on a large scale more than a
century ago -- is a puzzle yet to be solved, environmentalists said.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are now taking core samples of the bottom of dead
lakes in the Adirondacks to determine what their pH balance was
historically and to figure out how they can be reconstituted, Bauer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even trickier will be solving the ''very, very tough riddle'' of
how to fix the damage to the ecosystems of forests in the
Adirondacks due to pollution from sulfur dioxide, nitrogen,
mercury, aluminum and mercury, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''How to restore (the environment) is going to take a couple of
generations,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in
Albany. He can be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Capitol Station,
Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
