<HEADLINE> Three drug rings broken up in Rochester, 22 arrested  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Using informants, wiretaps and video
surveillance, police infiltrated three cocaine drug rings in the
Rochester region in a yearlong operation that culminated in the
arrests of 22 people.
</P>
<P>
   Seized in the pre-dawn raids Wednesday were three pounds of
crack and powder cocaine, $70,000 in cash and a cache of
assault-type weapons.
</P>
<P>
   All suspects identified by police were captured and indicted on
multiple felony drug charges, criminal conspiracy and weapons
possession. Among them were the suspected leaders of all three drug
gangs.
</P>
<P>
   New York Attorney General Spitzer called the undercover
investigation one of the biggest of its kind in upstate New York.
''In aggregate, the three rings constitute a big piece of the drug
distribution in Rochester,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While predicting that the clampdown would prompt ''some market
decline in access to drugs in the Rochester area in the near
term,'' Spitzer cautioned that ''it doesn't mean there will not be
regeneration of a distribution system if we're not vigilant.''
</P>
<P>
   The gangs were all based in Rochester, shipping in drugs from a
variety of sources, notably New York City and the Midwest, and
distributing them throughout the city and outlying regions,
including Genesee and Orleans counties in rural western New York.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said the investigation began, ''as so many of these
cases do, through tips from informants and people whom we turned
and then through a lot of aggressive cooperation'' among state,
county and city police agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Through a lot of cooperative effort -- turning more people,
wiretaps, surveillance, all the different undercover techniques --
we were able to take just a few random leads and build it into an
investigation that brought down 22 defendants and three major drug
distribution rings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ''There's no question these guys are prone to
violence. They use their weapons not only for intimidation but also
to commit violent crimes, and they have serious records.''
</P>
</TEXT>
