<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court documents shed light on Mother's Day slaying  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE VALLEY, N.Y. (AP) -- A day after a woman's body was found
near a jogging trail, a 15-year-old neighbor described how he raped
and then killed her to stop her from going to police, according to
newly released court documents.
</P>
<P>
   ''I meant to knock her out, by just cutting some of her breath
off. I ended up strangling her,'' the schoolboy scrawl of Edward
Kindt revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The strapping Salamanca youth detailed the killing in a
statement to police two days after Penny Brown, 39, a nurse and
mother of two, was killed during a Mother's Day run with her two
dogs last year.
</P>
<P>
   Her body was found the following day, partially buried. The red
leash from one of her dogs was wrapped three times around her neck.
</P>
<P>
   Kindt pleaded guilty March 8 to second-degree murder. Now 16, he
was sentenced Monday to nine years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Kindt's statement to police and other documents in the case were
unsealed Wednesday at the request of several news organizations,
including The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got scared and put her in a hole and (began) throwing brush
over her,'' wrote Kindt, a youth with a 1997 sex crime conviction
who had recently been thrown out of school for falling asleep.
</P>
<P>
   The murder of Brown, the daughter of a former mayor, by a Native
American youth raised fears about possible racial conflict in
Salamanca, the only U.S. city built almost entirely on Indian land
and the site of past conflict. A prosecutor cited the threat of
violence in successfully arguing to have records in the case sealed
until its conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Kindt's confession gives no indication that race was a factor in
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Kindt's guilty plea, defense attorneys Fern Adelstein
and Daniel Henry have said they would appeal. The plea, they said,
was to expedite the appeal process.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no way to bring an appeal until there's a finality to
the case,'' Henry said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys plan to challenge several pre-trial issues,
including the admissibility of Kindt's statements to police and his
being questioned without his mother present.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators said the boy's mother was asked to wait
outside the interrogation room to make it easier for Kindt to talk
freely.
</P>
<P>
   Police sought to question Kindt after encountering him on the
jogging trail while searching for a then-missing Brown. Kindt told
police at the time he was looking for a stick he had whittled the
day before.
</P>
<P>
   While Kindt showed little emotion at Monday's sentencing as the
victim's 14-year-old daughter and others tearfully described their
loss, he sobbed during his confession, documents show.
</P>
<P>
   ''He got emotional when he admitted it,'' Sgt. Timothy Whitcomb
of the Cattaraugus County Sheriff's Department testified in a
November hearing that was closed to the public. ''He started to
cry. He was sobbing. He was hugging (the state police investigator
questioning him).''
</P>
<P>
   The documents also indicate that investigators retrieved no
fingerprints from the dog leash used to strangle Brown. An autopsy
showed no sperm present.
</P>
</TEXT>
