<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Peace Process Rattled  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The deaths of seven U.N. peacekeepers in
Sierra Leone and the abduction of 50 others has rattled the peace
process in the small west African nation and raised doubts about
prospects for future U.N. peacekeeping on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Even with an announcement by rebels Wednesday night that the
U.N. hostages would be freed, the Sierra Leone case has already
become the last entry on the list of deadly U.N. missions in
Africa. By contrast, none of the more than 8,000 U.N. peacekeepers
sent to East Timor have been killed in clashes there.
</P>
<P>
   With the attacks this week rekindling memories of failed U.N.
missions in Somalia and Rwanda, the question now is whether a new
U.N. peacekeeping mission can succeed in the much bigger and more
complicated conflict in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan raised the issue Wednesday night,
saying the killings would almost certainly have a ripple effect on
current and future U.N. missions on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Already we know what happened after the tragedy in Somalia,''
Annan told reporters in Paris, referring to the 1993 deaths of 18
American servicemen in a botched U.S. raid in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
   The debacle led to a U.S. pullout from Somalia and all but ended
U.S. support for U.N. peacekeeping in Africa that only began to
change last year with approval for the mission in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   After the slayings of the past week, however, Annan said, ''I
think there's going to be very little encouragement for (western
countries) to get involved in operations in Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven U.N. peacekeepers have been killed and 50 abducted by
rebels of the Revolutionary United Front in clashes over the past
three days in the interior of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The 8,500-member U.N. force was dispatched in January to oversee
a cease-fire and peace agreement between rebels and the government
to end a bloody eight-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   RUF leader Foday Sankoh agreed Wednesday night to free any
hostages held by his organization. But Sankoh has made similar
promises in the past and it was unclear exactly when or if the U.N.
hostages would be freed. Sankoh did not directly acknowledge any
were being held by the RUF.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council and Annan have condemned the attacks and
blamed Sankoh for them, saying he would be held accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone's U.N. ambassador, Ibrahim M'baba Kamara, said
Sankoh was clearly trying to test the United Nations by challenging
its authority. But he warned that the failure of the U.N. force to
stand up to the challenge would have a wider impact than in his
country alone.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sierra Leone is a test case here,'' Kamara told reporters.
''If they fail in Sierra Leone, what chances are there that they
will succeed in'' Congo?
</P>
<P>
   Congo poses one of the biggest challenges yet to the United
Nations, which is planning to deploy a 5,500-strong U.N. observer
force in the coming weeks to monitor a cease-fire signed by six
warring countries and three rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a Security Council delegation led by U.S. Ambassador
Richard Holbrooke will begin a formal visit to Congo, Rwanda,
Uganda and other countries involved in the war to try to cement a
cease-fire and allow the U.N. forces to deploy.
</P>
<P>
   Security Council ambassadors have refused to speculate about the
implications that the Sierra Leone deaths would have on sentiment
for the Congo mission, which still hasn't received troop
commitments for the full 5,500 force.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they have stressed their support for the Sierra Leone
force and its commander and made clear that the United Nations
would stand for nothing less than cooperation from Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue of the Congo deployment was clearly on Annan's
mind after returning from West Africa and meeting with French
officials in Paris on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The behavior of Foday Sankoh and his troops risk complicating
the situation and the deployment of troops for the Congo because
the member states will be discouraged from sending their troops to
Africa,'' Annan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 0113 </TRAILER>
