<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Flood Victims Despair  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHOKWE, Mozambique (AP) -- More than two months after her home
was swept away by raging floodwaters, Caroline Sotho surveyed her
life from a crude shelter of wood and plastic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have nothing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The elderly woman, who does not know her age, was too frail to
run when Chokwe was engulfed by a muddy wave in the early hours of
Feb. 27. Neighbors loaded her into a wheelbarrow, pushed her to
higher ground and helped her climb a tree. She held on for three
days.
</P>
<P>
   Mozambique, whose devastating, 16-year civil war ended in 1992,
had been one of southern Africa's economic success stories, with an
average 10 percent annual growth recently. But the floods cut
economic growth projections to 6 percent for this year, and
inflation is expected to double to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding destroyed the homes or livelihoods of more than 10
percent of the country's 19 million people and caused about $1
billion in damage, according to the World Bank's preliminary
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, President Joaquim Chissano appealed for hundreds
of millions of dollars in aid at a conference in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ''Help is required now and not tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclones and torrential rains destroyed hundreds of thousands of
homes and farmlands and killed more than 700 people in February and
March.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Development Program has estimated that at least $450
million is required to rebuild homes, schools, hospitals, bridges
and roads devastated by Mozambique's worst natural disaster on
record.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of Chokwe, about 130 miles northeast of the
capital, Maputo, have little confidence that aid will matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one is going to see that money,'' said Richard Xhosa, a
local builder who believes corrupt officials will steal the aid.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in dozens of towns tell of aid being pilfered and
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Inyene Udoyen, a spokesman for the U.N. World Food Program, says
aid theft is inevitable in any emergency situation, but is hard to
monitor and control.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the moment we don't feel it's at an alarming level,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since relief operations began in February, almost 11,000 tons of
aid have been distributed.
</P>
<P>
   There are also signs that reconstruction is under way. Many
roads rendered impassable by the floods have been rebuilt, hundreds
of wells have been decontaminated and schools have been reopened.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have started to plant maize and beans,'' Chissano told
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The center of Chokwe, coated in a thick layer of sludge when the
floodwaters receded, has been cleaned up. Water and power supplies
have been reconnected, and the junior school has been reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Chokwe's 40,000 residents who took shelter at a
sprawling displacement camp at the village of Chaqualane to the
south have returned in recent days, and a handful with the strength
and money have begun erecting houses from mud and wooden staves.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despair haunts the town. Even if facilities are fully
restored, residents say they will still have lost their meager
possessions swept away in the flood. Finding work -- difficult
before the floods -- is now virtually impossible, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people are suffering here,'' said Xhosa, who was
working in neighboring South Africa when the floods struck.
</P>
<P>
   He lost his home and all his possessions, which he estimates
will cost $600 to replace -- a small fortune in a country where most
people live on less than a dollar a day.
</P>
<P>
   Chissano said more than 500,000 people who fled the floods are
still in displacement camps or are staying with relatives and need
to be resettled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
