<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Arson Suspects Go On Trial  </HEADLINE>
By KIM GAMEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOTEBORG, Sweden (AP) -- Prosecutors showed pictures of a charred
interior thick with debris as they sought to prove that four men
set fire to a stack of chairs and sent a blaze racing through a
crowded dance hall.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors and relatives of the 63 victims listened intently
Wednesday as prosecutors used diagrams and graphic photos to show
how they believe the four defendants poured flammable liquid over
chairs in an emergency stairwell, added torn pieces of paper and
set the pile alight.
</P>
<P>
   ''All four were in the immediate vicinity when it happened. They
knew that their actions would lead to a fire that could have
serious consequences,'' chief prosecutor Ulf Noren said.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with aggravated arson in the Oct. 29, 1998, fire that
killed 63 people and injured more than 200 are Shoresh Kaveh, 19;
Housein Arsani, 19; Mohammad Mohammadamini, 21; and Meysam
Mohammadyeh, 19 -- all Iranian-born Swedish residents. They pleaded
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to see their faces,'' Narin Cemal, 19, said during a
break in the proceedings. ''I still can't believe it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Her boyfriend, 17-year-old Daniel Gubic, gripped her hand on the
night of the fire until they were pulled apart in the crush of
young people fleeing the blaze. His face was scarred by burns.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why should I forgive them?'' he said. ''I will never be normal
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial began Wednesday in an exhibition center in Sweden's
second-largest city, Goteborg, 300 miles southwest of Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants were in one large room designed as the main
courtroom. More than 300 survivors and relatives of victims
gathered in a second room and watched the proceedings on
closed-circuit television. A third room was set aside for the
media.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants looked on quietly as lawyers argued their cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''My client ... denies responsibility for aggravated arson,''
said Goeran Bergendahl, Kaveh's attorney. ''He admits to having set
fire to a paper under a chair in the emergency staircase'' but did
not intend to hurt anybody, Bergendahl said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the victims were immigrants or children of immigrants.
The proceedings were translated from Swedish into Arabic,
Serbo-Croatian, Russian, Turkish, Spanish, Portuguese, Armenian and
six other languages.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the defendants set the blaze after three of them
argued with the party's organizers over the $5 entrance fee.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth youth let the other three into the building through
an emergency exit, where they found paper and a can of flammable
liquid, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Mohammadyeh's attorney, Leif Silbersky, claimed one of the other
young men brought the flammable liquid with him to sniff.
</P>
<P>
   The aggravated arson charge carries a sentence of six years to
life in prison, but Swedish law would allow a lesser sentence
because the suspects were under age 20 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Jurists, lawyers, prosecutors and some survivors and relatives
were to be taken in buses today to inspect the site of the fire. It
was not clear whether the defendants would be present.
</P>
<P>
   The dance was organized by four teen-agers who rented the hall
from the Macedonian Association. About 400 people were crammed into
a space licensed for 150 when the fire broke out.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Goteborg's Web site, with English-language site.
http://www.goteborg.se
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
