<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Join Vieques Protesters  </HEADLINE>
By MANUEL ERNESTO RIVERA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- With opposition growing in the
United States -- including from Hillary Rodham Clinton -- federal
agents faced the prospect Wednesday of arresting bishops and a
congressman who have joined protesters occupying a Navy bombing
range.
</P>
<P>
   In the most clear indication yet of a planned move against the
dozens of protesters blocking use of the Navy training ground on
Vieques, a Department of Justice official said Wednesday that they
would first be asked to leave in order to avoid confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ideal situation for the law enforcement professionals is
that we would like them to leave voluntarily,'' David Branham, a
spokesman with the Dept. of Justice, told The Associated Press.
''We are not seeking confrontations with protesters. What we are
asking is their cooperation to voluntarily leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they don't, appropriate law enforcement will be
implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plans in place for an operation quite soon, a justice
department official said on condition on anonymity. ''It will
include approximately 100 U.S. marshals and a number of FBI
agents,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Luis Gutierrez arrived Wednesday on the Puerto Rican island
of Vieques, where he planned to remain and face arrest with dozens
of others intent on making the Navy end its bombing exercises. A
federal raid to clear the range has been expected for days.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the final count, we are going to win peace for Vieques,''
the Illinois Democrat told demonstrators in the bomb-littered range
at dawn on Wednesday. Groups of Roman Catholic bishops and priests
have also joined the fray.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the first lady, meanwhile, said she opposed the
Navy's bombing exercises on Vieques. ''A small, inhabited island
should not be used for target practice,'' she said. ''I urge the
Pentagon to negotiate a peaceful resolution to this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon sent three warships -- reportedly carrying 1,000
Marines -- to the area Monday to help the Justice Department expel
the protesters, who began occupying the range in April 1999 after a
civilian guard was killed in an accidental bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy insists the 60-year-old range is vital to national
security as the only place its Atlantic fleet can conduct
simultaneous air, sea and amphibious training using live munitions.
The range has been used to prepare for every U.S. conflict since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   That argument has failed to win over the Vieques activists, who
enjoy broad support in Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory of 4 million
Spanish speakers.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Puerto Rico's government agreed Jan. 31 to
resume limited training until 2003, using dummy bombs instead of
live ones. They also agreed to allow a Vieques referendum, probably
next year, on whether the Navy ultimately should leave.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for $40 million in aid for the island's 9,400
civilians, who live between a Navy munitions depot on the western
third of the 21-mile-long island and the bombing range in the east.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the Navy would begin removing 1,600 tons of
munitions on Thursday so it can transfer the western third of the
island to Puerto Rico later this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the protesters to the east are blocking resumed training.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the Navy of Puerto Rico and the Navy of the United
States. We have a relationship that I want to improve,'' Adm. Kevin
Green, commander of the training ground, said after meeting
Wednesday with San Juan Mayor Sila Calderon, who supports the
Vieques cause.
</P>
<P>
   Calderon asked that a referendum be held before any resumption
of training -- a position also put forth by Mrs. Clinton. Green
noted that the existing deal is a presidential directive and told
reporters: ''It is not my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. National Council of Churches, the Geneva-based World
Council of Churches and the Pastors for Peace human rights group in
Chicago sent several bishops and pastors to the range last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Rep. Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., said nearly 50 members
of Congress had signed a letter urging President Clinton to hold
off arrests and hold a referendum before training.
</P>
<P>
   But Utah Representative Jim Hansen, a House Armed Services
Committee member who supports action against the protesters, said
the ''impending action'' was coming ''a year late and is the
culmination of a continuing failure of the Clinton-Gore
administration to properly support our military forces,'' said
Hansen, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nydia Velazquez, D-N.Y. -- who arrived in Vieques with New
York City council members Jose Rivera and Roberto Ramirez -- warned
that ''if arrests are conducted here, there are going to be
important implications elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez said he didn't believe President Clinton was ''at the
helm'' of the Vieques controversy. ''The armed forces have decided
that they want this island, that they don't want to negotiate,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart -- a harsh critic of the April
22 Justice Department raid to seize little Elian Gonzalez in Miami
-- demanded President Clinton call off a similar Vieques operation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Puerto Rican people are decent, hardworking American
citizens who do not deserve to be threatened,'' Diaz-Balart said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Navy Atlantic Fleet: http://www.atlanticfleet.navy.mil
</P>
<P>
   Links to Vieques activist groups: http://www.viequesvive.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
