<DOCNO> APW20000504.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Lawyer Won't Be Extradited  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Colombian attorney and anti-drug crusader
Victor Tafur will not be extradited to his homeland to face drug
trafficking charges.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Judge Charles Smith ruled Wednesday that U.S.
prosecutors failed to show probable cause for Tafur's extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Tafur had been sought by Colombian authorities since September
on charges he helped finance the largest cocaine shipment ever
seized in Colombia, a 7-ton cache intercepted in the Caribbean port
of Cartagena in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a gaping hole and we don't have the necessary link''
between Tafur and the drug shipment, Smith said. Government
attorneys said they have not decided whether to refile their
petition.
</P>
<P>
   Tafur, 36, would have been the first fugitive returned to
Colombia on drug charges since the two countries signed an
extradition treaty in 1979. The treaty was written in part by
Tafur's father, Donald Rodrigo Tafur, a former senator who was
killed in March 1992 outside his son's home in Cali, Colombia, in
what was presumed to be a settling of accounts by drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   ''He died in my arms,'' Tafur testified, adding that because of
his father's death, he would be ''the last person to be related''
to drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Tafur has been in the United States since last year, recovering
from injuries sustained in a plane crash and pursuing his master's
degree at Pace University in White Plains, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until my life is completely not at risk I cannot go back,''
said Tafur, who had been involved in drug eradication efforts in
his country.
</P>
<P>
   The government's case was based on a $350,000 payment that
Colombian prosecutors say Tafur made to a ''front company'' called
E.I. Caribe to arrange the drug shipment.
</P>
<P>
   Tafur's lawyers said he was engaging in a legitimate financial
transaction on behalf of his mother. Supporters say Tafur is the
victim of circumstance -- of a black-market dollar exchange system
that allowed checks he wrote to end up in the coffers of a
trafficker front company.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors tried to discredit Tafur's story, questioning why he
would have entrusted so much money to men he did not know.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was trying to put a legitimate gloss on what he was doing,
and he was sloppy about it,'' said federal prosecutor Thomas
Eicher.
</P>
</TEXT>
