<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regulators Approve CBS-Viacom Merger  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With final government approval in hand, CBS
and Viacom are speeding toward completion of a massive merger that
positions them to become a powerhouse in the radio, TV and film
worlds.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reunites a pair of entertainment giants that were
separated two decades ago: The company that became Viacom was spun
off from CBS in the 1970s because of government rules, since
repealed, that prevented networks from owning their own
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Viacom is buying CBS in a $44 billion deal that was
expected to close today.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission signed off on the merger
Wednesday, the final regulatory hurdle that the companies needed to
clear.
</P>
<P>
   The commission gave the companies one year to comply with rules
that limit the percentage of national audience one company may
reach through its own stations. Together, the companies would reach
41 percent of the national audience through its owned TV stations --
exceeding the agency's 35 percent cap. The companies are looking at
various options for coming into compliance with the restriction.
</P>
<P>
   CBS and Viacom also would have a year to comply with another FCC
rule that prohibits one entity from owning two networks. Under
their deal, the companies would control both CBS and the fledgling
UPN network, which Viacom owns. They would hold onto the UPN
network during the one-year period.
</P>
<P>
   But the FCC is in the midst of reviewing the dual network ban,
and it could be relaxed before the companies ever are forced to
shed UPN. Company officials have said that keeping UPN in the
company's fold is essential for the fledgling network's survival.
</P>
<P>
   The company leaders celebrated the combination of their
businesses, which gives them control of 38 TV stations, 162 radio
stations, a top TV network, a movie studio, several cable channels
and the largest outdoor advertising company.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a truly momentous and historic day occasion for Viacom
as we combine with CBS to create an unparalleled entertainment and
information enterprise, with incomparable creative capability and
extraordinary reach,'' Redstone said Wednesday. ''Our businesses
span all ages and all audiences, across virtually all media.''
</P>
<P>
   The new company will be called Viacom, but the CBS name will
remain on the network. Redstone will serve as chairman and chief
executive. CBS President Mel Karmazin will be president and chief
operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Viacom and CBS are two powerful companies, each with strong
fundamentals and complementary strengths, including a legacy of
creative excellence and brand building that is second to none,''
Karmazin added.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators also gave the merged company six months to abide by
rules that limit how many television and radio stations one company
may own in the same market. The agency ruled that in five markets --
Los Angeles, Chicago, Dallas-Fort Worth, Baltimore and Sacramento,
Calif. -- the combined company would exceed the caps.
</P>
<P>
   All five FCC commissioners backed approval of the deal, but two
dissented in part. Commissioner Gloria Tristani chastised the
commission for not adequately considering the impact the deal would
have on the diversity of voices in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ultimately, the American public will pay the price if they do
not have meaningful access to the diverse and antagonistic
viewpoints that democratic deliberation requires,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger brings together the owner of hip properties such as
MTV and VH1 with the old-line broadcast network that has brought
viewers ''60 Minutes'' and ''Murder, She Wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal gives CBS, which changed hands four years ago when it
was bought by Westinghouse Electric Corp., a television and film
studio to provide shows for its network. Viacom gains major
advertising outlets to promote the films and shows produced by
Paramount and its Spelling Entertainment TV studio. Together, the
companies will be able to rival conglomerates Time Warner Inc. and
Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   When announced in September, the CBS-Viacom marriage was the
richest media deal ever. But the proposed merger of America Online
and Time Warner -- valued at $162 billion in January -- trumped it.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of CBS fell $1.25 to $58.75 in trading Wednesday on the
New York Stock Exchange, where Class B shares of Viacom fell 92
cents to $54.37{.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 0133 </TRAILER>
