<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judges question verdict after unusual selection of jurors  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A prosecutor says an appeals court panel should
not overturn two convictions related to the 1991 Crown Heights
riots just because the trial judge chose two jurors out of sequence
to improve the racial and religious balance of the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Alan Vinegrad argued Wednesday before
the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals that the decision to take
jurors out of sequence was ''obviously unorthodox'' but did not
prejudice the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's been no showing of any bias in the jury or in the
trial because of it,'' he said after members of the three judge
panel raised the possibility that the verdicts could be reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The concern I have is really the public perception of the
integrity of the process and whether the court itself can be
involved in the abandonment of neutrality,'' said Judge Fred
Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Guido Calabresi called it an ''explicit violation'' of
jury selection rules and said the court must decide whether it can
be permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer James Neuman agreed, saying, ''This so
fundamentally affects the entire integrity of the system that it
cannot be approved.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 trial before U.S. District Judge David Trager in
Brooklyn ended in the conviction of Lemrick Nelson Jr. and Charles
Price on civil rights charges for inciting a black mob against Jews
during the riots. Nelson received 19 1/2 years in prison. Price got
21 years and 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   Both were convicted for their roles in the fatal attack of
Yankel Rosenbaum, a 29-year-old Australian man fatally stabbed on
Aug. 19, 1991. The stabbing occurred during four nights of unrest
in Brooklyn after a 7-year-old black boy, Gavin Cato, was fatally
injured in a traffic accident involving a car driven by a Hasidic
Jew.
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad noted that the defense and prosecution both accepted
the judge's decision shortly before opening statements to add a
black juror and a Jewish juror to the jury panel to replace two
members of the original panel who could no longer serve. Judges are
required to assign new jurors in the order that they were chosen as
substitute jurors. In this case, the judge went out of order.
</P>
<P>
   He said ''the procedure was undertaken in part for the benefit
of the parties who now complain about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that as an appellate court you can exercise your
collective discretion not to upset criminal convictions where the
parties in fact agree to the procedure,'' Vinegrad said.
</P>
<P>
   Calabresi questioned whether the issue went to the heart of
rules about who can try a case.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said the fact that the jurors were chosen out of order
likely represented ''the abandonment of racial and religious
neutrality.''
</P>
<P>
   ''At the bottom, what happened was that race was taken into
account, race and religion were taken into account,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After several minutes of argument on the issue, Vinegrad
conceded that the judges needed to at least make clear that the
unusual selection process should not become common.
</P>
<P>
   Calabresi questioned whether the judges should let the verdict
stand but warn prosecutors that ''in the future, if the prosecution
agrees to something like this it is acting in its peril because we
will reverse (the conviction).
</P>
<P>
   ''Sounds good to me,'' Vinegrad said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sounds better to you than it does to me, maybe,'' Calabresi
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Read it over a few times, you'll get used to it judge,''
Vinegrad said as laughter broke out in the courtroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 0136 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
