<DOCNO> APW20000504.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill allows gays, unmarried couples to adopt partners' children  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Gays and other unmarried people would be
able to adopt their partners' children under a bill Gov. John G.
Rowland says he will sign into law.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate gave final legislative approval to the measure
Wednesday after about an hour of debate on what constitutes a
family and what is in the best interest of a child.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe it makes perfect sense to acknowledge what is
current practice and not only accept but applaud people who want to
take responsibility for children who need to be adopted,'' said
Sen. Donald Williams Jr., D-Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill died in the House of Representatives last year
after it was amended to ban same-sex marriages. That amendment was
not raised this year, but language was inserted in the bill to make
clear that the measure would not affect current marriage laws.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut law does not recognize gay marriages, but allows
single gay people to adopt.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thomas Upson, R-Waterbury, proposed making the statute read
that traditional marriages are considered the best option for a
child. He argued that the bill, as written, could serve as a
springboard for proponents of gay marriage as had a similar bill in
Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont Supreme Court used an adoption law passed in that
state three years ago to overturn the definition of marriage and
allow same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   Upson's amendment was voted down.
</P>
<P>
   ''By its very terms, it suggests the ideal state of raising
children is by any two people who have married, regardless of the
state of that marriage,'' said Senate President Pro Tempore Kevin
Sullivan, D-West Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, a judge would have to decide whether it is in
the best interest of a child to be adopted by its parent's partner.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was written after the state Supreme Court ruled that a
lesbian could not adopt her partner's 6-year-old son because the
law restricted adoption to married couples.
</P>
<P>
   The child's mother was impregnated by artificial insemination,
using sperm from a man who legally surrendered his parental rights.
The mother and her partner planned the conception together, and the
partner was present at the boy's birth.
</P>
<P>
   In deciding the ''Baby Z'' case in January 1999, the Supreme
Court said the Legislature, and not the courts, must establish
adoption and family policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 0154 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0036 </DOCNO>
