<HEADLINE> Judge considering alleged juror misconduct to rule Monday  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- Scott Smith's fate now rests in one
man's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Charles D. Gill is scheduled to announce
Monday whether the former New Milford police officer will get a new
trial or a prison sentence following allegations of juror
misconduct during Smith's trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors in March convicted Smith, 28, of intentional manslaughter
for shooting a suspect in the back at point-blank range. The
officer faces from 5 years to 40 years in prison if the conviction
stands.
</P>
<P>
   Smith -- the first Connecticut police officer to be charged with
murder for an action committed in the line of duty -- said he shot
Franklyn Reid in December 1998 because he believed Reid was
reaching for a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the shooting, Reid, 27, was unarmed. A short
folding knife was discovered in the pocket of a jacket found a few
feet away from his body.
</P>
<P>
   Gill questioned jurors individually during a preliminary inquiry
Wednesday, examining issues raised by Smith's lawyer, John J.
Kelly. Gill also reviewed television news interviews during which
one of the jury members strongly defended the panel's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Based upon interviews with three of the 12 panelists, Kelly
claimed nine instances of juror misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Of those nine instances, Kelly said, three were considered,
including claims that one juror displayed a badge to the others,
stated he had law enforcement experience and told them that Smith's
actions were not consistent with police training.
</P>
<P>
   Also, one or more jurors allegedly brought notes into the jury
deliberation room and read from them while making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Should Gill decide to hold a second trial, 12 new jurors would
be seated.
</P>
<P>
   Waterbury State's Attorney John Connelly, who tried the case,
filed a 20-page motion saying that alleged juror misconduct is
nothing more than conjecture or speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't feel there is any basis for Kelly's claim,'' Connelly
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, Smith and his family declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Reid's mother, Pearlylyn Reid, said she has confidence in the
justice system. ''If Kelly wants to put it on a roller coaster and
roll it his way, it's not going to work,'' she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
