<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislative session ends after passage of $12.3 billion budget  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The 12-week Legislative session ended
early this morning, with Gov. John G. Rowland lauding a $12.3
billion state budget and the passage of government reform bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''For a sixth year in a row we have balanced the budget,'' Gov.
John G. Rowland told lawmaker just after midnight in his annual end
of session speech. ''And for the first time in my memory the budget
was approved by a unanimous vote in both chambers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature also passed bills to abolish the state's sheriff
system, revamp the treasurer's office and reform Connecticut's
campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland signed the sheriff and treasurer reform bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh yea, oh yea, oh yea. God save the sheriffs,'' Hartford
County Sheriff Walter Kupchunos said as he officially adjourned the
session, a duty given to him in the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said he will announce Friday whether he will sign or
veto the campaign finance measure.
</P>
<P>
   In the session's final hours, lawmakers approved a $270 million
bonding package that includes money for the University of
Connecticut and the state's public university system. It passed the
Senate unanimously vote, and the slid through the House 138-12.
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly also voted to raise salaries for their
offices in 2001 and boost the pay for constitutional officers in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   And Rowland said he would sign a bill passed Wednesday that
allows gays and other unmarried couples to adopt their partners'
children.
</P>
<P>
   The governor signed legislation earlier this week to use $455
million of state money to build Adriaen's Landing in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes a 700-room hotel, a convention center,
entertainment and retail space and nearly 400 housing units. Also
planned is a $90 million stadium in East Hartford for the
University of Connecticut. The development is expected to create
about 3,400 construction jobs and more than 1,100 permanent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new state budget, motorists will get a 7-cent
reduction in the gas tax and shoppers will have more money in their
pockets after buying clothes.
</P>
<P>
   But parents who send their children to private elementary and
secondary schools will not be getting the tuition tax credit that
Rowland was pushing for. Leading Democratic lawmakers blocked the
$500 credits from the budget, and Republicans never tacked the
measure on a separate bill.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also includes $75 million in tax breaks to the
state's hospitals and $54 million in tax cuts for industry, of
which $15 million goes to Bristol-based ESPN. The sports
broadcasting giant is planning a $500 million expansion of its
world headquarters that could mean up to 1,000 new jobs in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Warburg Dillon Read, the former Swiss Bank based in Stamford, is
getting $157 million in loans and tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the major tax breaks, the Legislature showed it's
sweet side to candy lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday night, the Senate slipped in a $200,000 tax
exemption for items sold through vending machines for 50 cents or
less, such as gum balls.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you have to swallow hard and accept something you
really don't like,'' Rep. Anne McDonald, D-Stamford said. ''We
cannot at this time send this whole package back to the senate over
gum ball machines.''
</P>
<P>
   The $12.3 billion budget is about $150 million more than what
the Legislature agreed to spend last year for the 2001 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly $40 million of the increase is going to new programs; the
rest is needed to make inflation adjustments and cover agencies and
programs running in the red.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Pro Tempore Kevin Sullivan, D-West Hartford,
commended the Legislature for its bipartisan cooperation in passing
the budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have been able to put their politics aside and make
good policy for the state of Connecticut,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   About $3 million in the budget is slated for beefing up the
state's three juvenile detention facilities in Bridgeport, Hartford
and New Haven. Another $4.4 million is earmarked to ease prison
overcrowding by creating more treatment programs.
</P>
<P>
   About $1.5 million is being used to expand eligibility
requirement for the state's ConnPACE prescription drug program.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the budget expenditures, lawmakers doled out $250 of
the state's surplus money.
</P>
<P>
   About $20 million of that is earmarked for a bailout of
deficit-plagued University of Connecticut Health Center.
</P>
<P>
   Municipalities will be getting $34 million of the surplus to use
however they want.
</P>
<P>
   The surplus also will sink $43 million into school construction
and $10 million into getting classrooms wired for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also has a Democratic-backed measure that pushes the
clothing tax exemption from $50 to $75. In return, the GOP won a
one week-long sales tax exemption on clothing priced up to $300.
</P>
<P>
   The gas tax cut is expected to save $85 to $140 a year for a
family that drives 30,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The $12.3 billion budget stays about $51 million under the
state's mandatory spending cap. But expenditure of the surplus
breaks the spending cap by about $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have protected the future by restraining government
spending,'' Rowland said. ''We have given Connecticut families the
opportunity to save and invest more of their own money through
additional tax relief. We have in vested in education, health and
the environment. And we have used government incentives to business
to encourage economic development.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers did not finish their work. They must return for a
special session to approve technical bills that implement the
budget. A date was not immediately set for the special session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 0154 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rowland signs treasurer reform bill  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Gov. John G. Rowland has signed into law
legislation intended to safeguard the state treasurer's office
against the types of crimes committed by former Treasurer Paul
Silvester.
</P>
<P>
   The bill had passed easily though the General Assembly and was
signed by the governor on Wednesday. Rowland had threatened to veto
a weaker version. He said the early bill didn't impose enough
oversight or crack down on ''finder's fees'' paid by companies to
people who set up investment deals with the state.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, the state Ethics Commission would have input
in deciding who can collect finder's fees.
</P>
<P>
   The law also creates the position of an investment specialist in
the treasurer's office and beefs up the Investment Advisory
Council's oversight.
</P>
<P>
   The law prohibits the payment of finder's fees to anybody except
qualified financial counselors, who must be designated by the
treasurer in consultation with ethics officials. It penalizes
anyone who violates the finder's fee provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The reform measure came out of last year's scandal surrounding
Silvester, a Rowland appointee who pleaded guilty in September to
charges of racketeering and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted accepting kickbacks from finders fees paid by
companies with which he invested state pension money. Some of the
money went to his failed 1998 election campaign. He is to be
sentenced June 19.
</P>
<P>
   State Treasurer Denise Nappier had pushed for the law, which
also replaces the deputy treasurer with a chief investment officer
and prohibits the treasurer, any candidate for treasurer or any
member of the Investment Advisory Council from seeking campaign
contributions from people connected to an investment company.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, who has denied any knowledge of Silvester's
fund-raising illegalities, appointed Silvester after former
treasurer Christopher Burnham resigned to take a job with an
investment company that had done business with the state.
</P>
<P>
   The law requires the treasurer to wait at least one year from
the date a contract is negotiated before going to work for a
company, if the contract amounts to $50,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   It also restricts the governor's power to appoint someone to
fill a vacancy in the treasurer's office. An appointee would be
subject to confirmation if the General Assembly is in session at
the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 0154 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firing of administrator in strip search incident upheld  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state Supreme Court has upheld the
firing of a New Haven school administrator who lost her job after a
1997 strip search of students at Jackie Robinson Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Rogers, an assistant principal at the school, was accused
of authorizing the search of 22 fifth-graders after a student
reported $40 missing. No money was found.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was fired by the New Haven Board of Education after the
March 1997 search for ''inefficiency and incompetence.'' She had
denied authorizing the search or knowing the girls had been asked
to strip.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision released Wednesday, the high court concluded that
the school board had a right to fire Rogers, even though she had
had an unblemished record since joining the school system as a
teacher in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although we recognize that this one incident exists against
the backdrop of an excellent record, we cannot ignore the fact that
the plaintiff's actions compromised the privacy of the students who
it was her duty to protect,'' Justice Robert Callahan wrote for the
court.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers had claimed the Board of Education was negligent and
abused its power when it ignored an arbitration panel's non-binding
ruling that cleared her of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The report from the arbitration panel said Rogers did not order
or condone a strip search although she used ''poor judgment'' and
should have done more to make sure the search was legal.
</P>
<P>
   The court concluded that the school board had cause to fire
Rogers, citing her failure to stop the search when she became aware
it was happening inside a gym teacher's office as she was searching
for the missing cash in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The court cited the district administrative procedure manual's
search and seizure section, which states that ''at no time should
school officials conduct a search which requires a student to
remove more clothing than his/her shoes or jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   A security aide accused of conducting the search and a gym
teacher, Marie Young, also were fired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
