<DOCNO> APW20000504.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khannouchi To Skip Marathon Trials  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL, AP Track Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- His Olympic marathon ambitions squelched by
injuries, a saddened Khalid Khannouchi now will direct his
attention to making the U.S. team at 10,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Moroccan-born world record-holder in the marathon
and the new U.S. citizen will feel shortchanged. The marathon is
his event, and little else seems to matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not going to be enthusiastic about the 10,000, because he
wants the marathon,'' his wife, Sandra, said Wednesday at a news
conference, where Khannouchi withdrew from Sunday's U.S. Olympic
marathon trials in Pittsburgh because of ligament damage in his
left ankle and a strained right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would not be enough for me,'' he said. ''If healthy, I
think I would have a chance to win a medal in the marathon. It will
be very difficult in the 10,000. I don't have much time to train
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The injuries will keep Khannouchi from training seriously for
the 10,000 until at least June 1, his physiotherapist, Gerard
Hartmann, said. The track trials are in mid-July at Sacramento,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent from getting completely rusty, Khannouchi is
cross-training -- swimming and biking.
</P>
<P>
   ''He will be at the starting line if he can perform,'' his wife
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The biggest adjustment for Khalid will be going from road
racing shoes to spikes. Adjusting to spikes is a very slow
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi has not run a race on the track since 1995, when he
won the African 5,000-meter championship.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he's at the trials, he will be confident,'' Sandra said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra, who is also Khannouchi's coach, has been trying to
instill confidence in her husband in the 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've told him (Haile) Gebrselassie (of Ethiopia) is no better
than you,'' she said. ''I know you can run 27 (minutes).''
</P>
<P>
   Gebrselassie owns the world record of 26 minutes, 22.75 seconds,
set two years ago at Hengelo, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic 10,000 at Sydney is not expected to be nearly that
fast, since there will be no pacesetter, and with a major
international championship at stake, the racing usually is a lot
more tactical.
</P>
<P>
   ''He would be very disappointed if he went to the Olympic Games
in the 10,000 and didn't win a medal,'' said Harry Gee,
Khannouchi's Houston-based lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi also was very disappointed Wednesday when he sadly
withdrew from the marathon trials. He had fought for three years to
become a U.S. citizen so he would be eligible to run, and just
obtained his citizenship Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel frustrated and very disappointed,'' he said at a news
conference. ''I feel sorry for the people who have been working so
hard for my dream to come true.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a shame. I feel very bad. My heart wants to run, but what
can I say?''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Khannouchi, appearing drained from the stress of
the past two days, stopped to fight back tears.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's nervous, he's nervous,'' his wife, Sandra, said.
</P>
<P>
   When Khannouchi regained his composure, he said, ''I hope I have
another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He might get that opportunity in the 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my heart, I want to give something back,'' he said. ''The
people of the United States deserve a medal. I want to bring a
medal back to the States. But if I don't, it's not going to be the
end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartmann said Khannouchi would have to continue ''extensive
physical therapy'' in Limerick, Ireland, the trainer's home base,
in order to be ready for the track trials.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi injured the ankle March 1 during training after
having won a 10-kilometer race in Puerto Rico. Despite the badly
twisted ankle, he resumed training two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   While trying to compensate for the ailing ankle, he injured the
hamstring. Still hurting, he honored his contract to run the London
Marathon on April 16. Injuries had forced him out of last year's
race and he didn't want to withdraw again. Another mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Although he finished a respectable third in 2:08:36, the time
was nearly three minutes slower than his world record of 2:05:42 in
last year's Chicago Marathon. Worse, he aggravated the injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to make excuses, but if you're not 100 percent
physically, you're going to have problems,'' Khannouchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi said that if he had known he would get his U.S.
citizenship so soon, he would have backed out of London.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't take that risk,'' he said, ''and I didn't want to
break the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife said Khannouchi and Hartmann discussed his possible
participation in the marathon trials as late as Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told Khalid the decision is up to you,'' Sandra said.
''It's your body. But I advise you not to do it. You will be
ruining your running career.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandra agreed with Hartmann.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said, 'Listen to him,''' she told her husband. ''You don't
want to go to the Olympic trials or the Olympic Games just to be
there. You want to bring something (a medal) home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 0230 </TRAILER>
