<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Arrested in Japan Hijacking  </HEADLINE>
By JOJI SAKURAI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIGASHI HIROSHIMA, Japan (AP) -- A knife-wielding teen-ager
hijacked a passenger bus in Japan, killing a woman and holding the
blade to the neck of a 6-year-old girl before police stormed the
vehicle Thursday and ended the 15-hour standoff.
</P>
<P>
   After a 190-mile chase and hours of negotiations at a highway
rest stop, police charged into the bus before dawn, entering
through a window and an emergency exit, and subdued the youth. None
of the remaining passengers was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The hijacking, which began about noon Wednesday on Sanyo
Expressway in Fukuoka prefecture, 560 miles southwest of Tokyo,
riveted Japan. Television stations interrupted regular programming
to bring overhead shots of the white bus moving slowly down the
highway, windows drawn, chased by several police cars.
</P>
<P>
   As shocking as the hijacking was for this low-crime nation, what
troubled many even more was the age of the suspect -- 17, police
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wonder why juveniles keep committing crimes. I'm shocked.
It's becoming more and more like America,'' said Yoshio Zuigyo, 50,
who happened to drive by the highway rest area where the bus
eventually stopped, trailed by police cars and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Before hijacking the bus, the suspect had been hospitalized at
the National Sanitorium in Saga prefecture, on the southernmost
main island of Kyushu where the hijacking began, a hospital
official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. He declined to
specify his illness.
</P>
<P>
   The teen had been allowed to leave the mental institution to
visit his home this week, national broadcaster NHK said. The
hospital spokesman and officials at three prefectural police
departments refused to confirm the report.
</P>
<P>
   The hijacking began when the teen-age suspect went to the front
of the bus, slashed several passengers with the knife and sat
behind the driver, according to passengers.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 people were aboard the passenger bus, but nearly half
had either been released or had escaped before the hijacking ended.
</P>
<P>
   Three women were freed after each was stabbed in the neck with
the hijacker's 16-inch knife. Police said one of them, 68-year-old
Tatsuko Tsukamoto, died. Four male passengers were also released.
</P>
<P>
   Three other hostages escaped by leaping out windows of the bus,
two of them as the vehicle was moving, injuring one of them.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the standoff, the suspect's mother arrived
at the scene, but he refused to speak with her. The hijacker's name
was withheld because of his age.
</P>
<P>
   Police said he demanded a gun, but officials refused to give him
one. NHK TV reported that he also demanded cash and wanted to be
driven to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper photo shot through the front window of the bus
showed a pudgy, bespectacled youngster with a pageboy hairstyle,
sitting next to a girl behind the driver.
</P>
<P>
   Mikiko Matsuno, a 30-year-old nurse who jumped from the bus,
told police the hijacker paced back and forth ''with a bloody knife
dangling from his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When my eyes accidentally met his, he asked my name and told
me, 'I'll kill you,''' police quoted her as saying in the hospital,
where she was being treated for bruises and a broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   After an hours-long chase, the bus was stopped by two large
police vehicles and forced into the rest area, where police later
captured the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken to a nearby police station and charged with taking
hostages and carrying an illegal weapon, police said. He was not
immediately charged with murder, for which the maximum penalty is
execution.
</P>
<P>
   Police spokesman Joji Fujiha said the suspect admitted to the
hijacking but would not disclose a motive.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the 6-year-old girl who had been traveling alone
to visit her grandparents was receiving psychological counseling.
</P>
<P>
   The hijacking was the latest in a series of high-profile
juvenile crimes in Japan. Although still low compared to the United
States, the juvenile crime rate has climbed recently, with murders
by youngsters up by 56 percent in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is what happens when kids grow up in solitude in a
virtual world,'' said Takashi Ota, an honorary professor at Tokyo
University. ''With just man-made things to play with, kids have
lost the natural feeling of sharing experiences with friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The hijacking was on the front-page in all major newspapers
Thursday. ''The Drive of Death,'' said a headline in the Mainichi
national newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should all try to relate to our children better,'' said an
editorial in the Yomiuri newspaper. ''Their utter lack of
conscience or discipline is unsettling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
