<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Washington's Forgotten River  </HEADLINE>
By DERRILL HOLLY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation has spent more than $1 billion to
clean up the Potomac, that broad, noble river that flows by the
nation's granite and marble monuments. Now Washington's other
river, the neglected, polluted Anacostia, is coming in for its
share of attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Anacostia was on a poor, black side of town and nobody
really cared,'' said James Dougherty, spokesman for the Sierra
Club. Chain link fences and corrugated metal barriers separate the
neighborhood from the river.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and local governments have designated $130 million to
rejuvenate the river and its environs.
</P>
<P>
   Vacant housing projects near the river banks are being
demolished. Trails will be developed. Pollution abatement projects
are under way. Government offices employing some 5,000 people are
moving to the Navy Yard, on the Anacostia, from suburban Virginia.
The federal government and private developers have committed $47
million for a federal center. New housing will be built for Marines
assigned to the nearby Marines Barracks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any great city should value its waterfronts as precious
assets,'' Mayor Anthony A. Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre L'Enfant had the same idea when he laid out Washington in
the 1790s, nestling the capital between the Potomac and the river
then called ''the Eastern Branch,'' now called the Anacostia, an
Indian name.
</P>
<P>
   L'Enfant and George Washington placed the Navy Yard on the
Anacostia, expecting it would become the home port of the U.S.
military fleet. Today, one of Washington's most attractive natural
sites, the National Arboretum, sits on a rise overlooking the
river.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a century, federal agencies used the 8.4 mile-long
waterway as a dumping ground and sewage system for Washington. A
riverfront portion of the arboretum served as a manure pit for the
National Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints from environmentalists prompted officials to
redevelop the manure site as a waterfront garden of flowering
shrubs beneath a red pagoda perched on a hillside.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fish, birds and wildlife were less common than the tires and
oil drums 40 years ago,'' recalled Diane Dale, president of the
Anacostia Garden Club.
</P>
<P>
   The river played a role in the city's racist past, too. As late
as the 1960s, blacks were made to feel unwelcome along much of the
river bank and could not use the publicly financed swimming pool or
golf course in Anacostia Park.
</P>
<P>
   The area became the site of public housing, landfills and a huge
incinerator.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, starting in the Johnson administration, the Potomac
was cleaned up at a cost of $1 billion. Now the Bass Anglers
Sportsman Society rates the Potomac as one of the nation's 10 top
bass waterways.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the Anacostia remained despoiled. Heavy rains
would periodically overburden the city's sewage treatment plant,
allowing a billion gallons of raw sewage to flow into the Anacostia
each year.
</P>
<P>
   ''It takes about half an inch of rain to cause the problem,''
said Robert Boone, president of the Anacostia Watershed Society.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, the group has planted nearly 9,400 trees and removed
269 tons of debris from the river and its banks.
</P>
<P>
   Anacostia pollutants endanger one of the nation's major
fisheries, the Chesapeake Bay, about 100 miles downstream from
where the Anacostia and Potomac merge inside Washington's borders.
The Anacostia flows through suburban Prince Georges and Montgomery
counties in Maryland before reaching the Potomac.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pollution, anglers can be seen daily in Anacostia
Park and near the three bridges that cross it fishing for bluegill,
white perch, catfish and shad. For many, it is a way to combat high
food prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have hiked, canoed, paddled, swam, fished and played in this
river since I was a little boy,'' said Carl Cole, 56, an
environmentalist who helped block development of two islands in the
river as an amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   And improvements in water quality have brought wildlife back to
the wooded areas lining 25 percent of the river's banks.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can see beaver, otter, deer and hundreds of blue heron on
the river,'' said Robert Nixon, director of the Earth Conservation
Corps which has released more than a dozen bald eagles into the
watershed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
