<DOCNO> APW20000504.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Diagnoses Artist's Ills  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Great artists get sick like anyone else and a
professor at Georgetown University believes he can tell from their
paintings what ailed people like Rembrandt and Michelangelo.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Carlos H. Espinel says Rembrandt suffered from temporal
arteritis, an inflammation of an artery on his temple. He cites a
self-portrait painted nearly 350 years ago now in Washington's
National Gallery of Art.
</P>
<P>
   He says Michelangelo had gout.
</P>
<P>
   Espinel directs the Blood Pressure Center in suburban Arlington,
Va. His articles on what he calls ''ArtMedicine'' appear in the
British medical weekly, The Lancet, and he teaches a course in the
subject and another in blood pressure at Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   Espinel has advised the president of Colombia on health policy
and devised a simple test for kidney failure. He studied the role
of salt in blood pressure that was instrumental in getting Congress
to pass the law on nutrition labels for processed food.
</P>
<P>
   He developed his interest in art almost by accident.
</P>
<P>
   ''I strolled into the National Gallery one day,'' he said, ''and
there I was facing all those great minds -- some of the greatest
minds ever. It was like a new world.''
</P>
<P>
   Espinel soon found himself doing medical research on the
gallery's self-portrait by Rembrandt.
</P>
<P>
   ''One has to scrutinize each brush stroke,'' he wrote in The
Lancet. ''Notice that in ... other portraits Rembrandt places the
light on the right. But in the Washington portrait he puts it
directly on his forehead, on his left temporal artery, as if to
say: 'Look at me. Look what is happening to me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Francis Robicsek, medical director of the Carolinas Heart
Institute in Charlotte, N.C., said he did not know Espinel's work
but urged caution in identifying disease from paintings. He noted
that considerable work has been done on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some who think the Mona Lisa's smile is evidence of
a partial paralysis of a branch of the face muscle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Espinel's diagnosis of Michelangelo comes from a painting by the
artist's contemporary, Raffaello Sanzio, known as Raphael. Espinel
identifies as Michelangelo a prominent but unlabeled figure in a
large Raphael called ''The School of Athens.'' He is especially
interested in the figure's exposed right knee and its conspicuous
bumps, called tophi: deposits of uric acid salts.
</P>
<P>
   Letters and poems by Michelangelo say he suffered from kidney
stones.
</P>
<P>
   ''In practice,'' Espinel wrote for The Lancet, ''in an adult man
with both kidney stones and tophi, the diagnostic possibilities are
reduced to gout.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelangelo, obsessed with his work, would go for days on a
diet of bread and wine. Espinel points out that Italians used to
process wine in lead containers, and that the artist may have been
exposed to lead-based paints -- both possible causes of gout.
</P>
<P>
   Espinel has also found medical interest in a more recent
painter, Dutch-born Willem De Kooning, leader in the American
movement called abstract expressionism. Espinel wrote that the year
before he died in 1997 with a long history of Alzheimer's disease,
De Kooning had made a partial recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ''And even if at times he confused his wife with his sister,''
the Lancet article said, ''his brush strokes are not the weaving,
thinning squiggles that betray a weakening mind.''
</P>
<P>
   ''De Kooning's recovery suggests art as an aid for the
understanding of dementia, and art as a discipline for the study of
the mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 0252 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 02:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> James Brown Mementos Lost in Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Authorities confirmed Wednesday that a fire
at the office of singer James Brown was deliberately set.
</P>
<P>
   Fire investigator Lt. G.B. Hannan said he identified four
ignition points inside James Brown Enterprises inside the building
where concerts, tours and radio programming for radio station
WAAW-FM were coordinated. Hannan said he found spots on the floor
where a liquid fire accelerant had been poured before last Friday's
blaze.
</P>
<P>
   Other evidence included an unlocked front door. Brown's attorney
said a burglar alarm apparently did not go off.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is offering a $20,000 reward for information leading to
the arrest and conviction of the arsonist, said the lawyer, Buddy
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The singer turned 67 on Wednesday, and those close to him said
he was depressed by the loss of unpublished music and more than 40
years of personal mementos that were in the building.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown also kept valuables in his home in Beech Island,
S.C., a slew of trinkets, awards and irreplaceable photographs were
stored at his office, Dallas said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the memorabilia were the preacher's robe Brown wore in
''The Blues Brothers'' movie and a pair of boxing gloves from the
set of ''Rocky IV,'' in which he performed the song ''Living In
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Master tapes of unreleased material -- including a live concert
at the Apollo Theatre in Harlem and studio tapes -- were destroyed,
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 0253 </TRAILER>
