<DOCNO> APW20000504.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rule To Remove Anti-Abortion Signs  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- When nearly two dozen anti-abortion
demonstrators were arrested outside the Supreme Court building last
week, the ink was barely dry on the federal order they violated.
The court's marshal had issued the edict earlier that day.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court does not make the law, the saying goes. But it
can -- and does -- promulgate orders that have the same effect.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely censorship,'' said Troy Newman of Operation
Rescue West in Los Angeles, one of those arrested. ''We offended
someone on the court and the decision was made to yank our signs
off the public sidewalk, where the Supreme Court has said free
speech is supposed to flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   Court officials declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Three days before the justices heard arguments over Nebraska's
ban on a surgical procedure opponents call ''partial birth
abortion,'' anti-abortion activists showed up with huge, grisly
banners, including a full-color depiction of a decapitated fetus.
</P>
<P>
   They were allowed to stake out a portion of the public sidewalk
in front of the Supreme Court building. But shortly after the April
25 argument ended inside, court police informed the demonstrators
outside they were violating something called ''Regulation Six.''
</P>
<P>
   It says signs that are not hand-carried are barred from
''perimeter sidewalks of the Supreme Court grounds'' if larger than
4 feet long and 4 feet wide and are elevated higher than 6 feet
from the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The order was issued under the authority of a federal law that
lets the court protect its building and grounds and the people who
use them. It was signed into being by Supreme Court Marshal Dale
Bosley on April 25, only hours before its enforcement. It was
effective immediately, in contrast to executive branch rules and
regulations. In the latter case, agencies have to first propose a
rule or regulation and then allow for a period of public comment
before implementing them.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators, told about the new order, were arrested when
they refused to remove the offending signs. They spent 12 hours in
jail before pleading innocent to a misdemeanor that carries a
maximum penalty of six months in jail and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ''No hearings. No public comments. Does the court have absolute
power to regulate? This is something you'd expect from Fidel
Castro's regime or in Tiananmen Square -- the government coming in
and telling people they are violating some rule they just made
up,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law says the rectangular-shaped Supreme Court grounds
include the public sidewalks that surround them, to the four
streets beyond.
</P>
<P>
   But in a 1983 decision, the court itself struck down a federal
law that treated demonstrations on those public sidewalks the same
as demonstrations elsewhere on the court's property.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sidewalks comprising the outer boundaries of the court
grounds are indistinguishable from any other sidewalks in
Washington, D.C., and we can discern no reason why they should be
treated any differently,'' the unanimous court said back then.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sidewalks ... traditionally have been held open to the public
for expressive activities and are clearly within those areas of
public property that may be considered ... public forum property,''
the court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said his organization had not yet decided whether to
challenge Regulation Six as unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The justices this week hosted the eighth rendition of Music at
the Supreme Court for about 200 guests, a concert that featured New
York Philharmonic harpist Nancy Allen, an accomplished string
quartet and the collaborations of husband-wife team William Bolcom
and Joan Morris.
</P>
<P>
   A highlight of the afternoon concert, held in one of the court
building's ceremonial conference rooms, was a Bolcom and Morris
interpretation of a clever, turn-of-the-century ditty titled ''Some
Little Bug is Going to Find You Some Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sung by Morris with piano accompaniment by Bolcolm, the song
drew lots of chuckles -- especially from Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist and Justice Antonin Scalia, the court's two most avid
sing-along fans.
</P>
<P>
   The two violins, viola and violincello used by the Axlerod
Quartet all are 300-year-old creations of Antonio Stradivari, whose
musical instruments carried his Latin name ''Stradivarius.'' They
came to the court accompanied by two bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   After the concert, Rehnquist told guests they could come forward
and view the master's craftsmanship up close. ''You can take a look
but no touching,'' he warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 0257 </TRAILER>
