<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Risks in Helping Ex-Soviets  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Spending $240 million to steer Russian
biological weapons experts into peacetime research may bolster the
work of still-secretive former Soviet military institutes,
according to a congressional report.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said any risk is far outweighed by
the program's benefits, with U.S.-supported scientists of at least
15 Russian institutes rejecting approaches from other nations to
conduct ''questionable research.''
</P>
<P>
   The report issued Wednesday by the General Accounting Office
provides no evidence that Moscow is working on germ weapons, but
says it is dangerous to improve the skills of scientists who have
worked on such deadly pathogens as anthrax, plague and smallpox.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, the United States has provided $20 million to fund
alternative pursuits by Soviet-era scientists who worked in
biological weaponry programs.
</P>
<P>
   The administration proposes to spend $220 million over the next
four years expanding the effort to redirect the work of former
Soviet biological weapons institutes, some of which are still
off-limits to foreigners, according to a General Accounting Office
report released Wednesday by the House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''We found that expanding the program will pose certain risks to
the United States,'' by sustaining Russia's existing biological
weapons facilities and advancing Russian war scientists' skills for
conducting offensive research, said the report by the GAO,
Congress' investigative arm.
</P>
<P>
   The report said nothing prevents scientists assisted by the U.S.
program designed to lower the risk of weapons proliferation from
engaging in offensive activities at Russian military facilities or
from selling their skills to rogue states or terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The administration, in responding to the report, said there is
no evidence that Moscow is developing germ warfare weapons and
danger of U.S.-assisted Russian scientists helping terrorists or
rogue nations is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   It acknowledged some risks but said they have been reduced to an
acceptable level and ''the benefits far outweigh the remaining
risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest anthrax production facility is being
dismantled and Russians are conducting new research that may help
combat some of the world's deadliest diseases, said the State,
Energy and Defense departments in a joint statement accompanying
the report.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, ''Congress must carefully evaluate the risks and
benefits of this program to ensure that it does not have unintended
consequences that could jeopardize the national security,'' said
Rep. Floyd Spence, Armed Services Committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that some officials who ran Moscow's
clandestine biological weapons programs during the Cold War remain
in place.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although Russia has generally allowed the United States access
to its nonmilitary institutes that receive U.S. nonproliferation
assistance, Russia has consistently rebuffed U.S. efforts to
inspect its military institutes currently managed by the Ministry
of Defense,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO's conclusions were based on unclassified documents and
on interviews with officials running the U.S. program, with experts
from nongovernmental organizations and with former and current
Russian scientists. Investigators also visited six former Soviet
nonmilitary biological weapons facilities currently receiving U.S.
assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 0407 </TRAILER>
