<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 08:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Rabbi says confessions of private eye are false  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A prominent southern New Jersey rabbi
accused of hiring a hitman to kill his wife says recent confessions
by another defendant in the case were ''baseless,'' according to a
published report.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Fred Neulander, who has been charged with accomplice
murder and conspiracy to commit murder in the death of his wife,
told The Philadelphia Inquirer he knew a private investigator who
confessed in the case only as a member of his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Len Jenoff, the investigator, last week said Neulander offered
him $30,000 to hire someone to kill his wife of 29 years, according
to an account in The Inquirer for Tuesday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   But Neulander told The Inquirer for Thursday's editions his
relationship with Jenoff was limited to a professional capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a professional relationship as a rabbi and
congregant,'' Neulander told The Inquirer in a 90-minute interview
conducted Tuesday with the rabbi's lawyers present.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, 58, also said, ''I was stunned'' by Jenoff's
statement to authorities. ''It's been very difficult and
isolating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander's wife, Carol, was beaten to death in the family's
Cherry Hill home. Authorities say she was killed by a hit man
posing as a deliveryman.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander was charged four years after the killing. But his
trial, scheduled to begin in June, was postponed indefinitely after
Jenoff confessed in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, 54, and Paul Michael Daniels, 26, were arrested Monday
in the Nov. 1, 1994, beating death.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, who had been counseled by Neulander for his own marital
problems, said the rabbi offered him the money to kill a person he
claimed was an enemy of Israel, the newspaper reported Tuesday.
Jenoff said the rabbi told him he could get him a job with Israel's
secret service if he pulled off the murder, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander said he didn't know why Jenoff had confessed to the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know why he put himself into this position,''
Neulander said. ''You have to ask him. I think Mr. Jenoff's
(allegations) are baseless.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff's lawyer, Francis Hartman, has said his client was
haunted by what had happened and felt compelled to confess.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was something that was eating at him. The trial is coming
up and the thought occurred to him that the rabbi might be
acquitted and that might be a terrible thing,'' Hartman said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander's lawyers, Jeffrey Zucker and Dennis P. Wixted, said
they will try to show Jenoff and Carol Neulander knew each other.
That way, it will make implausible Jenoff's story that he thought
he had been hired to kill a terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's impossible to believe that he did not know her,'' Zucker
told The Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, a former roommate to Jenoff, also has confessed,
prosecutors have said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff and Daniels were being held in Camden County Jail, Jenoff
on $200,000 bail and Daniels on $400,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
