<HEADLINE> Reaction to the death of Cardinal John O'Connor  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Reaction to the death of Cardinal John O'Connor:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''With a deep sense of personal loss I have received the news of
the death of Cardinal John J. O'Connor, and I offer my prayerful
condolences to you, the auxiliary bishops and the priests,
religious and laity of the archdiocese of New York. ... I join you
in commending this faithful servant of the church to our heavenly
Father's eternal love. Throughout the years he has been of great
support to me in the service of the universal church, he worked
tirelessly to build better ecumenical and interreligious relations,
and for Catholics and other Christians and men and women of good
will throughout the world he was a source of inspiration in serving
God in our less fortunate brothers and sisters.'' -- Pope John Paul
II, in a telegram of condolence sent to the archdiocese's auxiliary
bishop, the Rev. Robert A. Brucato.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Holy Father is deeply saddened by the news of Cardinal
O'Connor's death. Cardinal O'Connor was an extraordinary figure in
the Catholic church in the United States. He was a truly faithful
shepherd and an outstanding witness to faith and human dignity. He
performed his priestly duties in the most passionate manner, always
helping those in need. His presence will surely be missed.'' --
Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls.
</P>
<P>
   ''A legend has been called home to God. As a leader and teacher,
Cardinal O'Connor was absolute in his love for the church and
indefatigable in his defense for the vulnerable among us. He did it
all with great compassion and common sense ... and with that
wonderful glint in his eye.'' -- Cardinal Adam Maida of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Church has lost a great warrior and the country has lost a
great patriot, who will long be remembered. ... He was a bold and
courageous man, who stood firmly for what he believed. He was loyal
and faithful to his friends and to his Church.'' -- The Rev. Billy
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ''The Church has lost one of its great leaders and the United
States has lost one of its most patriotic sons. But God has his
friend back with him. Cardinal O'Connor was a very religious,
patriotic American who served his country with pride and his God
with great care, great concern.'' -- Raymond Flynn, former mayor of
Boston and one-time U.S. ambassador to the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   ''For more than 50 years, he has reached out with uncommon
fortitude to minister to the needs of America's Catholics. The
courage and firm faith he showed in his final illness inspired us
all.'' -- President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have lost an eloquent voice for human rights and human
dignity and a champion for the least among us.'' -- Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''John Cardinal O'Connor's courage, selflessness and devotion to
duty are inspirations to his fellow New Yorkers and fellow
Catholics, but not only to them. He is admired throughout the
country, and by people of all faiths. New Yorkers are profoundly
grateful for his years of service to our city.'' -- New York City
Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''I long admired Cardinal O'Connor for his commitment to social
justice. ... Throughout his entire life, Cardinal O'Connor worked
as a passionate advocate for the poor and the less fortunate.'' --
First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''He and I didn't agree on all things, for instance we didn't
agree on abortion and the gay community ... but it did not stop
him. He didn't hesitate a moment when called upon for assistance.''
-- Former New York City Mayor David Dinkins.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York City lost one of its greatest sons in the cardinal.
... People many times thought he was tough. He was tough, but he
was also the most compassionate. ... He said the Catholic faith is
not a salad bar, but at the same time he understood that people
were weak and most of us are sinners.'' -- Former Mayor Edward I.
Koch.
</P>
<P>
   ''A priest to the very core of his person, Cardinal O'Connor
lived out his priesthood with an energy, a spiritual dynamism and
commitment which inspired us all.'' -- Cardinal Roger Mahony of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether it was a late night visit to dying patients in AIDS
hospital wards or his determination to keep Catholic parochial
schools open and available to every child seeking a good education,
he was a man who sought to serve others at every opportunity.'' --
Cardinal Francis George of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was faithful to his priestly calling, and courageous in
facing his death. He will be remembered both among Catholics and
the broader community with reverence and respect.'' -- Archbishop
William J. Levada of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an incalculable loss for all New Yorkers. ... The
cardinal was incredibly sensitive to the issues vital to the Jewish
community and in some respects served as spokesman at the Vatican
for Jews around the world. He worked tirelessly for peace in
Northern Ireland and for peace with justice in the world. He was
compassionate for those less fortunate, the poor, the elderly, the
sick. He was accessible, wise and always caring. He will be
remembered as one of our greatest New Yorkers.'' -- New York City
Comptroller Alan G. Hevesi.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was always stalwart in his support for the Jewish community
and remained a tireless advocate for improving and expanding the
Catholic-Jewish relationship. ... He was a man of God in every
sense and a true friend whose visionary wisdom, advice and
leadership will be sorely missed.'' Abraham H. Foxman, national
director of the Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   ''New York will always remember him as a great man who helped so
many people in so many ways.'' Manhattan Borough President C.
Virginia Fields.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember when he was named to New York, the reporters came
in from New York and they wanted to know what he was like, because
they didn't know who he was. I remember telling them, 'He eats very
little and he sleeps very little and he works very hard. So, look
out, New York.''' -- Bishop James C. Timlin of Scranton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
