<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 21; Dow Down a Fraction  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed at the start of
trading today after a report of slowing productivity growth
intensified worries that higher interest rates are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 0.62 at 10,479.51.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 21.46 to 3,728.77, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 2.49 to 1,417.59.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks stalled after the Labor Department reported that
Americans' productivity, a key measure of future prosperity, rose
at an annual rate of 2.4 percent the first three months of this
year. That marked a sharp slowdown from the previous quarter, when
productivity rose at an extremely sharp 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Economists had expected productivity growth to come in at 3.5
percent. The lower-than-expected number exacerbated fears that the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates by as much as a
half-percentage point at its May 16 meeting as it works to keep
inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan was speaking at a
banking conference in Chicago, keeping Wall Street traders on edge
as they sought signs of the Fed's likely action on May 16. Instead,
Greenspan's speech was focused primarily on risk management for
banks.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are highly sensitive to interest-rate
fluctuations, recovered some ground today after tumbling broadly on
Wednesday. American Express rose 1 5/16 to 143 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 114.48 million
shares, behind Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 3.22 to 498.78.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's stock market was closed for a national
holiday. In afternoon trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was up 0.1
percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.1 percent, and France's
CAC-40 was up 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
