<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 44; Nasdaq Up 14  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were narrowly mixed today after a report
of slowing productivity growth intensified worries that higher
interest rates are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   In late morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 44.37 at 10,435.76.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Nasdaq composite index
was up 14.86 to 3,722.17, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 3.43 to 1,411.67.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks stalled after the Labor Department reported that
Americans' productivity, a key measure of future prosperity, rose
at an annual rate of 2.4 percent the first three months of this
year. That marked a sharp slowdown from the previous quarter, when
productivity rose at an extremely sharp 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Economists had expected productivity growth to come in at 3.5
percent. The lower-than-expected number exacerbated fears that the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates by as much as a
half-percentage point at its May 16 meeting as it works to keep
inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan spoke at a banking
conference in Chicago, keeping Wall Street traders on edge as they
sought signs of the Fed's likely action on May 16. Instead,
Greenspan's speech was focused primarily on risk management for
banks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a hesitant market right now,'' said Larry Wachtel, market
analyst at Prudential Securities. ''The productivity number was a
little worse than expected, but the real problem is that there's
just no conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachtel said the Labor Department's April employment report, due
out Friday morning, should give the market direction. Any signs of
escalating wage pressures could spark selling, while a modest
report could enable stocks to close out the week with a rally,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are highly sensitive to interest-rate
fluctuations, recovered some ground today after tumbling broadly on
Wednesday. American Express rose 1 13/16 to 143 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Retail stocks were lower for a second straight session as many
of the nation's largest retailers reported that April sales didn't
meet expectations. Wal-Mart fell 2 5/16 to 51 1/8 and Gap fell 2
15/16 to 34 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said cooler-than-normal weather caused the
disappointing results in April -- not rising interest rates or stock
market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the retail sector stumbled after Goldman Sachs
removed many retail stocks from its recommended list.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 282.85 million
shares, behind Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.69 to 501.25.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
