<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal O'Connor, known for wit, staunch defense of Catholicfaith  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In his 16 years at the nation's most prominent
Catholic pulpit, Cardinal John O'Connor inspired a flock of
millions by preaching compassion, working to help the poor and
fighting a brave public battle against the brain tumor that
eventually would kill him.
</P>
<P>
   He also placed himself at the center of the nation's most
emotionally charged debates, angering many with his staunch support
of the Catholic church's positions on abortion and homosexuality.
But in a city known for its rough-and-tumble public life, O'Connor
managed to charm many of his enemies with his famous wit and
warmth.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor died Wednesday at 80, eight months after undergoing
surgery to remove a brain tumor in late August. He was ailing since
the operation, appearing weak and bloated but celebrating Mass at
St. Patrick's Cathedral as often as his health allowed. A public
viewing was scheduled for Friday, Saturday and Sunday and his
funeral was scheduled for 2 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners attending early morning Masses on Thursday reacted
to the news with saddness and tears.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget McDonnell struggled to compose herself as she remembered
the cardinal's kindness. ''I think he was a wonderful man,'' she
said, tears welling in her eyes. ''Once when I came to a function
here, he gave me his seat. I'll never forget that but it's all in
God's hands now.''
</P>
<P>
   John Pfeffer, of Paramus, N.J., said of all the cardinal's
qualities, the one he would miss most was ''his humility and
willingness to listen.'' But he added, ''I feel a certain sense of
relief to know that his suffering has passed.''
</P>
<P>
   A small pile of flowers and votive candles were left overnight
on Fifth Avenue, opposite the main entrance of the cathedral and a
constant stream of people entered the church throughout the
morning. The cathedral had a somber air as people sat quietly, some
ashen-faced, with heads bowed.
</P>
<P>
   ''His Eminence John Cardinal O'Connor has completed his earthly
journey and has gone home to God,'' said Joseph Zwilling, spokesman
for the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York. ''May the Lord
grant eternal peace to the soul of our loving and faithful
archbishop.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's condition deteriorated sharply early Wednesday, and
he died in his residence behind the cathedral at 8:05 p.m. with a
sister, other relatives and clergy members by his side, Zwilling
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was kept comfortable and did not experience any pain,''
Zwilling said at a news conference. ''The cardinal died very
peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Zwilling's announcement said the cardinal had suffered from
cancer; until then, church officials had only said he had a brain
tumor.
</P>
<P>
   ''With a deep sense of personal loss I have received the news of
the death of Cardinal John J. O'Connor, and I offer my prayerful
condolences to you, the auxiliary bishops and the priests,
religious and laity of the archdiocese of New York,'' said Pope
John Paul II in a telegram to the Rev. Robert A. Brucato, the
auxiliary bishop of the archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ''Throughout the years he has been of great support to me in the
service of the universal church, he worked tirelessly to build
better ecumenical and interreligious relations, and for Catholics
and other Christians and men and women of good will throughout the
world he was a source of inspiration in serving God in our less
fortunate brothers and sisters,'' the telegram continued.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro-Valls had earlier said the
pope planned to send a personal envoy, Cardinal Angelo Sodano, to
attend O'Connor's funeral. There was no immediate word on when a
successor would be named.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop John P. Foley, head of the Pontifical Council for
Social Communications and a Pennsylvania native like O'Connor, told
Vatican Radio that it was possible the pope has ''already chosen
somebody to be an apostolic administrator, that I don't know.''
That is an interim position.
</P>
<P>
   As for a permanent replacement as archbishop, ''I presume that
because he had already turned 80, that the process for finding a
successor had already begun,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   A flood of tributes from prominent admirers -- President Clinton,
Texas Gov. George W. Bush and fellow cardinals from around the
country -- testified to O'Connor's position as America's foremost
Catholic leader and a close ally of the pope.
</P>
<P>
   ''For more than 50 years, he has reached out with uncommon
fortitude to minister to the needs of America's Catholics,''
Clinton said in a statement. ''The courage and firm faith he showed
in his final illness inspired us all.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Adam Maida of Detroit recalled O'Connor's ''great
compassion and commonsense ... and that wonderful glint in his
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   ''A legend has been called home to God,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor was the oldest active bishop in the United States and
the most influential, leading two million Catholics in the nation's
media capital.
</P>
<P>
   Although he made a farewell visit to the pope in February, he
missed many public Masses at St. Patrick's Cathedral after his
surgery and was absent from his traditional perch in front of the
cathedral when the St. Patrick's Day Parade went by in March.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the perception of his power remained intact: It was
in a letter to the cardinal -- sent 10 days before New York's
presidential primary -- that Bush expressed regret for appearing at
Bob Jones University, which many see as anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Congress awarded O'Connor the country's highest
civilian honor, the Congressional Gold Medal.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal was a familiar figure to devout Catholics as well
as average New Yorkers. He blessed parades as they passed St.
Patrick's Cathedral on Fifth Avenue; provoked a firestorm by
recommending excommunication for Catholic politicians who support
abortion rights; and used his pulpit to weigh in on controversies
large and small.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when American Catholics were increasingly inclined to
go their own way on matters of faith and morals, O'Connor staunchly
championed the Vatican line on birth control, abortion and
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   He battled with prominent Catholic abortion rights supporters,
most notably New York's Gov. Mario Cuomo and Geraldine Ferraro, the
1984 Democratic vice presidential nominee. Cuomo and Ferraro said
they opposed abortion personally, but believed women had the right
to make their own choice.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor refused to accept their position, writing in 1990 that
Catholics who opposed the church's teachings on abortion ''must be
warned that they are at a risk of excommunication'' from the
church.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal also led opposition to local gay rights legislation
and kicked a gay Catholic group out of a parish church where it had
met for years. In 1989, enraged activists responded by chaining
themselves to pews and throwing condoms in the air during Mass at
St. Patrick's.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, O'Connor made unannounced visits to Catholic
hospitals where he ministered to AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Fay, a member of the steering committee of the gay and
lesbian Catholic group Dignity New York, said the cardinal's famed
compassion did not extend to homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we will maybe remember most as representative of the
cardinal's stance toward our community is the closed doors of the
cathedral,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor also defied then-Mayor Ed Koch's executive order
requiring social service organizations -- including those run by the
church -- to provide equal services to homosexuals. O'Connor
maintained that that would imply church toleration of
homosexuality. A court later held that Koch had exceeded his
authority.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal and the acerbic mayor went on to become good
friends and co-authors of a book, ''His Eminence and Hizzoner,'' in
1989. Koch, a Jew, faithfully attended the cardinal's Christmas Eve
Mass long after his tenure as mayor was over.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor grew up in a Philadelphia row house hearing his father
-- a gold-leaf painter and union man -- quote from the pope's
encyclical on labor. The cardinal once quipped that he wanted his
casket to have a union label, and when the archdiocese was caught
in a hospital workers' strike, he stood fast against hiring
nonunion replacements.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor described himself as ''thoroughly orthodox in church
doctrine and progressive, even -- heaven forbid! -- liberal, on
social issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes O'Connor put his foot in his mouth. He once compared
aborted fetuses to victims of the Holocaust, and characterized the
Holocaust as Judaism's ''gift'' to the world. He meant that
European Jews showed how to endure the unendurable, but some found
the comment offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ''I said some dumb things,'' O'Connor conceded.
</P>
<P>
   But on Yom Kippur in 1999, he sent a letter to Jewish leaders
expressing ''my own abject sorrow for any member of the Catholic
Church, high or low, who may have harmed you or your forebears.''
Nobel Peace Prize winner Elie Wiesel published the letter in an ad
in the Sunday Times, saying: ''For the prince of the church to say
the things he does, it's very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor spent most of his clerical life in military uniform,
joining the Navy in 1952 in response to a call for more chaplains
during the Korean War. When he retired in 1979, he had risen to
rear admiral and chief of Navy chaplains.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor was made an auxiliary bishop and assigned to the
military vicarate under Cardinal Terence Cooke of New York.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1983 he was appointed bishop of Scranton, Pa. He held
that post less than a year before being chosen to succeed Cooke
--who died of cancer -- as New York archbishop. He was elevated to
cardinal in May 1985.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said he would have been satisfied to be a parish priest
or teacher, and feared he might instead be remembered for ''the
alleged -- and to me, the mythical -- power, about my purported
political manipulations and all that kind of nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What I would like my epitaph to say is simply that 'He was a
good priest.'''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor is survived by three siblings: Dorothy Hamilton of St.
Petersburg, Fla., Mary Theresa Ward of Chadds Ford, Penn., and
Thomas J. O'Connor of Sea Isle City, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
