<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Defends Charter Schools  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Disputing critics who say charter schools
don't work, President Clinton said today that they are most
effective when states establish ''the right kind of
accountability'' and invest enough resources.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton visited the pioneer City Academy in St. Paul to tout the
popularity and success of charter schools. The school is stop No. 3
on a two-day tour of education success stories in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want all of America to know about you, and through you
understand what might be done in other communities,'' Clinton said.
''You proved charter schools are a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said public charter schools expanded from one at his
election in 1992 to roughly 1,700 today. He admitted not all
charter schools are the best, but pinned part of the blame for
dysfunctional schools on ''loose'' state rules that allow them to
''stay open and become like another bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Not every state has had the right kind of accountability,''
Clinton said. ''Not only has this first charter school in America
done great, but Minnesota's law is right. You have struck the right
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced that the Education Department will develop
national guidelines for participation by businesses and religious
organizations in charter schools. He also announced $16 million in
new money and the continuation of $121 million in previously
awarded grants for charter schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   He then took part in an Internet chat with students and teachers
on ChannelOne.com. He sat before a computer monitor but didn't
touch the keyboard, directing his attention and remarks to the
audience before him.
</P>
<P>
   Later today, he is to end the tour at an elementary school in
Columbus, Ohio, where improvements are just getting started.
</P>
<P>
   Each school exemplifies a different component of Clinton's plan
to lower class sizes, modernize schools and increase community and
parental involvement in public education. The tour also gives
Clinton an opportunity to tweak congressional Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want every single school in America to be a school of the
future,'' Clinton told students at Central High in Davenport, Iowa.
The school was built in 1907 and is undergoing a renovation. ''You
need it, you deserve it and if Congress will pass my proposals, you
will get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate this week took up an education bill that the White
House calls a setback to education reform.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans used their majority to advance a GOP measure
that would give states more discretion in their use of federal
funds. At the same time, they rejected a Democratic alternative to
target funds for more teachers and smaller classes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton advocates national standards and charter schools, which
are public schools created by parents and teachers and run with
exemptions from many state laws and regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the House backed a gradual increase in federal aid to
special education from $5 billion this year to $25 billion in 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Last month both houses approved a $1.83 trillion package that
includes large tax cuts and reductions in many domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   During Clinton's term, federal money for charter schools grew to
about $400 million. Schools may use the money for planning,
organization and start-up costs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has asked for an additional $30 million for charter
schools in next year's budget, bringing the total request to $175
million.
</P>
<P>
   House Education Committee Chairman Bill Goodling, R-Pa., did not
dispute that charter schools are on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, his taking credit for the growth is like Al Gore
saying that he invented the Internet,'' Goodling said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday in Owensboro, Kentucky, Clinton announced a new
federal report-card system for low-performing schools. The
Education Department will compile a list of such schools and what
they are doing to improve, and teams of federal experts will try to
help, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House: www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
<P>
   Channel One: www.ChannelOne.com
</P>
</TEXT>
