<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notification under STAR tax abatement program will change  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Homeowners will not be getting checks
directly from the state containing rebates under the STAR property
tax reduction program, but changes will be made in how taxpayers
are notified about their savings.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition by Democrats blocked Republican Gov. George Pataki
from instituting a system of sending individuals checks for the
amount their property taxes are going down under STAR, as the
governor proposed in his 2000 State of the State address.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said the checks would give New Yorkers a truer sense of
how much the STAR program means to them than the current method.
Districts bill the state for how much STAR is reducing property tax
bills, and pass on the savings directly through the tax bills. No
money changes hands between the state and property owners.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's proposal called for taxpayers to get rebate
checks from the state two to three months after they pay the tax
bills which districts typically send out each Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno complained
that some districts could raise school taxes substantially and
mislead taxpayers about the sizes of those increases because STAR
savings were being applied at the same time to the tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, however, contended that Pataki was seeking to more
directly get credit for the STAR program which the governor
championed. They noted that all tax bills already require tax
collectors to state ''Your tax savings resulting this year from the
STAR program is'' and to fill in the number.
</P>
<P>
   Agreed to in the 2000-01 state budget will be a modified
notification system for homeowners. They will be told how much in
STAR savings is being applied to their tax bill and how much the
increase -- if any -- is in the school tax levy.
</P>
<P>
   Most homeowners will see higher school tax bills in those
notifications, according to the state Business Council. It said its
survey of school tax bills for the 2000-01 school year show average
proposed property tax increases of nearly 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic state Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said the
modified STAR notification system will accomplish what Pataki had
sought -- to prevent school tax increases from being camouflaged --
without creating a cumbersome system of sending out millions of
rebate checks each year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we accomplished that without the necessity to have the
administrative need of receiving checks, and sending back checks,''
Silver said. ''Instead, we've given them the notification and
they've never had to lay the money out to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki had estimated it would cost $8 million to implement the
rebate check system, which the governor continued to defend.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it should have been passed, but as part of the
negotiations you give and take, and that was one we were unable to
convince the Legislature to adopt,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Silver agreed Pataki tried, but could not get his way on the
rebates.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some things you win and some things you lose at the bargaining
table,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   STAR rebates will total about $1.6 billion in the next state
budget, with $600 million going to senior citizens. Older New
Yorkers were the first to see savings under the program, which is
being phased in for all homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   STAR is scheduled to be fully phased in the state's 2001-02
fiscal year, when property tax exemptions will total about $2.3
billion. New York City residence owners get related income tax
credits which will push the cost of the STAR program to $2.8
billion in 2001-02.
</P>
<P>
   STAR stands for the School Tax Relief program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 1318 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Volunteer firefighters often have outdated tools, training  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) -- Poor training and outdated or malfunctioning
equipment has threatened the lives and safety of volunteer
firefighters statewide, state records showed.
</P>
<P>
   The violations reported over the last two years include rusty,
untested fire extinguishers and firehouses with faulty wiring,
broken sprinkler systems and explosive chemicals stored near
heaters. The problems were reported by the Utica Observer-Dispatch
after a review of state inspection records from the state Labor
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the problems were serious enough that they could have
caused firefighters to be killed or seriously hurt, the records
show. Others have more to do with equipment that does not work
right.
</P>
<P>
   The implications of these problems for public safety are unclear
because government inspectors usually check only for hazards that
could endanger firefighters, not the people they are supposed to
protect.
</P>
<P>
   An exception may be the high death rate among volunteer
firefighters in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every year, more firefighters die on the job in New York
than in any other state -- a rate experts said is not surprising
because New York's fire service relies so heavily on small,
volunteer departments that often cannot afford to screen
firefighters for health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the roughly 100 firefighters who die on the job
every year in the United States die of heart attacks and other
stress-related conditions, according to government statistics.
Safety officials insist most such deaths are preventable, but
federal investigators said many fire departments still have not
taken even basic steps to ensure that their firefighters are
healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say it potentially puts the public at risk,'' said Tom
Hales, who investigates firefighter deaths for the National
Institute for Occupational Safety and Health. ''How big is that
risk? I don't know the answer to that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the last year for which reliable data are available, 15
firefighters died in New York, compared to nine in California
</P>
<P>
   ''Practically speaking, a lot of volunteer departments don't
require any screening at all, said Bill Hershman, a spokesman for
the International Association of Fire Chiefs in Alexandria, Va..
</P>
<P>
   In all, the state Labor Department's investigators found 388
violations at 66 different fire departments outside New York City
during the last two years. Officials from the departments cited for
violations insist that they never posed much danger, but the
government labeled 240 of the problems serious.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department records show:
</P>
<P>
   --Many fire departments do not train their firefighters as well
or as often as the law requires.
</P>
<P>
   --Fire departments in many places are using equipment that is
sometimes two decades old.
</P>
<P>
   --A number of firehouses across the state are fire hazards,
because of shoddy wiring, broken sprinkler systems and other
problems.
</P>
<P>
   --Many departments do not keep complete equipment maintenance and
training records.
</P>
<P>
   --Several departments knowingly used equipment they knew
malfuntioned and state inspectors said was dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   --Several departments have been cited more than once for the same
violation. Nevertheless, in two years, the state has not imposed
any penalties on any of its volunteer departments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, firefighters in Ovid near Syracuse weren't issued
protective gloves to handle people injured in accidents and
hazardous material spills. The same Seneca County department,
hadn't tested firefighters to make sure their respirators fit and
for not insisting that firefighters enter burning buildings in
pairs -- something most experts consider to be a basic safety rule.
</P>
<P>
   And officials in Hubbardsville, 40 miles southeast of Syracuse,
ordered firefighters to use air packs without training, records
show.
</P>
<P>
   Other departments failed to screen and vaccinate firefighters
for tuberculosis and hepatitis. Inspectors said the departments
needed the procedures because their members had been exposed to
people who were known to carry the diseases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 1325 </TRAILER>
