<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Receives Heart Assist Pump  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- The first successful human recipient of a type of
miniature pump implanted inside the heart says she feels like she
has a new life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to go out and talk to people and tell them about the
miracle the Lord created for me,'' Lois Spiller, a 52-year-old
retired financial analyst, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The operation, performed three weeks ago, brings scientists
closer to the elusive goal of finding a permanent alternative to
the heart transplant. For now, the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration has approved study of the pump only as a bridge to a
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Spiller, the first patient enrolled in the five-patient study,
will probably have to wait two to four months for a donor heart,
doctors told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The battery-operated device, known as the Jarvik 2000, is about
the size of a wine cork and fits directly into the heart's left
ventricle. When the heart can no longer pump properly, the tiny
turbine pushes oxygenated blood throughout the body.
</P>
<P>
   The Jarvik 2000 was developed by Dr. Robert Jarvik, the
artificial heart pioneer, and Dr. O.H. Frazier, chief of
cardiopulmonary transplantation at the Texas Heart Institute at St.
Luke's Episcopal Hospital. It was Frazier who performed the surgery
on Spiller.
</P>
<P>
   ''To see her recovery is a remarkable thing,'' Frazier said.
''Before the operation, she was so sick she couldn't speak a
complete sentence -- not just because she was out of breath but
because she couldn't think, so bad was the blood flow to her
brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other people have had the device implanted on an emergency
basis, and both died.
</P>
<P>
   Spiller, whose history of heart trouble dates to 1987, received
the pump April 10 after other measures failed to support her
failing heart. At one point, doctors had to restart her heart after
she went into coronary arrest. Her case, though, wasn't technically
considered an emergency, as the other two were. Instead, she is the
first of five patients who are to receive the device as part of the
FDA-approved study of the device.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors were ecstatic about the results. Spiller stayed in the
intensive care unit only 1{ days after the operation, which they
said is at least 10 days less than most heart-transplant patients.
Spiller was also walking within a week, whereas most
heart-transplant patients are bedridden for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have been working on a variety of devices to assist
or even replace the heart, and they are at varying stages of
development and testing. One of the most widely tested is the left
ventricular assist device, which is attached to a diseased heart to
help it do its work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
