<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Derides S.F. Paper Suspension  </HEADLINE>
By BOB EGELKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- When San Francisco Examiner publisher
Timothy White testified this week that he offered favorable
editorial coverage to the mayor in exchange for support of The
Hearst Corp.'s purchase of the rival Chronicle, he was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst said the conversation White described with Mayor Willie
Brown may not have taken place, and if it did, was a ''serious
breach of Hearst's policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But White said the same thing to Justice Department lawyers in
December. A transcript of his deposition, shown to reporters
Wednesday, lists two Hearst Corp. lawyers as present, although a
Hearst spokeswoman said one left during the session. The second
attorney said today he attended the entire deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ''Apparently they have fired this man not because of the
information itself, but because it was revealed in a public
forum,'' attorney Joseph M. Alioto said in court after reading from
White's deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto represents businessman Clint Reilly, the former mayoral
candidate suing to block Hearst's purchase of the San Francisco
Chronicle and sale of the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends the acquisition of California's second-largest
newspaper would give Hearst an illegal monopoly, despite approval
of the sale by the Justice Department's Antitrust Division. The
civil trial began Monday.
</P>
<P>
   White, in a statement issued by Hearst after his testimony
Monday, said he had been ''tired and confused by the question.''
</P>
<P>
   He was placed on indefinite leave Tuesday, and was replaced as
publisher by George Irish, head of Hearst's newspaper division.
Hearst said it was launching an internal investigation into White's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   According to a transcript of White's Dec. 16 deposition, Justice
Department lawyers questioned him about an Aug. 30 meeting with
Brown. At the time, Brown was publicly opposed to Hearst's plans to
buy the Chronicle and sell or merge the Examiner into the larger
paper.
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department lawyer asked if White was intending to
convey to Brown that his support for Hearst's purchase of the
Chronicle ''would result in more favorable treatment'' by the
Examiner. White answered yes.
</P>
<P>
   He gave the same answer to the same question in court Monday,
and later specified that he was talking about editorials, not news
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Both Brown and Examiner executive editor Phil Bronstein, who
also attended the lunch meeting with the mayor, said outside of
court that no such discussion took place.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Shriver, Hearst's director of corporate communications,
said White was suspended entirely because of what he revealed in
his testimony on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The deposition transcript shows that two Hearst lawyers were
present at White's deposition -- Gary Halling, the company's chief
attorney at the trial, and Jonathan Thackeray, Hearst's vice
president and general counsel. Shriver said Thackeray told her he
left the session before it ended and did not hear the testimony in
question. She did not know whether Halling remained throughout the
deposition. Halling confirmed to The Associated Press today that he
was present throughout the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Shriver said, ''senior executives at the company
were not aware of the content of the testimony'' until White
testified in open court.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said Hearst must have known what White told the Justice
Department, and cited White's deposition in asking for a court
order prohibiting Hearst from punishing witnesses for their
testimony. He was turned down by U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker,
who is overseeing the non-jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''It sounds like it's not the fact of these actions but the
exposure of these actions which motivated his removal,'' said Tom
Rosenstiel, director of the Project for Excellence in Journalism,
affiliated with Columbia University's Graduate School of
Journalism.
</P>
<P>
   In a note to its readers Wednesday, the Examiner said: ''The
newsroom employees of The Examiner are proud that our editorial
support is not, and never has been, for sale. We fully expect any
employee to be held accountable for actions that undermine our
editorial integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Chronicle: http://www.sfgate.com/chronicle/
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Examiner: http://www.sfgate.com/examiner/
</P>
</TEXT>
