<HEADLINE> Soybeans Grains Mostly Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean prices retreated today in morning
dealings on the Chicago Board of Trade on the latest forecasts for
rain in Midwestern growing regions. Grains also were mostly lower.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans were pressured by improved chances for rain both this
weekend and later next week. Losses were limited by divided opinion
on how extensive the rains will be.
</P>
<P>
   Corn also was sent lower by the wet forecasts, although
market-watchers said only the arrival of actual rain would send
prices down sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat sank under the early selloff in soybeans and corn, before
forging higher. It was little changed at mid-morning.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery was unchanged at $2.72 a bushel; July
corn fell 1 cent to $2.49} a bushel; July oats fell { cent to
$1.27} a bushel; July soybeans fell 3{ cents to $5.68{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures declined in early trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle fell .03 cent to 68.87 cents a pound; August
feeder cattle fell .03 cent to 84.67 cents a pound; June lean hogs
fell 1.02 cent to 73.25 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell the
limit 3 cents to 89.62 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
