<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujitsu To Invest $550M in Plant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRESHAM, Ore. (AP) -- Fujitsu Microelectronics will invest $550
million in a manufacturing plant and hire 300 workers as it races
to fill increasing demands for the type of computer memory chips
used in cellular telephones and digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our manufacturing strategy is to shift where the demand is,''
said Kazunari Shirai, executive vice president and president of
Fujitsu's Electronic Devices Group.
</P>
<P>
   Fujitsu is among several chip-makers that are boosting
production of flash memory chips, used mainly for portable devices.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing demand for these kind of chips is welcome news to
the semiconductor industry, which had been suffering through a
sales slump.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Fujitsu pulled out of a property tax-break agreement
with Gresham and Multnomah County because it was unable to create
the jobs it had promised.
</P>
<P>
   Fujitsu will equip a now-idle plant in Gresham as part of the
expansion. It also will add manufacturing equipment to a second
plant. When the project is complete, Fujitsu will triple its
manufacturing capacity in Gresham and will employ 800 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
