<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CDs and Bonds Looking Better  </HEADLINE>
By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With stock market volatility and higher interest
rates, fixed-income investments such as bank certificates of
deposit and bonds are starting to look more attractive to some
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on one-year CDs are averaging 5.36 percent nationwide,
compared with 4.36 percent a year ago, and five-year CDs are
yielding an average 6.01 percent, up from 4.63 percent, according
to bankrate.com, which tracks the returns on CDs around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But scout around, and you can find some banks that pay in the 7
percent range.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, bond yields are also up sharply, following the path
of other interest rates. The Bond Buyer, a municipal bond industry
newspaper, publishes an index that tracks the average yield on 40
tax-exempt muni bonds; over the past year it has climbed to 6.1
percent from 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you should start taking advantage of these growing
returns depends on what you want from an investment.
</P>
<P>
   Are you looking for income? Then CDs or bonds can provide it.
Have you already sold stocks and are now looking for a safe place
to earn some money for a while? CDs can do that for you.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think, with the stock market well off the highs of
earlier this year, that you'll get better gains with bonds or CDs
than you will on Wall Street, that's a bet you could lose.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you've held on this long, it may be time to look at your
portfolio'' and make some changes, said Scott M. Kahan, a New York
certified financial planner. But, he said, even if the market
continues to slide, it's still likely over the long term to deliver
higher returns than CDs or bonds.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide that you want to put money into a CD, don't just
head for the commercial bank where you do your checking.
Bankrate.com's Web site (www.bankrate.com) lists the highest CD
rates and yields it has found at banks across the country. You can
open accounts over the phone or by mail, so don't be deterred by
the fact that some of these banks are located far from your home.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, longer-term bank CDs and bonds tended to have
higher yields than shorter-term investments, simply to make it more
worthwhile for investors to tie their money up for a longer time
period. But the gap among CD yields has narrowed, and Kahan noted
that because of shifts in the marketplace, two-year Treasury bonds,
with a yield of about 6.7 percent, are currently a better deal than
10-year bonds, which are paying out 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're advising is for people to invest between a two- and
10-year range'' of bonds, Kahan said. He said investors leaning
toward CDs could employ a similar strategy, known as ''laddering,''
or choosing investments with varying maturity dates.
</P>
<P>
   If you feel that bonds are a more conservative investment than
stocks, you should recognize that bonds are still risky in that you
can lose some of your principal, especially if you invest in a bond
mutual fund, the price of which fluctuates along with the market.
And because bond prices and yields move in opposite directions and
interest rates are currently going up, the price of a bond fund you
buy into now may drop in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Individual bonds also fluctuate in price, but that may not be a
problem if you're planning to hold them until maturity, when you'll
be paid back in full. However, if it turns out that you need some
cash before the bonds mature and you decide to sell when the market
is down, you'll be taking a loss.
</P>
<P>
   The attractiveness of bank CDs is that they aren't subject to
the vagaries of the markets. Your money is guaranteed to grow, and
there's no risk to your principal. However, banks do assess heavy
penalties if you withdraw your money before the CD's term ends.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you choose a CD or bond -- or neither -- may depend on how
much money you'll make over the year, 5 years, 10 years or whatever
length you want. www.bankrate.com has a compound interest
calculator that can tell you approximately how much you can expect
to earn from a certificate of deposit or a bond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
