<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Thursday, May 4, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   'I Love You' Virus Hits Computers
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A new software virus that spread quickly around
the world today, has swamped U.S. computer networks with e-mails
entitled ''ILOVEYOU'' after crippling government and business
computers in Asia and Europe. Experts said they were stunned by the
speed and wide reach of the virus -- which struck members of the
U.S. Congress and Britain's parliament -- and warned computer users
not to open the ''LOVELETTER'' attachment that comes with the
contaminated e-mail. It seems to be the same sort of virus as
''Melissa,'' the e-mail virus that overwhelmed computer systems
around the world about a year ago, said Bill Pollack, spokesman for
the CERT Coordination Center in Pittsburgh, a government-chartered
computer security team. But the new virus, which uses the Outlook
e-mail program from Microsoft to spread, also may infect other
types of files stored on desktop computers and network servers,
CERT reported on its telephone hotline. According to other reports,
the virus may rename or damage those files.
</P>
<P>
   Weather Hurts April Retail Sales
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cooler-than-normal weather throughout most of
April dampened business at many of the nation's biggest retailers
last month, with many chains reporting sales well below
expectations. Merchants with significant presence in the eastern
half of the country and a heavy reliance on clothing were
particularly hurt. Some storeowners said they would miss
first-quarter earnings estimates. Analysts were quick to point out
that the disappointing results in April were mostly weather
related, and not a result of any sweeping pullback in consumer
spending due to rising interest rates or stock market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity Rises at 2.4 Pct. Rate
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The productivity of U..S. workers rose at an
annual rate of 2.4 percent in the first three months of this year,
considerably less than the 3.5 percent growth economists had
expected. The figure announced by the Labor Department is likely to
accelerate the pace of Federal Reserve interest rate hikes in order
to fight inflation, according to Oscar Gonzalez, an economist at
John Hancock in Boston. He notes that the slower productivity
increase comes at a time when unit labor costs have risen more than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Down 52; Nasdaq Down 11
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks are modestly lower this afternoon after a
report of slowing productivity growth intensified worries that
higher interest rates are on the way. Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the
Dow Jones industrial average was down 52.43 at 10,427.70. Advancers
on the NYSE outnumbered decliners 1,541-1,298. The Nasdaq was down
11.48 at 3,695.83.
</P>
