</P>
<P>
   Soros: U.S. May Be in Bear Market
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Financier and philanthropist George Soros said
today that the recent selloffs in U.S. stocks probably constitute a
bear market. ''We probably are in a bear market, only we don't know
it yet. I think one has to position oneself accordingly,'' he told
a group of journalists at the Association of American
Correspondents in London. Soros said he is keeping many of his
investments in the form of assets that are easily converted into
cash. ''We are very heavily liquid and rather happy with it,'' he
said. Soros suggested that U.S. markets could also be at risk
because many brokers and traders are not old enough to remember the
last time the economy suffered a severe downturn and prolonged
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan Warns Banks of Risks
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan warned
banks today that they must not become overconfident in deciding how
to handle risks in the broader range of activities they now engage
in. In his speech for a bankers convention in Chicago, Greenspan
concentrated on two developments, the growing participation of
banks in holding derivatives and merchant banking. He noted that
the derivative market has not been tested in non-prosperous times.
In merchant banking, banks are allowed to buy stock in
non-financial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram Posts Wider Loss
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Seagram Co., the Canadian media and beverage
company, posted a wider loss in its third fiscal quarter today but
still beat Wall Street expectations. Seagram, owner of the
Universal movie and music studios, lost $265 million or 61 cents
for the three months ending March 31. Analysts had expected a loss
of 66 cents. In the same period a year ago, Seagram posted a loss
of $199 million, or 50 cents a share. Revenue rose 5 percent to
$3.38 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shell Earnings Double in 1st Quarter
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The Royal Dutch Shell Group of Cos. said today its
earnings nearly doubled in the first quarter thanks to higher crude
oil prices and stricter cost controls. The energy company reported
earnings of $3.34 billion in the January-March period, up from
$1.68 billion during the same period last year. The Anglo-Dutch oil
group said demand for crude continues to grow. Given the limited
excess capacity of many oil-producing countries, prices should
remain well above the company's minimum target of $14 per barrel,
it said.
</P>
<P>
   Fujitsu To Invest $550M in Plant
</P>
<P>
   GRESHAM, Ore. (AP) -- Fujitsu Microelectronics will invest $550
million in a manufacturing plant and hire 300 workers as it races
to fill increasing demands for the type of computer memory chips
used in cellular telephones and digital cameras. ''Our
manufacturing strategy is to shift where the demand is,'' said
Kazunari Shirai, executive vice president and president of
Fujitsu's Electronic Devices Group.
</P>
<P>
   Cathay Pacific To Buy New Jets
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Cathay Pacific Airways said today it is
spending $1.5 billion to buy and lease new jets from Airbus
Industrie and the Boeing Co. Cathay said today it will create more
than 1,400 new jobs -- employing another 1,000 cabin crew, 220
pilots and more than 200 ground workers -- most of them based in
Hong Kong. Cathay is expanding its fleet after seeing its passenger
volumes rise by 8 percent and its freight volumes by 11 percent in
the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Poll: Public Optimistic on Finances
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A majority of Americans expect their personal
financial situations to be stronger a year from now, according to
an Associated Press poll. Just over half, 51 percent, said they
felt that their finances would be better, while 42 percent said
they would be about the same. Only 4 percent expected things to get
worse. One-third in the poll, conducted for the AP by ICR of Media,
Pa., said their own personal situations were better than a year
ago, while 57 percent said they were about the same. Eleven percent
felt their financial situations were worse. Two-thirds of Americans
said they have not changed their spending habits because of recent
financial news such as fluctuations in the stock market. But three
of 10 said they are now more cautious, according to the telephone
poll of 1,017 people conducted from April 27 through Tuesday. The
poll had an error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
   Productivity: up 2.4 percent
</P>
<P>
   Jobless claims: up 20,000 to 303,000
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow: Unemployment
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow: Consumer credit
</P>
