<HEADLINE> Poll: Public Optimistic on Finances  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Retired dentist Norman Alpher, a man who
follows and invests in the markets, is upbeat about his financial
prospects. So is Dana Thompson, a 29-year-old house painter with
young kids and no investments.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, a majority of Americans expect their personal financial
situations to be stronger a year from now, according to an
Associated Press poll.
</P>
<P>
   Just over half, 51 percent, said they felt that their finances
would be better, while 42 percent said they would be about the
same. Only 4 percent expected things to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pretty upbeat about it,'' says Alpher, a 67-year-old
resident of Silver Spring, Md. ''Everybody seems to be working and
seems to be making a living.''
</P>
<P>
   One-third in the poll, conducted for the AP by ICR of Media,
Pa., said their own personal situations were better than a year
ago, while 57 percent said they were about the same. Eleven percent
felt their financial situations were worse.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of Americans said they have not changed their
spending habits because of recent financial news such as
fluctuations in the stock market. But three of 10 said they are now
more cautious, according to the telephone poll of 1,017 people
conducted from April 27 through Tuesday. The poll had an error
margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Public optimism about the nation's generally strong economy is
about the same now as it was in an AP poll in the late summer of
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The generally upbeat tone on the economy could be encouraging
for Vice President Al Gore, the likely Democratic presidential
nominee who argues that as part of the current administration he
would be the best man to keep the strong economy going. Republican
George W. Bush says his tax cut proposal is the best way to ensure
continued economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Just over half of both Democrats and Republicans say they expect
their own financial situations to be better a year from now.
Democrats appeared to be slightly more upbeat than Republicans
about their finances in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Almost four in 10 of those with money invested in the stock
market said things were better financially than a year ago, while
just over a fourth of those with no investments felt that way.
Those who made $25,000 or more were more likely to feel things have
been getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economy should keep going for a while unless they
artificially hold it up,'' said Alpher, referring to recent
increases in interest rates intended to harness inflation. ''I
don't think there's much they can do to slow it down.''
</P>
<P>
   In the poll, younger adults were more likely to say their
financial situations were better, with four in 10 adults between 18
and 34 saying that compared with just over a third of people
between 35 and 44.
</P>
<P>
   Only one in six adults 65 and over said they were doing better
financially, while three-fourths said their situation was about the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes Noto, a widow who scrapes by on Social Security, said, ''I
think everything's too high and they don't pay me much. Everybody's
struggling, especially senior citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the market fluctuations, the economy continues to signal
its strength with recent reports on strong income growth and
surging home sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where I live, things are booming in construction work and
things like that,'' said Dana Thompson, the house painter and
mother of two from Gulfport, Miss. She pays little attention to the
news from Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never gotten into that ... probably should,'' she said.
''But it has no effect on me.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a third in the poll said they had investments. Only
one in eight said the stock market had the most influence on them
personally, compared with the job market and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not a person who allows myself to get too fidgety or
nervous over what I'm hearing,'' said Romona Murdock, 40, a real
estate agent from Cincinnati. ''I am optimistic. I set a plan for
myself and keep my debt load low.''	   Not everybody is getting the benefits of
the economic expansion,
Murdock said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people I talk to and have been around, most of them are
trying to work two jobs,'' she said. ''Or if they're working in a
job where they make good money, they're working long hours and
doubling the workload.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
