<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1812 Arsenal fighting for critical cannon contract  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATERVLIET, N.Y. (AP) -- The nation's oldest Army arsenals is in
a battle for a critical contract with a Kentucky firm.
</P>
<P>
   A $1 billion contract to manufacture gun tubes for 723
lightweight, 155mm towed howitzers for the Army and Marine Corps is
at stake.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sens. Charles Schumer and Daniel Patrick Moynihan, both New
York Democrats, as well as New York congressmen Michael McNulty, a
Democrat; and John Sweeney, a Republican; have told Defense
Secretary William Cohen that the Watervliet Arsenal needs the
contract to survive.
</P>
<P>
   A similar congressional effort is underway among Kentucky
representatives to land the contract in Louisville. They say United
Defense Unlimited can produce the artillery pieces for far less
than the Watervliet Arsenal, which was built during the War of
1812.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky effort is led Sen. Mitch McConnell, a Republican
and chairman of the powerful Senate Rules Committee, who wants the
guns built in Louisville. McConnell, Sen. Jim Bunning, and U.S.
Reps. Ron Lewis and Anne Northup also support a bid by United
Defense, which has headquarters in Arlington, Va., but operates in
the Greater Louisville Technology Park, the former site of the old
Louisville Naval Ordnance Station.
</P>
<P>
   In an April 7 letter to Cohen, the Kentucky delegation said
''Louisville's United Defense was asked to bid on the LW155 gunwork
because of the incredibly high cost of production at the Watervliet
Arsenal ... United Defense is able to perform the same work in
Louisville at a fraction of the cost and without government
subsidy,'' McConnell's letter states.	   
</P>
<P>
   The Watervliet facility made an initial bid of $266,000 per gun
tube. United Defense proposed to make them for $143,000 each. And
the Kentuckians claim Watervliet will need a $20 million government
subsidy ''to bring its cost even close to that of Louisville.''
</P>
<P>
   The Watervliet Arsenal just north of Albany is the nation's
oldest arsenal and employs more than 600 people, although that
number will be reduced to about 430 next year due to layoffs
resulting from fewer orders for the arsenal's cannons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
