<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 47; Nasdaq Down 7  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly lower today after a report
of slowing productivity growth intensified worries that higher
interest rates are on the way. Blue chip stocks suffered the
biggest losses as investors theorized that these companies' growth
will be most compromised by rising rates.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was down 47.78 at 10,432.35.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Nasdaq composite
index was down 7.57 at 3,699.74, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 7.20 to 1,407.90.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell after the Labor Department reported that Americans'
productivity, a key measure of future prosperity, rose at an annual
rate of 2.4 percent the first three months of this year. That
marked a sharp slowdown from the previous quarter, when
productivity rose at an extremely sharp 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Economists had expected productivity growth to come in at 3.5
percent. The lower-than-expected number exacerbated fears that the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates by as much as a
half-percentage point at its May 16 meeting as it works to keep
inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan spoke at a banking
conference in Chicago, keeping Wall Street traders on edge as they
sought signs of the Fed's likely action on May 16. Instead,
Greenspan's speech was focused primarily on risk management for
banks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a hesitant market right now,'' said Larry Wachtel, market
analyst at Prudential Securities. ''The productivity number was a
little worse than expected, but the real problem is that there's
just no conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachtel said the Labor Department's April employment report, due
out Friday morning, should give the market direction. Any signs of
escalating wage pressures could spark selling, while a modest
report could enable stocks to close out the week with a rally,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks, which are highly sensitive to interest rate
fluctuations, recovered some ground today after tumbling broadly on
Wednesday. American Express rose 2 7/8 to 144 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   But most blue-chip stocks were lower. AT&AMP;T fell 2 to 37 3/4,
General Electric fell 2 3/16 to 153 7/8 and McDonald's fell 1 1/2
to 35 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Goldman Sachs removed several retail stocks from its
recommended list, many of the nation's largest retailers reported
that April sales didn't meet expectations. Analysts said
cooler-than-normal weather caused the disappointing results in
April -- not rising interest rates or stock market volatility.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart fell 2 9/16 to 50 7/8 and Gap fell 2 5/16 to 34 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were mixed. Dell Computer fell 2 to 47 5/16,
while Palm Inc. rose 2 3/8 to 30 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Financier George Soros delivered a downbeat assessment of the
U.S. stock market today. Just last week, Soros reshuffled his hedge
fund company, saying he would convert his popular Quantum Fund to a
vehicle offering less risks, but also less potential for vast
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We probably are in a bear market, only we don't know it yet,''
Soros told a group of journalists at the Association of American
Correspondents in London. Soros added that that U.S. markets could
be at risk because many brokers and traders were not old enough to
remember the last time the economy suffered a severe downturn and
prolonged recession.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Soros noted that retail investors, whom he described as
''the little guys,'' were continuing to buy shares, particularly
through mutual funds and in high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 9-to-8 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 776.28 million
shares, behind Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.06 to 499.62.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
