<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aussies Pinpoint Disease Outbreak  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CORDER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The air conditioning system at
Melbourne's new aquarium spread a bacteria-tainted mist responsible
for a deadly outbreak of Legionnaires' disease, authorities said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two women have died, eight people are in critical condition and
66 people are confirmed to have the disease, health officials said.
All but one of the affected visited the aquarium in April.
</P>
<P>
   Health authorities issued an international alert Thursday asking
anybody who visited the aquarium from April 11-25 and who is
displaying Legionnaires' symptoms to visit a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also urged everyone who visited the aquarium in
April, including Prime Minister John Howard, to contact their
doctor if they suffer from muscle aches, fever, chills, headache
and shortness of breath.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,800 people gave urine samples for testing. Howard said
he felt fine and did not contribute a sample.
</P>
<P>
   The $19 million aquarium was viewed as one of the southern
city's major new tourist drawing cards, and the staff was
devastated to learn that the facility was to blame, spokesman Tom
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria state's Human Services Department said that the air
conditioning cooling towers, where the water that cools the
building's air is chilled, was to blame. The bacteria that are
believed to cause the illness grow in air conditioning ducts,
storage tanks and rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The system's cooling towers have been disinfected, and the
building has received a clean bill of health, but workers are still
trying to figure out what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Two travelers from New Zealand and one each from Britain and the
United States have reported symptoms, said Dr. John Carnie of the
Communicable Diseases Network Australia New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   The aquarium opened to public acclaim in January on the banks of
Melbourne's Yarra River, but Smith said attendance fell about 45
percent on suspicions that the outbreak began there.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak is a blow to Melbourne, Australia's second largest
city, as it tries to cash in on the flood of tourists expected in
Australia for the Sydney Olympics in September.
</P>
<P>
   Legionnaires' disease, a form of pneumonia, was discovered after
an outbreak that killed 34 people at a 1976 American Legion
convention in Philadelphia. An outbreak in the Netherlands last
year, the worst since 1976, killed 28 visitors to a flower show
near Amsterdam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1527 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
