<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Imposes News Censorship  </HEADLINE>
By DILIP GANGULY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Sri Lanka imposed censorship on the
foreign media and gave wide powers Thursday to the military, police
and administration to combat Tamil rebels poised to recapture their
former capital.
</P>
<P>
   Refused arm sales by India on Thursday, Sri Lanka re-established
relations with Israel after a 30-year gap. Israel is a big producer
and exporter of weapons, which the Sri Lankan army desperately
needs in its battle against the Tamil Tiger separatists.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Ministry said its soldiers were holding the main
defense line 15 miles south of Jaffna city, the Tamil's former
capital in the north.
</P>
<P>
   The government, which put the nation on war footing Wednesday
night, followed by invoking the Public Security Act giving sweeping
powers to the military, police and administration and imposing
censorship on the foreign media.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our aim is to see that news reports going out of Colombo are
balanced and carry our version as well,'' Ariya Rubasinghe, the
government's chief censor, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Sri Lankan media is already under censorship regulations
that were imposed in May 1998. However, foreign media was exempted
from censorship until Thursday's directive.
</P>
<P>
   Rubasinghe said journalists based in Colombo would be guided by
the Public Security Act, which bars anyone from reporting anything
the government may find prejudicial to the interest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Rubasinghe said the ''coming weeks are going to be critical, so
we had to take this decision, but we hope we will not be required
to carry this on for long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Correspondents' Association of Sri Lanka said it
will protest.
</P>
<P>
   Under the special powers, state authorities can seize aircraft,
ships and property without giving a reason and can ban publication
of newspapers and leaflets, prohibit demonstrations and strikes
that may harm the country's war efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities can obtain ''the services of any person for
nation's security or maintaining essential services,'' the
state-run radio said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Publication of any material that could harm national security
may be banned,'' the radio said. ''This includes photographs,
films, teleprinter messages and television.
</P>
<P>
   ''The printing, sale and distribution of certain newspapers that
contravene national security can also be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, the international journalists' group Reporters Sans
Frontiers criticized the censorship.
</P>
<P>
   ''The military situation is very critical, but I'm not sure that
imposing these draconian laws is the right solution,'' said Vincent
Brossel of the Paris group.
</P>
<P>
   The island nation is already under emergency rule that lets the
armed forces and police search any home and detain suspects without
formal warrants.
</P>
<P>
   The Ministry of Foreign Affairs gave no reasons for the decision
to resume ties with Israel, but the radio called the move
significant because it came when the country was faced with the
threat of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Sri Lanka's Tamil Tiger rebels have been fighting for 17 years
for an independent homeland for the country's 3.2 million minority
Tamils. They accuse the majority Sinhalese of widespread
discrimination in education and jobs. The government denies the
charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
