<DOCNO> APW20000504.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Warns Banks On Risks  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
Thursday that banks may be turning complacent about risks in the
technology-flavored economy.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to a banking conference, Greenspan called such
behavior by banks -- fueled by the record-breaking economic
expansion -- ''somewhat disquieting.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned that banks must not become overconfident in their
ability to manage risks, especially as they venture into new types
of financial activities.
</P>
<P>
   ''The possibility that market participants are developing a
degree of complacency or a feeling that technology has inoculated
them against market turbulence is admittedly somewhat
disquieting,'' Greenspan said. ''Such complacency is not
justified.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's warnings were reminiscent of comments he made in
March urging banks to be more careful in their lending to take into
account the fact that the current economic good times will not last
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Thursday to a conference sponsored by the Federal
Reserve in Chicago, Greenspan reviewed some of the new activities
in which banks are getting involved. The changes have been
accelerated by the passage in November of landmark legislation
removing Depression-era restrictions on banks getting involved in
new areas, such as securities transactions and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan noted that the legislation had greatly expanded the
opportunities for U.S. banks to get involved in merchant banking
activities.
</P>
<P>
   In merchant banking, a bank is allowed to buy stock in
non-financial companies. Greenspan said banks going into these new
areas needed to have a good understanding of the risks involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed chief, in his speech and a follow-up question and answer
period, did not make any direct comments on current economic growth
or the potential threat of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates five times since
last June in an effort to slow the economy and keep inflation at
bay.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are becoming nervous that the central bank may
accelerate the pace of those rate increases in coming months
because so far there are few signs that the economy is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks turned mostly lower on Wall Street Thursday after a
government report of slowing productivity growth intensified
worries that higher interest rates are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Greenspan concentrated on the growing
participation of banks in merchant banking and derivatives.
</P>
<P>
   Derivatives are complex financial instruments whose value
depends on the value or change in value of an underlying security,
commodity or asset. They are used by businesses to guard against
losses from unexpected market movements, but also by high-risk
investment funds to speculate.
</P>
<P>
   Derivatives played a key role in the near-collapse in September
1998 of hedge fund Long-Term Capital Management, which sent shock
waves through world financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said so far bank losses from their derivatives
holdings have been small, but he said they still should exercise
caution.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rapid growth and increasing importance of derivative
instruments in the risk profile of many large banks has been a
particular concern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The value worldwide of over-the-counter derivatives, which are
traded privately between investors rather than on futures
exchanges, is estimated at $80 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan noted, however, that even with the growth of bank
holdings in derivatives, they still remained quite small compared
with traditional activities, such as loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1556 </TRAILER>
