<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts To Ponder Napoleon Theories  </HEADLINE>
BY CHRISTINE OLLIVIER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Historians, toxicologists and cancer specialists
gathered Thursday to consider one of French history's legendary
puzzles: Was Napoleon murdered during his final exile, or did the
notorious emperor die a natural death?
</P>
<P>
   The conference, sponsored by the International Napoleon Society,
revolved around such unlikely questions as Napoleon's widening
girth, his seafood diet and a few well-preserved strands of his
hair.
</P>
<P>
   Napoleon was 52 when he died May 5, 1821 on the remote volcanic
island of St. Helena, where he was exiled after his final defeat at
Waterloo. His death has long been attributed to stomach cancer
despite lingering theories of murder, which have gained credibility
in many academic circles.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the pieces of the puzzle are in place'' to indicate
arsenic poisoning, said Ben Weider, president of the Canada-based
group and author of six books on Napoleon.
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy theories took on new seriousness in 1995 after the
FBI and Britain's Scotland Yard discovered that clippings of
Napoleon's hair were tinged with poison. But during the conference,
experts said the only way to solve the question for good is to
exhume Napoleon's body from its marble tomb in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   One French cancer specialist argued that Napoleon couldn't have
had stomach cancer because most patients with the disease lose
weight dramatically. According to testimonies, ''not only did the
emperor not lose weight during his captivity at St. Helena, he in
fact became rather stout,'' Dr. Andre Tardot said.
</P>
<P>
   Weider, who organized the conference, noted that Napoleon's
final on-again, off-again sickness showed classic signs of arsenic
poisoning. He said that when Napoleon was exhumed from his island
burial place and brought to Paris about 20 years after his death,
the body was remarkably well-preserved -- a possible result of
arsenic, which has preservative qualities and is often used by
taxidermists.
</P>
<P>
   Weider co-wrote 1982's ''The Murder of Napoleon,'' which
catapulted the arsenic theory into academic circles. In the book,
he claims the Count of Montholon -- a close friend who accompanied
him in exile -- owed a favor to the future Charles X and went to St.
Helena specifically to carry out the slow, systematic murder.
</P>
<P>
   But some toxicologists have pointed out that people who eat
large amounts of seafood have naturally high levels of arsenic in
their blood, and Napoleon, who lived on an island, likely made
seafood a staple of his diet. Another theory holds that the strands
of hair carefully guarded all those years were kept in a
preservative -- arsenic.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics of the arsenic theory turned down the invitation to
attend the discussion, held at Paris' Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Napoleon case is the second historic mystery to have
recaptured France's imagination in the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In April, scientists cracked one of the country's most enduring
puzzles by proving that an ailing boy who died in a Paris prison
more than 200 years ago was indeed the son of King Louis XVI and
Marie-Antoinette and heir to the French throne. Many had long
believed that the royal heir escaped and another child died in his
place to save official face during the unstable days of the French
Revolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1702 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
