<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Thursday, May 4, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   'I Love You' Virus Hits Computers
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The FBI says it has opened a criminal
investigation of a new software virus that spread quickly around
the world today, swamping U.S. computer networks with e-mails
entitled ''ILOVEYOU'' after crippling government and business
computers in Asia and Europe. FBI spokeswoman Debbie Weierman also
said in Washington that the bureau assessing the virus attack's
impact domestically and internationally. By midafternoon Eastern
time, a virus-scanning system provided on the Internet by the Trend
Micro computer security company had already detected almost 1.2
million infected computer files around the world, including more
than 900,000 in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Ends Down 67; Nasdaq Up 13
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks drifted to a mixed finish today after a
report of slowing productivity growth intensified worries that the
Federal Reserve will raise interest rates by as much as a
half-percentage point later this month. Blue chip stocks led the
decline. The Dow Jones industrial average was down 67.01 at
10,413.12 and the Nasdaq composite index was up 13.44 at 3,720.75.
Broader stock indicators were mixed. Stocks stalled after the Labor
Department reported that U.S. workers' productivity, a key measure
of future prosperity, rose at an annual rate of 2.4 percent the
first three months of this year. That marked a sharp slowdown from
the previous quarter, when productivity rose at an extremely sharp
6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   New York (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:
Dow Industrials:        10413.12  - 67.01
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1620  Declines 1281  Unchgd  466
NYSE Volume:         915,558,020
Most Active NYSE issue:         AT&AMP;T Corp38{   - 1\  
S&AMP;P 500:         1408.53  - 6.57
