Nasdaq Composite Index        3720.75  + 13.44
Gold(final) -    $279.60    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.
</P>
<P>
   Weather Hurts April Retail Sales
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Sales for many of the country's biggest
retailers did not live up to expectations in April. But analysts
were quick to note that cool weather rather than the gyrations of
Wall Street Stocks was responsible. Still, many say that a spending
slowdown will likely come later this year. Despite the strong labor
market, U.S. consumers will scale back their buying if interest
rates keep rising and the economy finally begins to slow its pace,
analysts said. Earlier this week, Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. retail
analyst George Strachan took about a dozen retailers off the firm's
recommended list in anticipation of slowing sales later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Productivity Rises at 2.4 Pct. Rate
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The productivity of U..S. workers rose at an
annual rate of 2.4 percent in the first three months of this year,
considerably less than the 3.5 percent growth economists had
expected. The figure announced by the Labor Department is likely to
accelerate the pace of Federal Reserve interest rate hikes in order
to fight inflation, according to Oscar Gonzalez, an economist at
John Hancock in Boston. He notes that the slower productivity
increase comes at a time when unit labor costs have risen more than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan Warns Banks On Risks
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said
today that banks may be turning complacent about risks in the
technology-flavored economy. In a speech to a banking conference,
Greenspan called such an attitude -- fueled by the record-breaking
economic expansion -- ''somewhat disquieting.'' Greenspan noted that
the legislation had greatly expanded the opportunities for U.S.
banks to get involved in merchant banking activities. In merchant
banking, a bank is allowed to buy stock in non-financial companies.
Greenspan said banks going into these new areas needed to have a
good understanding of the risks involved. The Fed chief, in his
speech and a follow-up question and answer period, did not make any
direct comments on current economic growth or the potential threat
of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner Exec Expects Resolution
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner Inc. chairman Gerald Levin dismissed
suggestions today that the company's spat with Disney over carriage
of the ABC network and other programming was related to Time
Warner's pending merger with America Online Inc. ''This is a
commercial dispute that has been going on for some time, well
before the announcement of the AOL-Time Warner merger,'' Levin said
in an interview with financial news network CNBC. Disney, which
opposes the merger, has accused Time Warner of wanting to put off a
deal on ABC for eight months in order to complete its combination
with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Penney Top Executive To Retire
</P>
<P>
   PLANO, Texas (AP) -- J.C. Penney Co. Inc.'s top executive will
step down by the end of the year, leaving the giant retailer as it
struggles to regain its footing in an increasingly competitive
marketplace. Penney said today that 58-year-old James E.
Oesterreicher, who joined the company in 1964 as a management
trainee, plans to retire as soon as his successor is in place,
which is expected by year's end. ''Penney has drifted sideways and
down for too many years,'' said Jeffrey Edelman, a retail analyst
for the investment firm PaineWebber. ''Changes have been made too
slowly. This could be a major turning point.'' Investors cheered
the news, sending Penney's shares up $1.37{ to $17.25 in afternoon
trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram Posts Wider Loss
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Seagram Co., the Canadian media and beverage
company, posted a wider loss in its third fiscal quarter today but
still beat Wall Street expectations. Seagram, owner of the
Universal movie and music studios, lost $265 million or 61 cents
for the three months ending March 31. Analysts had expected a loss
of 66 cents. In the same period a year ago, Seagram posted a loss
of $199 million, or 50 cents a share. Revenue rose 5 percent to
$3.38 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shell Earnings Double in 1st Quarter
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The Royal Dutch Shell Group of Cos. said today its
earnings nearly doubled in the first quarter thanks to higher crude
oil prices and stricter cost controls. The energy company reported
earnings of $3.34 billion in the January-March period, up from
$1.68 billion during the same period last year. The Anglo-Dutch oil
group said demand for crude continues to grow. Given the limited
excess capacity of many oil-producing countries, prices should
remain well above the company's minimum target of $14 per barrel,
it said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure Mounts on European Bank
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Pressure mounted today on the European
Central Bank to take action to boost the ailing euro, which this
week set off alarm bells after hitting two record lows in as many
days. The central bank has long maintained a hands-off policy on
exchange rates. But some analysts say the more the central bank
insists the euro doesn't need outside help, the further it seems to
fall. Billionaire U.S. financier George Soros entered the fray
today and urged the European Central Bank to step in immediately
and prop up the euro. The bank manages monetary policy for the 11
European nations that adopted the single currency at the start of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   European Stocks End Higher
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A combination of good corporate news, minimal
losses on Wall Street and a Bank of England decision to hold
interest rates steady nudged jittery European markets slightly
higher today. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index rose 1.01 points to
441.93. London's FTSE-100 Share Index rose 0.2 percent to 6,199.6
after the Bank of England kept interest rates on hold, against
expectations of a quarter-point hike. Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index
was 0.1 percent higher to 7,386.71, while the Paris CAC-40 Index
was up 0.87 percent to 6,491.74. Traders warned the market was
still perturbed, with volume low as investors held back ahead of
the release of key U.S. economic data tomorrow.
</P>
