<HEADLINE> Gold Rises on Inflation Fears  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE CARPENTER, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gold prices climbed Thursday on the Comex division of the New
York Mercantile Exchange, buoyed by producer buybacks and what some
experts said are rising inflation fears.
</P>
<P>
   Silver also rode gold's rally higher.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets, coffee percolated higher and wheat also grew.
</P>
<P>
   Gold has been bogged down well under $300 an ounce with the
exception of brief flurries of buying excitement last fall and this
spring. On Thursday, several factors pointed it upward in a second
straight session of short-covering, or the buying of futures to
balance previous sales.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Labor Department's report of a sharp first-quarter gain
in productivity, rising at an annual rate of 2.4 percent, renewed
concerns about inflation that traditionally send investors fleeing
into gold.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Australian gold producers made significant
purchases of the metal at what they deemed attractively low prices
of under $280 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   And investors who had sold gold ahead of the Swiss central bank
sales that began this week returned to the metal, encouraged by
positive early sale results.
</P>
<P>
   Still, gold couldn't muster impressive gains. June gold settled
up $2.10 at $281.20 an ounce after reaching a 16-day of $284. June
silver piggybacked on the rally, rising 9.8 cents to $5.146 per
ounce.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, gold is a bit of a moribund affair these
days,'' said Bill O'Neill, senior futures strategist for Merrill
Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said the rise reflected a consensus that the selloff
ahead of the Swiss bank sales was overdone. He disputed others'
view that inflation worries are involved in recent gains, saying
the metal's allure as a safe haven isn't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my view, gold is not serving as a monetary asset at all,''
the analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee prices jumped 3 percent on New York's Coffee, Sugar &AMP;
Cocoa Exchange on continued talk of a retention plan among Latin
producers. Market-watchers said some buying was spurred by talk
that Colombia, the world's No. 2 producer, might reduce its exports
by as much as 10 percent as part of the collective effort to force
coffee prices higher.
</P>
<P>
   July coffee rose 2.70 cents to 99.90 cents a pound after
reaching a high of $1.00\.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat futures bounced sharply higher on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid worries about dryness in U.S. and Canadian spring wheat
areas and eastern China, in addition to concerns about winter wheat
crop conditions in the central and Plains states.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial funds drove prices higher with purchases late in the
trading session.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery rose 4{ cents to $2.76{ a bushel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
