<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislators expected to begin adopting budget  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Both houses of the state Legislature
expected Thursday to finally begin adopting bills constituting the
2000-01 state budget, which is late for the 16th straight year.
</P>
<P>
   To show that they have reached consensus, Republican Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno and Democratic Assembly Speaker
Sheldon Silver enjoyed cones of ''Budget Nut Crunch'' ice cream --
made up of vanilla, caramel swirl and peanut butter pieces -- in
front of photographers at the Capitol. The snack was symbolic of
the leaders' habit in earlier years of working out disputes at an
ice cream parlor near the state Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki said the $77.5 billion budget for the fiscal
year that began April 1 represents nearly a 5 percent increase in
general fund spending -- money supported by taxpayers -- and just
under 6 percent in all funds from last year's spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   The last major hurdle for final passage of the budget appeared
to have been cleared Tuesday when the state leaders reached a deal
on a debt-reform plan that called for establishing a cap on new
debt and on debt service payments. Lawmakers agreed to statutorily
set the cap at 4 percent of personal income retroactive to April 1.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki announced Thursday that the debt reform plan will also
reduce from 40 years to 30 years the maximum length of time the
state can borrow money for. In addition, the state would also
institute a ban on using debt as a ''fiscal gimmick'' -- like the
state's Cuomo-era move of ''selling'' Attica prison to itself so it
could borrow against the value of the prison -- and restrict the use
of debt for capital purposes only.
</P>
<P>
   Another last-minute kink worked out Thursday involved the
withdrawal of a new interpretation of taxes on electricity by the
Pataki administration that big non-manufacturing users of power
like supermarkets complained could cost them $45 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   The new budget would include $1.2 billion in tax-cut initiatives
over five years, with the pricetag for the first year at less than
$100 million. Under the deal, the state's gross receipts tax on
energy would be eliminated for large manufacturers and reduced for
small manufacturers and residential ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   Also included in the budget would be a record $1.2 billion
increase in public school aid to $13.2 billion, the highest level
in state history. In higher education, $680 million would be spent
on an expanded Tuition Assistance Program.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the state's prescription drug program for senior
citizens, ''EPIC,'' would be expanded from 115,000 to about 215,000
enrollees within three years. The starting date of the expansion
was set for Jan. 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Coinciding with budget adoption would be the implementation of a
five-year $17.1 billion bridge- and road-building program and a
$17.1 billion New York City-area mass transit improvement program.
</P>
<P>
   The final budget total was closer to Pataki and the
Republican-led Senate's spending plans. The governor had proposed a
budget of $76.8 billion and the Senate approved spending $500
million more. Democrats who dominate the Assembly had passed a
resolution for a $78.2 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   Though 34 days late as of Thursday, lawmakers were considering
the new budget as being almost on time. Last year, the budget
wasn't finished until Aug. 4, only hours before it would have
become the latest budget in state history.
</P>
<P>
   Following budget adoption, lawmakers would resume receiving
their paychecks, which had been withheld since their first payday
in the new fiscal year on April 12. Under legislation approved at
the end of 1998, lawmakers' pay is suspended for as long as the
budget is late.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators get all their pay back, without interest, when
budget adoption is completed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 1723 </TRAILER>
