<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILOVENEWYORK: Virus causes problems for state  </HEADLINE>
With AM-Computer Love Bug
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The fast-replicating ''ILOVEYOU'' computer
virus forced the emergency shutdown of e-mail servers at a number
of New York state agencies Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The bug was spreading throughout the United State after wreaking
havoc in Asia and Europe. If a contaminated attachment is opened,
the message spreads the virus to other e-mail addresses in the
victim's address book.
</P>
<P>
   Special notices were sent to every state agency Thursday morning
after the virus was detected, and six agencies were able to delete
it, said William Pelgrin, executive deputy commissioner for the
state Office for Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Eight other agency servers hit with the virus were turned off,
Pelgrin said. The agencies affected were: Parks and Recreation,
Alcoholism and Substance Abuse Services, Aging, the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority, the Human Service Application Center,
Probation and Emergency Management. The server shared by the state
Department of Motor Vehicles and the Office for Technology also was
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Servers in those agencies were being fitted late Thursday
afternoon with electronic ''patches'' to alleviate the problem,
Pelgrin said.
</P>
<P>
   The mail server at the Small Business Development Center in
Albany also was shut down. Information specialist Darrin Conroy
said the virus struck his computer, and he didn't want it to spread
any further.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a bit of a worry right now that we've pushed it along
more than we needed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The virus also appeared at the State University of New York,
which administers the business center. The SUNY School of
Environmental Science and Forestry was forced to temporarily take
down its server.
</P>
<P>
   The computer bug showed up at Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate
campaign headquarters in New York City this morning.
</P>
<P>
   It was also quickly spotted in the New York City Board of
Education network, which connects some 1100 schools serving more
than a million students.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Tung, the board's executive director, ordered the system
shut down soon after spotting it Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''We used the good old fashioned telephone,'' said Margie
Seinberg, spokeswoman for the board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 1727 </TRAILER>
