<DOCNO> APW20000504.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Govt. Said To Pass on Small Ad Firms  </HEADLINE>
By NEDRA PICKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Only a tiny fraction of federal government
advertising dollars go to small agencies owned by women and
minorities, according to a congressional report.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is another form of discrimination,'' said Rep. Carolyn
Cheeks Kilpatrick, a Michigan Democrat who requested the study by
the General Accounting Office.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO found that while the government's advertising budget
increased nearly fourfold between 1995 and 1998, the portion going
to small firms owned by women and ethnic minorities has fallen to
less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kilpatrick, who was joined at a Capitol Hill news conference by
Rep. Robert Menendez, D-N.J., Rep. James Clyburn, D-S.C., and
advertising industry groups, said congressional hearings or a
lawsuit are options being discussed to address the situation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers said things may get worse with the Army's plan to
award contracts only to large firms handling at least $350 million
in billings. The Army spends about $110 million a year on
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ''The requirements seem to be tailored to those already in the
system,'' said Clyburn, chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus.
''If that is happening, those who are outside the system, no matter
how talented they may be, will never get in.''
</P>
<P>
   The GAO found that in fiscal 1998, only $1.2 million of the
$368-million federal advertising budget was awarded to
minority-owned firms with less than $5 million in annual receipts.
Agencies owned by women -- both minorities and nonminorities --
received $1.7 million in contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when the advertising budget was only $96 million, about
$3 million in contracts were awarded to minority-owned firms.
Women-owned firms received roughly the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not examine the value of federal contracts to
larger agencies owned by women and minorities. The American
Advertising Federation said Thursday that it would survey larger
minority-owned agencies about their federal contracts and issue a
report by Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Small Business Act requires that 5 percent of federal
contracts be given to small women- and minority-owned businesses,
but there are no requirements for specific industries such as
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Menendez said it may be time to change the law.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you consider the growth minority firms have had in the ad
and media fields and the growing importance of reaching minority
audiences ... it makes no sense that the number of government
contracts to these firms would actually be in steep decline,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   GAO investigators plan another review to examine how contracts
are solicited.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.gao.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1730 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kent State Marks 1970 Shootings  </HEADLINE>
By AMY BETH GRAVES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENT, Ohio (AP) -- As thousands of people watched, a bell tolled
on the Kent State University campus Thursday at 12:24 p.m., marking
the exact moment National Guardsmen opened fire 30 years ago on
antiwar protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The Victory Bell sounded 15 times: once for each of the four
students killed and nine wounded at Kent State and once each for
the two students killed at Jackson State University in Mississippi
10 days later.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings on May 4, 1970, stunned the nation and galvanized
the anti-war movement.
</P>
<P>
   The 30th anniversary brought the nine survivors back to the
campus for the first time in those three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know why this happened to us. We don't know who said,
'Shoot.' We don't know when they said it or why,'' said Joseph
Lewis, now 48 and living in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   The anniversary also included a candlelight march that began on
the anniversary's eve and continued with an overnight vigil at the
parking lot where Allison Krause, Sandy Scheuer, Jeffery Miller and
William Schroeder were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Kent State shootings happened after days of student protests
against the Vietnam War and the burning of the campus Army ROTC
building. The National Guard was sent in to quell the disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   Guardsmen fired at least 61 shots in a 13-second burst, hitting
protesters, bystanders and students walking to class at a distance.
Some Guardsmen said they felt their lives were in danger.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis said Guardsmen shot at him for no reason.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't do anything wrong. People who did something wrong
were individuals of the Ohio National Guard who shot and killed
them and shot and wounded us deliberately,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors continued to blame the shooting on then-Gov. James
Rhodes, who ordered the troops on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to remember Rhodes virtually beat on the table,
saying he was going to keep this university open and all the
universities in Ohio,'' said Dean Kahler, a history and government
teacher in Nelsonville, Ohio, paralyzed from the waist down because
of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes has expressed regret over the shootings but maintains
that he had to send troops to Kent State.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a terrible thing,'' Rhodes, now 90, told The Columbus
Dispatch. ''But no one plans a train wreck, either. It just
happened. And life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania death-row inmate Mumia Abu-Jamal gave a taped
3{-minute speech during the ceremonies, speaking about what he
called government-backed killings in war, during civil rights
protests and at prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kent State teaches that a so-called free society will
slaughter students who are exercising their alleged constitutional
right of demonstrating for peace and give awards to the killers and
do so with impunity,'' said Abu-Jamal, who has claimed he was
falsely convicted in the 1991 slaying of a Philadelphia police
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Four students protested during the speech. They held up signs
saying, ''Say no to cop killers and yes to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There's just a time and place for that. This isn't it,'' said
Andrew Muck, a 20-year-old sophomore. ''Originally, it was a day of
mourning and now they've turned it into a leftist statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, dozens of people wandered through the parking
lot where the students were killed, snapping pictures and reading
messages scrawled in chalk.
</P>
<P>
   A person stood quietly at each of the spots where the four
students fell, now marked with granite borders and waist-high lamp
posts.
</P>
<P>
   One chalk message read: ''Allison, you've taught us so much
about ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
