<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruff Testifies About E-Mail Flap  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former White House counsel Charles Ruff
conceded Thursday he may have failed to aggressively pursue an
e-mail foul-up that kept his staff from properly reviewing messages
under subpoena. But he denied there was a cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   ''The buck stops with me,'' Ruff told the House Government
Reform Committee. ''I am willing to suffer the embarrassment'' for
any oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said he is unable to recall who he directed to conduct a
limited test of the e-mail system in June 1998 when he was first
told that many messages were not being properly archived.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't know who you asked to conduct the search?'' asked a
seemingly incredulous committee chairman, Dan Burton, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can vouch for you this much,'' Ruff said. ''I know a search
was being done'' by ''one or more members of my staff. If I knew
who that was I would tell you who that was. But I do not recall.''
</P>
<P>
   Testifying with Ruff, his former deputy, ex-White House lawyer
Cheryl Mills, said she wasn't overseeing the test and couldn't
recall much of the episode, though she said her boss had told her
of the e-mail problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said he concluded the ''glitch'' was not affecting document
production to investigators because a subordinate found that all
the e-mails recovered in a limited test were duplicates of ones
that had already been turned over to prosecutor Kenneth Starr in
the Monica Lewinsky inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ''I candidly put it aside and went on to other matters,'' Ruff
said of his handling of the e-mail problem.
</P>
<P>
   Burton asked Ruff why only a limited search for e-mails in the
Lewinsky affair was conducted rather than a broader search for mail
in the campaign fund-raising inquiry, the Whitewater probe and
other investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ''My immediate focus was'' on the subpoena from Starr's office,
Ruff replied. ''If I had concluded there was a broader-ranging
problem, I obviously would have done something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If in fact we failed ... it was by inadvertence and
unintentional,'' Ruff said. ''I am willing to suffer the
embarrassment if I failed to adequately pursue the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''Never ... did anyone on my staff seek to ... cover up any
document production,'' said Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Any suggestion that the White House has been ''less than
forthcoming, I submit, is simply flat-out wrong,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying later in the day, the current White House counsel,
Beth Nolan, said ''we do not know ... who asked for the search to
be done'' in 1998 -- the limited action that apparently lulled
presidential lawyers into thinking there was no problem. In fact,
at least 246,000 e-mails from mid-1996 to late 1998 were never
archived and are only now being searched to see if they relate to
various investigations.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's ranking Democrat, Henry Waxman of California,
faulted Ruff for inattention to detail but said Burton and other
committee Republicans are suggesting a cover-up when ''none of it
is true.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Ruff and others in the White House counsel's office simply
did a bad job in responding to the system defect that resulted in
missing e-mails,'' Waxman said. ''An embarrassing lapse of who was
doing what is a lot different than criminal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills said that in its zeal to investigate the White House, the
Republican-controlled Congress is ignoring important social issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could spend your time making the lives of the individuals
you serve better, as opposed to tearing down the staff of a
president with whose vision and policies you disagree,'' Mills
testified.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Mills, Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., said he
was outraged with ''the ethical and moral minimalism by this White
House's failure to disclose facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton said Mills ''didn't return our phone calls ... and said
she was too busy to give us an interview. ... Her lack of
cooperation really makes me ask why she is trying to hide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
