<HEADLINE> Leading lawmakers applaud and criticize 2000 session  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Hours after the 12-week Legislative
session came to a close, Democratic leaders on Thursday lauded a
package of reform bills while their GOP rivals said two bills don't
do enough and a third should be quashed by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had an excellent session,'' said House Speaker Moira Lyons,
D-Stamford. ''The session was really being driven by a race against
time. In that race against time, we had a goal of delivering on
major issues and major topics.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. John G. Rowland has already signed bills to
abolish the sheriffs system and revamp the state treasurer's
office. He's expected to announce Friday whether he will sign a
campaign finance reform bill.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff reform bill puts deputies under state agency
control, but the changes hinge on voter approval of a
constitutional amendment to wipe the office of sheriff from the
state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bill itself is good,'' said House Minority Leader Robert
Ward. ''But we're disappointed that Democrats tied that to a
referendum.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are concerned that the eight county sheriffs will
stage a campaign urging voters to reject the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   But Lyons said reform will prevail.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not even God can save the sheriffs,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders also gave lukewarm support to the treasurer
reform law, which they said should have included more controls over
state pension investments.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the campaign finance reform bill, which sets
limits on how much money political candidates could spend on their
races and allows campaigns to be paid for with tax dollars, will
reduce the impact of private money on politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should stop fighting it and just do it,'' said House
Majority Leader David Pudlin, D-New Britain.
</P>
<P>
   On a report card grading Democrats for the 2000 legislative
session which ended at midnight Wednesday, the House Republicans
gave the campaign finance reform bill an ''F.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward, R-Northford, called the bill ''a waste of taxpayer
money,'' and wants Rowland to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans gave high marks to Democrats for their support
of $171 million in tax cuts. On July 1, the gas tax will be cut 7
cents and there will be more tax breaks on clothing purchases.
Hospitals and businesses are also getting tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties praised the approval of spending $455 million on
the Adriaen's Landing development project that promises to
revitalize downtown Hartford and build a 40,000-seat stadium in
East Hartford for the University of Connecticut. Republicans and
Democrats also stood by their approval of pay raises for lawmakers
and constitutional officers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our top priorities were to cut the gas tax, to make reductions
in the sales tax and we met those priorities and we did it with a
balanced budget,'' Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also criticized Democrats for their management of
the session. The General Assembly, which is controlled by Democrats
in the House and Senate, failed to pass a bill needed to enact a
portion of the state's $12.3 billion budget pertaining to the
Department of Social Services. Lawmakers will have to come back for
a special session to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never seen a session quite like this,'' said Senate
Minority Leader Adela Eads, R-Kent. ''If we started earlier and on
time, we could have done more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
