<HEADLINE> Cardinal wanted to be buried as a people's priest, without militaryhonors  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- America's most powerful Roman Catholic wanted to
be buried as ''a priest for all the people'' -- rather than honored
for his years as a military chaplain and Navy rear admiral.
</P>
<P>
   Those simple wishes will be followed during the four days of
funeral rites for Cardinal John O'Connor, Archdiocese spokesman Joe
Zwilling said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing simple about the mammoth series of
religious events which are being planned in what Zwilling described
as a church ''command center.''
</P>
<P>
   So many people want to attend Monday's funeral Mass at St.
Patrick's Cathedral -- including first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton --
that close to 3,000 tickets were being issued. Requests were
pouring in ''by the hundreds'' on Thursday, said Zwilling.
</P>
<P>
   Phones were clogged at the archdiocesan offices on Manhattan's
East Side.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we were able to, I'm sure we could fill Yankee Stadium
three times over,'' the spokesman told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   With the cardinal's body in a Madison Avenue funeral home, the
first official sign of mourning appeared at the Fifth Avenue
cathedral that is the seat of the archbishop of New York.
</P>
<P>
   As noon bells tolled, firefighters from Ladder Co. 35 fastened
black and purple bunting above the huge bronze portals.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, O'Connor's body was to be brought from the
Frank E. Campbell Funeral Chapel to the cathedral's entrance. ''It
will be greeted, it will be blessed, prayers will be said over the
body,'' Zwilling said. ''It's a very special rite in which the
archbishop is welcomed back to his church.''
</P>
<P>
   The coffin will then be taken up the aisle, opened and placed in
the sanctuary in front of the main altar, where the public can walk
by and pay its respects; time also will be set aside for private
viewing. The cardinal's body will lie in state all day Saturday and
Sunday near his now empty chair -- the official archbishop's
''cathedra.''
</P>
<P>
   Regular Masses were to be celebrated in the presence of the
cardinal's remains. He is to be interred in the crypt under the
cathedral's altar, where all the previous archbishops of New York
are buried.
</P>
<P>
   As he lay dying, the cardinal -- who served 27 years as a
military chaplain and was a retired Navy rear admiral --
''specifically requested that there be no military honors at his
funeral. He wanted the emphasis to be placed on his priesthood,''
Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, the cathedral will be closed to prepare the
body for burial, and the coffin will be shut and placed in the
center aisle during the funeral Mass expected to last at least two
hours.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the public, special guests will include priests
and bishops to be seated in the sanctuary, as well as a list of
other dignitaries still being compiled Thursday, Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor asked that various people close to him and the church
deliver remarks at services over the weekend. For a Friday evening
Mass, the congregation will include members of traditional Catholic
organizations -- the Order of Malta, the Order of the Holy Sepulchre
and the Knights of Columbus and Columbiettes.
</P>
<P>
   Children, youth and handicapped people -- whom O'Connor
especially loved and noticed -- were invited to an early Saturday
afternoon service. Late-afternoon vespers were to be followed by a
reciting of the rosary with members of the Legion of Mary.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday evening, a prayer service is dedicated to the city's
multi-ethnic Catholic population, especially the large number of
Hispanics who had inspired O'Connor to learn Spanish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 1740 </TRAILER>
