<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lift Problem Reported in Kenya Crash  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN LINNEE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- The alarm that sounded after a doomed
Kenyan Airways Airbus took off Jan. 30 from Abidjan could give
investigators a clue as to what caused the plane to crash seconds
later, killing 169 people, an investigation report obtained
Thursday said.
</P>
<P>
   An alarm, called an ''aural stall warning,'' sounded in the
cockpit 1.7 seconds after the crew had received the go ahead to
raise the landing gear, said the April 28 report by France-based
Airbus Industrie, which was tabled in Parliament on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The warning sounded for 21.5 seconds while the aircraft
''transitioned from climb to descent.'' The crew then shut it off
manually at between 100 feet and 50 feet, or 3.3 seconds before the
first sound of impact. The information was captured by the cockpit
voice recorder, one of the two ''black boxes'' carried to record
flight information.
</P>
<P>
   The stall alarm occurs when the flow of air over the wings is
not sufficient to keep the aircraft aloft. When this happens, the
aircraft starts shaking.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors reported that the aircraft was shaking violently
before it smacked into the ocean in the early morning darkness.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of air flow over the wings is determined, in part, by
the speed the aircraft builds up before becoming airborne.
</P>
<P>
   The investigating committee determined, though, that engine
speeds were consistent with thrust settings and remained so until
the aircraft's impact with the sea.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said the investigation would continue at the
crash site to examine wreckage on the ocean floor and, if
necessary, recover key parts of the wreckage, including the engine.
</P>
<P>
   The flight data recorder contained no information, the Airbus
report said.
</P>
<P>
   Nairobi-bound Flight 431, which had originated Jan. 29 in
Nairobi, had been scheduled to stop in Lagos, Nigeria, but bad
weather forced it to fly on to Abidjan's Felix Houphouet Boigny
International Airport. It was returning to Nairobi when it plunged
300 feet into the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Ten people survived the crash. Critics claimed more people might
have been saved had the rescue operation been more professional.
Most of the survivors were pulled in by volunteers who raced to the
scene in private boats, and one survivor swam to shore.
</P>
<P>
   The Airbus technical report said ''at this stage of the
investigation, the committee forsee no immediate actions to be
taken on the A310 fleet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1740 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DeLay: Racketeering Suit 'Pathetic'  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, the target of a
federal racketeering lawsuit by Democrats, on Thursday called the
efforts of his detractors ''pretty pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They'll do anything, lie, cheat and steal, to get back the
House,'' the Texas Republican told reporters at the National Press
Club. ''They're showing this desperation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''First of all, I'm not stupid,'' DeLay said in denying the
allegations. ''Every step I take is covered by lawyers. I know that
they're after me.''
</P>
<P>
   However, John Del Cecato, spokesman for the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, responded: ''The lawsuit is in
the judge's hands. We're confident that there is sufficient
evidence to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, the party had accused DeLay of overseeing an
organization that extorts campaign contributions and evades federal
disclosure requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In filing the lawsuit, Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., who chairs
the Democratic campaign committee, accused DeLay of ''hammering
contributors for money, threatening to punish those who decline and
setting up a shadow party structure outside public view and our
laws ...''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cited newspaper clippings and magazine articles but
admitted they had no independent proof of their claims. They said
they hope to question DeLay's associates as the lawsuit proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit comes at a time when Republicans are trying to make
a campaign issue of Vice President Al Gore's controversial
fund-raising activities in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay is accused of threatening to ''withhold favorable action''
on legislation unless donors contributed to the Republican Party.
The money was then channeled to a network of political
organizations, independent from traditional GOP groups, that are
not registered under federal election law and don't report their
donors, the lawsuit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says DeLay's operation directs GOP donors to
contribute to these organizations, thus evading reporting
requirements that would otherwise apply.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations were identified as the U.S. Family Network,
the Republican Majority Issues Committee and Americans for Economic
Growth. The DeLay associates involved in their operation were named
as Ed Buckham, his former chief of staff; Karl Gallant and Jim
Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said independent political groups ''have been used by the
left for many years.'' The lawsuit ''just shows how hypocritical
they (Democrats) are,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came after a speech in which Delay said Americans
were in the midst of a ''cultural coup d'etat -- a revolution
launched by a privileged few who are determined to discredit and,
ultimately, replace core American traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLay predicted that if Republicans keep the majority and Texas
Gov. George W. Bush wins the White House, lawmakers will attach a
provision to federal education spending ''that outlaws denying any
American ... the benefit of such spending on the basis of their
religious belief or identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a provision would directly attack complaints about
GOP-backed plans for school vouchers and education savings
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay also said he would support a second proposal to ensure
that schools receiving federal funding do not prevent students from
participating in private or voluntary prayer or religious activity.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must transform our resistance into an aggressive
counterattack,'' DeLay said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
