<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-NJ--Justice Nominated, 1st Ld-Writethru,490  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Gov. Christie Whitman on Thursday nominated
former Attorney General James R. Zazzali, a Democrat, to the state
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed by the state Senate, which appears likely, Zazzali
will become the governor's sixth appointee to the seven-member
court. He would replace Associate Justice Daniel O'Hern, who
reaches the mandatory retirement age of 70 on May 23.
</P>
<P>
   Senators who will handle his nomination were immediately
complimentary of the governor's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Most important among these would be Sen. John Bennett,
R-Monmouth, who represents the district where Zazzali lives and so
could exercise ''senatorial courtesy'' to single-handedly hold up
his nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, who also is the Senate GOP majority leader, said
Zazzali would be a ''tremendous asset to the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Rae Hutton, a spokeswoman for Senate President Donald
DiFrancesco, said the senator supports the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Gormley, R-Atlantic, chairman of the Judiciary
committee, said, ''I've known him for years. He has a good
reputation. I think that on its face, it appears to be a fine
nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Richard Codey, D-Essex, the leader of the Democratic
minority, issued a news statement calling Zazzali ''a compassionate
individual with a keen legal mind and a fine record in law
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she was drawn to Zazzali because of his integrity,
his reputation and his vast experience as a practicing attorney,
saying he provided a good blend with her other nominees: two
appellate court judges and three of her cabinet officers.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali was a commissioner on the State Commission of
Investigation from 1984 to 1994, including a period as chairman.
The SCI is an independent office created by the Legislature to
examine and issue written reports on corruption and policy
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali served as attorney general for 10 months at the end of
former Gov. Brendan Byrne's term in 1981 and 1982. He also served
as general counsel to the New Jersey Sports and Exposition
Authority under Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman last year named Zazzali to a search committee to find
candidates for State Police superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali also headed a coalition of six former state attorneys
general who supported former Attorney General Peter Verniero's
hotly contested nomination to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali, of Rumson, is a partner in the Newark law firm Zazzali,
Zazzali, Fagella &AMP; Nowak with his brother, Andrew Zazzali. He
graduated from Georgetown University in 1958 and earned a law
degree there in 1962, after which he served as an assistant
prosecutor in Essex County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
