<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deadline Lifted To Buy Bestfoods  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- International consumer products conglomerate
Unilever on Thursday removed a deadline imposed earlier on U.S.
food company Bestfoods to accept Unilever's $18.4 billion buyout
offer.
</P>
<P>
   The action by Unilever, the owner of Lipton teas, Vaseline and
Pepsodent toothpaste, essentially leaves the next move up to
Bestfoods.
</P>
<P>
   ''While our proposal remains on the table, the deadline is no
longer applicable. We feel the offer is very compelling, and we
remain very willing and eager to dialogue with Bestfoods,'' said
Unilever spokesman John Gould.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever chief executive Niall FitzGerald said Wednesday that
Bestfoods had until 5 p.m. Thursday to respond to the offer. If
Bestfoods let the deadline pass, Unilever might then consider
taking the proposal directly to Bestfood shareholders in a hostile
takeover, Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   But those plans are now on hold.
</P>
<P>
   A Bestfoods spokeswoman said Bestfoods' position hasn't changed
since the Englewood Cliffs, N.J.,-based maker of Hellmann's
mayonnaise and Skippy peanut butter rejected Unilever's $66 a share
bid on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods' shares continued to climb Thursday in the wake of the
offer from the Anglo-Dutch company. Investors pushed the stock up
83 cents to $62.08 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has soared 25 percent since Tuesday, when Bestfoods
announced it was a takeover target.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever's stock rose slightly Thursday, climbing 6\ cents to
$43.18}, after falling $2.31\, or 5 percent, on Wednesday on the
NYSE.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers believe Unilever will sweeten its bid, and that a
deal could be completed as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the companies will move from public rhetoric to
private negotiations and that a deal will be struck somewhere in
the low $70s some time next week,'' said PaineWebber analyst John
O'Neil.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would boost the value of the deal into the $20
billion range, far greater than the last food acquisition of this
magnitude, the $5.8 billion purchase of Pillsbury Co. by the
British distiller Grand Metropolitan in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil said Bestfoods has been able to play hardball with
Unilever for one simple reason: ''They have the best food business
of any domestic company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst agreed with Bestfoods' assertion that the $66 a
share was too low. But Bestfoods executives may have trouble
justifying to shareholders potential objections to an offer of more
than $70 a share, O'Neil said.
</P>
<P>
   ''At north of $70 a share, they're going to have a hard time
saying no,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods chairman and chief executive C.R. Shoemate has said in
interviews since the Unilever offer became public that he would
prefer to keep Bestfoods independent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.unilever.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bestfoods.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
