<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Futures Mostly Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Gasoline futures were up 2 percent Thursday on
the New York Mercantile Exchange on persistent supply concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Crude and heating oil made small gains, while natural gas
retreated a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Unleaded gasoline gained on concerns that inventories are low
and refiners will come up short in the peak summer driving season.
</P>
<P>
   June unleaded gasoline rose 1.81 cent to 90.88 cents a gallon;
light, sweet crude for June delivery settled up 23 cents at $26.98
a barrel; June heating oil was up .47 cent to 68.20 a gallon; June
natural gas fell 1.9 cent to $3.107 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   On the International Petroleum Exchange in London, Brent crude
from the North Sea rose 15 cents to $25.15 a barrel.
</P>
</TEXT>
