<DOCNO> APW20000504.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro hits another low, then moves up; yen stronger against dollar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro fell to its second-straight record low
against the dollar Thursday, but then moved slightly higher amid
rumors the European Central Bank might soon intervene to buoy the
currency.
</P>
<P>
   In New York trading, the euro was quoted at 88.99 cents,
compared with a late rate of 89.61 cents on Wednesday. Early in the
day on Thursday, the euro fell as low as 88.45 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 108.20 Japanese yen, down from
109.17 yen late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has been battered over the last week amid frustration
that European authorities have not taken sufficient action to boost
the ailing currency, which debuted in January 1999 and is used by
11 European nations.
</P>
<P>
   But rumors Thursday that the European Central Bank may soon
intervene by buying euros and selling off dollars helped prop up
the fledgling currency.
</P>
<P>
   One analyst, however, said Thursday it was ''ridiculous'' to
link the rumor of central bank intervention with the euro's slight
bounce back on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rumors or stories like that are ridiculous,'' said David
Solin, a partner in Foreign Exchange Analytics of Essex, Conn. ''I
don't think anyone in the market believes there will be
intervention. It's clear they have no interest in doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England on Thursday said it would not raise interest
rates, triggering a selloff of sterling and some large buying of
the yen, according to Solin. That caused the dollar to slip against
the Japanese currency in light trading Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they expect trading against the yen to remain slow
on Friday. Japanese markets have been closed since Wednesday for
national holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 1.7387 Swiss francs, up from
1.7226 Swiss francs, and 1.4976 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4932.
The British pound dropped to $1.5418, down from $1.5625.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.1965 German
marks, up from 2.1826; 7.3666 French francs, up from 7.3201; and
2174.49 Italian lire, up from 2160.77.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1808 </TRAILER>
