<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Cautiously Opposes Iran Trial  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The mother of a Jew accused of spying and on
trial in Iran pressed her hand on one of the massive stone blocks
of the Western Wall, Judaism's holiest site, and prayed.
</P>
<P>
   The woman came Thursday to a prayer vigil here for her son, Dani
Tefilin. She sobbed loudly as his name was read aloud.
</P>
<P>
   But she will not speak publicly about him. She is afraid any
public action could backfire in attempts to help him and 12 other
Iranian Jews accused of spying for the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   Such caution is widespread here: Israel is torn between
calculated silence and angry protest in trying to help the Iranian
Jews, three of whom have confessed to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have made the release of the Jews a top
priority, dismissing the confessions as a sham and the charges as
pure fiction. But they are reluctant to speak out, fearing for the
lives of the accused.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Iranian Jewish community gathered Thursday for
the prayer vigil at the Western Wall, the last remnant of the
ancient Jewish Temple. They shooed journalists away from Tefilin's
mother, who was wearing a black-and-white checkered head scarf.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't you understand, by talking to her you are putting (the
prisoners) at risk?'' said Anat, a relative of the Tefilin family.
She would only give her first name.
</P>
<P>
   Some Iranian Jews in Israel are pressing their government to
play a more visible role, but they are aware of the danger of a
high-profile protest from the Jewish state, Iran's sworn enemy.
''We don't want to give a weapon to the Iranian authorities,'' said
Moshe Katsav, an Israeli lawmaker born in Iran who attended the
prayer vigil along with about 600 people.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the defendants could face the death penalty, the
maximum punishment for passing secret information that damages
national security. Two Jews were hanged three years ago in Iran on
similar charges.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers for the Jewish defendants have questioned the
validity of the confessions and criticized the court, in which the
judge acts as prosecutor and judge. The United States and European
countries also have questioned the fairness of the closed-door
proceedings in the southern Iranian city of Shiraz.
</P>
<P>
   Menashe Amir, who directs Israel Radio's Persian-language
service program, said Thursday it was clear that Tefilin, the first
defendant to confess, was not speaking freely when he was paraded
on Iranian state television saying he had received espionage
training in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was not his real voice,'' Amir said. ''He talked in a
Muslim way, in a Tehrani way and it was not his real voice. I'm
sure all he said was dictated and recited by him for the TV
appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran's dwindling Jewish community, estimated at about 22,000
people, remains the Middle East's largest outside Israel despite
massive emigration. In Israel, some 250,000 Jews of Iranian origin
live as a tightly-knit community.
</P>
<P>
   Despite fears that too much public attention could harm their
fellow Jews on trial, members of the community said they had no
choice but to come out and protest.
</P>
<P>
   Said Motke Rahimi, who helped organize Thursday's vigil: ''The
only sin of those arrested was that they were Jews.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1808 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
