<DOCNO> APW20000504.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suns Practicing For Two Opponents  </HEADLINE>
By MEL REISNER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Kevin Johnson calls it being politically correct.
Luc Longley doesn't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   They're talking about the Phoenix Suns' no-favorite stance on
the Los Angeles Lakers and Sacramento Kings, who are playing for
the right to meet the Suns in the second round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and Kings were tied in their best-of-five series with
the deciding game set for Friday night. The winner advances to play
the Suns in Game 1 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix was 4-0 against the Kings during the regular season and
0-4 against the Lakers, who have won 16 of the last 19 games in the
rivalry. But Phoenix coach Scott Skiles said Thursday he's putting
equal weight on preparing for both.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to work on our own stuff and, as a staff, prepare
them both ways,'' Skiles said. ''It would be foolish to full-bore
prepare for one team or the other right now, and yet there are some
what I'll call generic things that both teams do, and we can work
on those without getting specific.''
</P>
<P>
   Longley, on the other hand, has been influenced by Shaquille
O'Neal's 33.0 point average against him and Phoenix's other
centers. He believes at least four more games against Los Angeles
and O'Neal are in the Suns' future.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the Lakers will win,'' Longley said. ''We didn't
address that at all in terms of on-court preparation, but it's hard
not to expect that. But, stranger things have happened. First
round, Game 5 -- first seeds have been knocked out before.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been five years since the Suns reached the second round.
They swept Portland in the first round and then had to wait a week
before getting Houston in the second round. The Rockets eliminated
them in a tense, seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who ended nearly two years of retirement to rejoin the
Suns on March 25 after Jason Kidd broke his ankle, is the only
current Phoenix player who was on that 1994-95 roster. But he
doesn't believe his teammates need his perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ''These guys are excited,'' he said. ''I mean, everybody is
biting at the bit and they're ready to get going, so there's not a
lot I need to share.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his preference in a next-round opponent, Johnson
smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let me give you some political correctness here,'' Johnson
said. ''I certainly would like to play the LA Lakers on hand,
because you want to be able to beat the best team in basketball. On
the other hand, I'm from Sacramento, and it would be nice to take a
couple of road trips up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd broke his left ankle on March 22. He sat out the first
three games of the first round while the Suns took a 2-1 lead over
San Antonio, then returned in dramatic fashion to play 31 minutes
Tuesday night as the Suns beat the defending champions 89-78.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Kidd was feeling no ill effects in bones
strengthened by the insertion of three titanium screws.
</P>
<P>
   ''He looks 100 percent,'' Skiles said. ''He's doing what
everybody else is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd said he's ready for anything he needs to do to get the Suns
into the Western Conference finals. He doesn't plan to watch much
of the Kings-Lakers game, but not because he isn't interested.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe I'll tune in and find out who won,'' Kidd said. ''You
don't really want to sit there and start wishing, you know, 'Make a
shot.' Whoever wins wins, and that's who we'll play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
