<HEADLINE> Minn. Firefighters Subdue Wildfire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOK, Minn. (AP) -- Firefighters using helicopters and bulldozers
subdued a wildfire Thursday that was advancing on a popular camping
and canoeing area strewn with dry, fallen trees along the Canadian
border.
</P>
<P>
   ''We threw everything we had at it to make sure it did not get
to any of the blowdown area,'' said George Meadows, a spokesman
with the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources. Meadows said
the blaze was expected to be fully contained by Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze started Wednesday afternoon and burned more than 1,200
acres.
</P>
<P>
   The flames came to within four miles of the 600,000-acre
Boundary Waters Canoe Area, which has become a tinderbox since a
windstorm last July blew down millions of trees.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters battled the blaze on Wednesday and Thursday with
air tankers, helicopters and bulldozers. They got a break Thursday
when winds that had gusted to 35 mph dropped to 10 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The wilderness area is a major tourist destination, drawing
250,000 people annually. During the summer, it attracts 6,000 to
12,000 visitors a day.
</P>
</TEXT>
