<DOCNO> APW20000504.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies 'Deal' in Lockerbie Case  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A State Department official on Thursday denied
allegations that the United States made a deal with Libyan leader
Moammar Gadhafi that might sway the outcome of the Lockerbie
bombing trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can say with complete confidence that there is no deal,''
Ronald E. Neumann, an assistant secretary of state, told a Senate
Foreign Relations subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi said Wednesday in an interview with a British television
station that he had made an ''agreement'' with the United States
and Britain. In turning the suspects over for trial, he said, the
court will not raise questions about Libyan government involvement
in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The agreement is to try these two suspects ... these two
suspects only,'' Gadhafi said.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing questioning overall U.S. policy toward Libya,
Neumann was asked Thursday about Gadhafi's statement and answered,
''I haven't a clue what Col. Gadhafi is talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Pan Am Flight 103 victims also say Gadhafi was told
his government would be spared further embarrassment in the trial
or that higher ups in his government would not be drawn into the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by senators, Neumann repeated several times
that no such deal had been made.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States engaged in no negotiations and placed no
restrictions on the prosecutors' freedom to follow the evidence,''
Neumann said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Scottish trial in the Netherlands will be a genuine
criminal proceeding ... and the prosecution will follow the
evidence wherever it leads.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who suspect a deal say details were laid out in a letter
to Gadhafi from U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, which Annan has
refused to release publicly or to a member of congress who asked
for it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have some suspicion that the Secretary General ... may well
have told Col. Gadhafi that he need not fear from this trial ... it
will not destabilize his government,'' said Sen. Sam Brownback,
R-Kan., chairman of the Subcommittee on Near Eastern and South
Asian Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this is not the case, why will the Secretary General and
the Secretary of State not release the contents of Mr. Annan's
letter to Col. Gadhafi cajoling him into cooperating in the trial
now taking place?''
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Bernstein, whose husband Mike was killed in the
December 1988 airline bombing, said sections of a letter giving
Libyans ''the assurances necessary to turn the suspects over'' were
read to her and other victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   ''Promises were made that the Libyan regime would not be
undermined or embarrassed during the trial,'' she told the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear who read her the letter. When families tried to
get a copy, she said, they were told first that it didn't exist,
then that it couldn't be found, then that it had been classified.
Lastly, a U.S. official told them that it was a U.N. letter and its
release would have to be made by the United Nations, Bernstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. spokesman Farhan Haq said Thursday that he could neither
confirm nor deny the existence of such a letter, but added: ''The
U.N. legal counsel says there have never been any assurances given
to Gadhafi or any others on the questions surrounding the Lockerbie
trial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1816 </TRAILER>
