<HEADLINE> Jim Kelly's Memorabilia Recovered  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- A two-week police investigation has led to
grand larceny charges pending against a man who allegedly walked
off with over $30,000 in sports memorabilia while working as a
handyman at the home of former Buffalo Bills quarterback Jim Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Orchard Park Detective Joe Wehrfritz said police have already
recovered about 25 items, many of which were found in Buffalo-area
collectable shops. Among the items were a pair of Shaquille O'Neal
sneakers, personally autographed to Kelly. Appraised at about
$20,000, the sneakers were worn by the current Los Angeles Lakers
star in an NBA championship game while O'Neal was with the Orlando
Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Also recovered was a bat autographed by Honus Wagner, a baseball
autographed by Babe Ruth and a football autographed by Jim Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The thefts allegedly took place over a six-month period after
the man was hired by Kelly last summer to clean and do yard work at
the Orchard Park home.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the items had been previously on display at the
quarterback's now-closed Buffalo restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got so much stuff, you wouldn't believe,'' Wehrfritz said
of the many other items that remain stored at Kelly's home. ''His
cellar is like a sports museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Police are not releasing any information on the suspect because
they are still attempting to recover all the items, some of which
were shipped out of state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't recovered everything yet. We want to make sure we
get everything recovered, that's our main goal,'' Wehrfritz said,
adding that he is scheduled to meet with Kelly on Friday to get an
inventory update.
</P>
</TEXT>
