<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gormley, Franks bicker over Clinton impeachment vote  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- When U.S. Rep. Robert Franks joined most of
his Republican colleagues to vote to impeach President Clinton in
late 1998, he also left the door open to support the lesser penalty
of censure if the president admitted wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half later, Franks' U.S. Senate opponent, state
Sen. Bill Gormley, says Franks can't have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, R-Berkeley Heights, should either have voted for
impeachment or supported censure, but not both, Gormley,
R-Atlantic, said at a Statehouse news conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the finger-to-the-wind approach to government,'' Gormley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley and Franks are among a field of Republicans running in
the June primary to replace retiring U.S. Sen. Frank Lautenberg,
D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley distributed to reporters a videotape of a television
news show in which Franks explained his pro-censure position a few
days after casting his pro-impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   A Franks spokesman said the congressman was consistent
throughout the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Charlie Smith said Franks let it be known, including
in personal letters to the president, that he did not want an
impeachment trial to disrupt the nation's business. But in the
absence of an admission from Clinton that he lied under oath about
his affair with Monica Lewinsky, Franks felt he had no choice but
to vote to impeach, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Franks said in a prepared statement that he suspected his vote
would come back to haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never, however, suspected a fellow Republican would be so
reckless as to engage in this type of deceptive campaign conduct,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley said he would have voted both to impeach and convict the
president, if given the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley also criticized Franks, a former New Jersey state
assemblyman, for abstaining on a vote to ban semi-automatic weapons
in the early 1990s. Gormley supported the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Franks abstained because he had constitutional concerns. But
those concerns were addressed by a 1994 federal ban, which Franks
supported, his campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gormley found himself on the defensive when asked whether
it's ethical to accept campaign contributions from the casino
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Franks' campaign said his opponent's acceptance of casino cash
creates a conflict of interest for Gormley, who has a hand in
regulating the gaming halls as chairman of the powerful Senate
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   It's illegal for state candidates to accept contributions from
the casino industry; not so for federal candidates.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gormley, the industry has given him $166,000.
Franks says it's more like $194,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley said he saw nothing wrong with the practice. In fact, he
said he would favor watering down the state law to allow limited
gaming contributions to state candidates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 1825 </TRAILER>
