<HEADLINE> Angels 8, Orioles 5  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GINSBURG, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Scott Spiezio drove in three runs and Mo Vaughn
hit his second homer in two games as the Anaheim Angels pounded
nemesis Mike Mussina and beat the Baltimore Orioles 8-5 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon also homered for the Angels, who hit eight homers in
winning two of three from Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad, the AL batting leader, went 0-for-5 and failed to
reach base for the first time in 28 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Mussina (1-3) allowed six runs on eight hits in 4 1-3 innings.
He came in with an 11-3 lifetime record against the Angels, going
6-0 in 10 starts since May 29, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a 138-pitch effort against Texas on Saturday, Mussina
retired the first five batters. But he yielded five straight hits
in the fourth inning and left in the fifth with Baltimore trailing
6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Brady Anderson homered for the Orioles, who have lost seven of
11. Baltimore got only two hits over the final five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill (3-3) got the win despite giving up five runs in five
innings. Shigetoshi Hasegawa got the final outs for his first save.
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio singled in a run in the second before Baltimore batted
around to go up 3-1 in the third. After B.J. Surhoff hit a bloop to
right that fell for an RBI single, Albert Belle followed with a
sacrifice fly and Harold Baines singled in a run.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels quickly regained the lead, scoring four runs on six
hits in the fourth. Vaughn hit a leadoff homer, his seventh,
Spiezio doubled in two runs and Bengi Molina hit an RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hit a two-run shot in the Orioles' half to make it 5-5,
but Anaheim again responded. Adam Kennedy opened the fifth with a
triple and scored on a groundout by Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon hit a solo homer and Benji Gil singled in a run in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Vaughn has hit 15 homers at Camden Yards, tied with Albert
Belle for first place among Oriole opponents. ... The Angels have
homered in 10 straight games. ... Cal Ripken got the day off and
was replaced by Mark Lewis, who did not get a chance third base and
went 0-for-4.
</P>
</TEXT>
