<BODY>
<HEADLINE> J.C. Penney Top Executive To Retire  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID KOENIG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLANO, Texas (AP) -- J.C. Penney Co. Inc.'s top executive will
step down by the end of the year, leaving the giant retailer as it
struggles to regain its footing in an increasingly competitive
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Penney said Thursday that 58-year-old James E. Oesterreicher,
who joined the company in 1964 as a management trainee, plans to
retire as soon as his successor is in place.
</P>
<P>
   ''Penney has drifted sideways and down for too many years,''
said Jeffrey Edelman, a retail analyst for the investment firm
PaineWebber. ''Changes have been made too slowly. This could be a
major turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors cheered the news, sending Penney's shares up $1.56\ to
$17.43} at 5 p.m. EDT on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Retail consultant Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail
Trend Report, said change at the top will finally create a ray of
hope for Penney shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Oesterreicher is a wonderful gentleman, but he totally
lacked the dynamism and executive decisiveness to turn J.C. Penney
around. It's truly one of the most mismanaged companies in
retailing,'' Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   Since he took over as chairman and chief executive in 1997,
Oesterreicher has moved aggressively to get the ailing retailer
back on track. He closed underperfoming stores, sold noncore
businesses, overhauled merchandise buying and hired more outside
executives.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts believe the company was too slow to adapt to
changes in consumer tastes and improve the cluttered look of its
department stores. It continues to lose shoppers to trendier rivals
such as Old Navy, Kohl's and Macy's.
</P>
<P>
   The company's sales and profits have been under pressure and its
stock has been battered, losing about two-thirds of its value in
the last year.
</P>
<P>
   In a message to employees Thursday, Oesterreicher said the
cost-cutting steps ''have been painful but absolutely critical for
our future profitable growth.''
</P>
<P>
   He also told the staff that with the cost savings already taken,
''now is the appropriate time to announce my retirement and for the
company to transition to a new generation of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Penney's spokeswoman Rita Trevino Flynn said Oesterreicher and
company directors began discussing succession plans several months
ago. She said the board will consider both insiders and outsiders
and expects to name a replacement by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Possible successors include Vanessa Castagna, 49, who Penney
hired last year as chief operating officer from Wal-Mart Stores
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a need for new blood and more dynamic leadership in
the company. Ms. Castagna brought new blood,'' said Walter Loeb,
who runs the retail consulting firm Loeb Associates, who called
Castagna the strongest early candidate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1829 </TRAILER>
