<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Social Security Commission Pushed  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican Sen. John McCain joined with two
Senate Democrats on Thursday to propose insulating Social Security
from election-year politics by creating a bipartisan commission to
hammer out a compromise on changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''For too long, Social Security has been used by politicians on
both sides of the aisle -- both sides of the aisle -- to polarize,
manipulate and scare American voters,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security has become a particularly contentious issue on
the presidential campaign trail in recent days, with Democrat Al
Gore attacking Republican George W. Bush's support for diverting
some Social Security taxes into private investment accounts for
workers.
</P>
<P>
   The commission envisioned by McCain and Democratic
collaborators, Sens. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Daniel Moynihan of
New York, would be directed to consider creating such accounts. But
it also would have to consider something Gore favors: using money
from expected income tax surpluses to help shore up Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, speaking from Mission Viejo, Calif., on Thursday expressed
support for the idea. ''This shouldn't be a partisan effort,'' he
said. ''Social Security shouldn't be used to frighten seniors as
has been done in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was skeptical. ''These commissions are in the eye of the
beholder,'' he said, speaking to reporters after a campaign
appearance in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Of the senators proposing the commission, Gore added ''I also
disagree with them and agree instead with the great majority of
Democrats and Republicans in the Senate and the House who are not
for privatization of Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a Republican from Arizona, bowed out of the presidential
race in March. Kerrey and Moynihan are noted for their expertise on
the nation's retirement system, as well as work together on
legislation that would create voluntary Social Security investment
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats, although Gore supporters, criticized the vice
president for his attacks on such accounts and his characterization
of any reform plan that includes them as ''privatization.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That is a scare word,'' Moynihan said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey met privately with Bush last week to discuss Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand that people are nervous about this. I think it's
going to take a commission,'' Kerrey said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the proposed Social Security commission would be
appointed February 1, after presidential and congressional
elections are decided. The panel would have to produce legislation
no later than September 1, and Congress would be obligated to vote
on it before adjourning its 2001 session.
</P>
<P>
   The commission would be composed of 12 members of Congress -- six
Democrats and six Republicans -- including the chairmen and senior
minority members of the House Ways and Means and Senate Finance
committees.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate leaders of both political parties would each
get to pick two commission members. The nation's new president
would not be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security Commissioner Kenneth S. Apfel would participate
on the commission, but have no vote. Apfel is a Clinton appointee,
but serves a six-year term which gives him status independent from
the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation passed by the House in 1998 to create a commission
to deal with Social Security was opposed by the White House as
unnecessary and ignored by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The last Social Security commission, chaired by Federal Reserve
Governor Edward Gramlich, ended its work in early 1997 without
reaching consensus. Lawmakers are still debating the issue that
divided that panel: whether and how to invest Social Security money
in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the 1983 recommendations of a Social Security
commission chaired by Alan Greenspan, now Fed chairman, resulted in
Congress enacting major changes to the program, including a gradual
increase in the eligibility age for benefits, from 65 to 67.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1829 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shares Of Mexico's Big Banks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- An offer from Mexico's largest bank, Banamex,
to second-place Bancomer to merge and form one of Latin America's
largest financial institutions sent both companies' stocks sharply
upward Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The unsolicited $2.4 billion offer made late Wednesday
effectively doubled the $1.2-billion bid for Bancomer made only
weeks ago by BBV-Probursa, the Mexican unit of Spanish bank Banco
Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria.
</P>
<P>
   The offer by Grupo Financiero Banamex-Accival, the controlling
company of Banamex, represents a 25 percent premium over
Wednesday's closing prices for Bancomer's shares, raising the value
of the company in the eyes of investors.
</P>
<P>
   Bancomer O shares soared 31 percent Thursday to close at 5.08
pesos, or 54 cents. Banacci O shares added 1.6 percent to close at
34.60 pesos, or $3.68.
</P>
<P>
   But the merger also threatened to create yet another
market-dominating company during a presidential administration that
has let monopolies or near-monopolies spring up in several
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican laws don't allow hostile takeovers, but Bancomer's
management is required to present both offers to shareholders. The
proposal will also need approval from bank regulators and the
federal antimonopoly commission.
</P>
<P>
   The two banks, if merged, would dominated most segments of the
banking market here: 81.6 percent of credit cards, and nearly half
of all outstanding loans and deposits.
</P>
<P>
   No one at the National Banking and Securities Commission was
available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Any regulatory approval would probably imply forcing the
companies to sell off some assets, and Banamex has already said it
would liquidate $1 billion in ''redundant assets'' as part of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Under President Ernesto Zedillo, domestic airline service has
been largely concentrated in one holding company, and vertical
integration has been allowed in telephone and Internet service. One
or two companies have come to dominate many industries here in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   While large by Latin American standards at $60 billion in
assets, the size of the bank merger, if approved, would still be
less than one-tenth the size of U.S. banking giant Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the Banamex bid may lead to a counterbid from BBV
that will also contribute to increasing the value that Bancomer
shareholders will get from their stake.
</P>
<P>
   Under BBV's offer, its initial stake in the merged company would
be about 26 percent, and would rise gradually to 40 percent through
market operations. Bancomer's controlling group of shareholders
would get a stake of about 23 percent in the merged company.
</P>
<P>
   Banacci's proposal would give it a 65 percent stake in the new
merged company, with Bancomer holding the remaining 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Banacci proposal calls for the resulting entity to undergo a
$2.4 billion capitalization plan.
</P>
<P>
   Banacci's offer will be mostly backed by $1.4 billion in new
capital resources, and a contingent financing facility of $1
billion committed by Chase Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   It also said the annual cost savings from the merger could be
equivalent to 15 percent of the combined banks' operating expenses
within three years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1830 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Democrats Forge Medicare Plan  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Democrats are working on Medicare
prescription drug legislation that would build on President
Clinton's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Among additions being discussed by Democratic lawmakers are a
cap on senior citizens' out-of-pocket expenses of $3,000 annually,
according to a memo obtained by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has earmarked $35 billion to help retirees with very
high drug bills and whose costs would exceed the limits of new
Medicare coverage he has proposed. But the president has said
Congress should decide how best to do that.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional Democrats' proposal, which could be made
public as soon as next week, would counter a plan House Republicans
outlined last month. Democratic leaders also hope it can help rally
the party around a single piece of drug legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Clinton's plan, Democrats have introduced a wide
variety of bills this year designed to help senior citizens with
their drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're working for unity,'' said Laura Nichols, spokeswoman for
House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The House Democrats also are consulting with their Senate
counterparts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   A second provision under consideration by the Democrats is a
board of private experts who would advise the government on
Medicare drug benefits. Some conservative Democrats may like that
''because it shows a willingness to consult/use private sector,''
the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation advocated by House Republicans' relies heavily on
the private sector, providing government subsidies for new
prescription drug policies that insurance companies would be
encouraged to sell. Rules for the new policies have not been
completed, but the GOP plan specifies they would have to include a
cap on annual out-of-pocket expenses.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats generally are keeping the basic structure of
Clinton's plan. Under it, Medicare would contract with the same
private pharmaceutical benefit management companies that many
insurers use to help them negotiate discount prices from drug
companies and otherwise control costs.
</P>
<P>
   Senior citizens would pay a monthly premium -- Clinton has set it
at $26 to start -- for Medicare coverage of half the cost of each
prescription, up to $1,000 in benefits annually. Benefits would
rise to $2,500 a year when fully phased in, with premiums
increasing as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1831 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
