<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardinal Wanted Simple Funeral  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cardinal John O'Connor, America's most powerful
Roman Catholic, wanted to be buried as ''a priest for all the
people'' rather than honored for his years as a military chaplain
and Navy rear admiral.
</P>
<P>
   Those simple wishes will be followed during the four days of
funeral rites for the cardinal, Archdiocese spokesman Joe Zwilling
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A long series of religious events were being planned in what
Zwilling described as a church ''command center.'' So many people
want to attend Monday's funeral Mass at St. Patrick's Cathedral
that close to 3,000 tickets were being issued.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we were able to, I'm sure we could fill Yankee Stadium
three times over,'' the spokesman told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   With the cardinal's body in a funeral home, the first official
sign of mourning appeared at St. Patrick's, the Fifth Avenue
cathedral that is the seat of the archbishop of New York. As noon
bells tolled, firefighters fastened black and purple bunting above
the huge bronze portals.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, O'Connor's body was to be brought to the
cathedral's entrance. ''It will be greeted, it will be blessed,
prayers will be said over the body,'' Zwilling said. ''It's a very
special rite in which the archbishop is welcomed back to his
church.''
</P>
<P>
   The coffin will then be taken up the aisle, opened and placed in
the sanctuary in front of the main altar, where the public can walk
by and pay respects; time will be set aside for private viewing.
The cardinal's body will lie in state all day Saturday and Sunday
near his now-empty chair.
</P>
<P>
   Regular Masses were to be celebrated in the presence of the
cardinal's body. He will be interred in the crypt under the
cathedral's altar, where all the previous archbishops of New York
are buried.
</P>
<P>
   The coffin will be shut and placed in the center aisle during
the funeral Mass, which is expected to last at least two hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
