<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Weakens Egg Safety Plan  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bowing to the egg industry, House
appropriators agreed Thursday to weaken the Clinton
administration's plan to require more extensive testing of eggs for
harmful bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   That plan would require that producers to test for salmonella
enteritidis all around their farms, not just on the hens or eggs.
If the bacteria were found anywhere, including in manure pits, all
of the farm's eggs would have to be pasteurized or diverted from
market.
</P>
<P>
   Under legislation approved by the House Appropriations
subcommittee on agriculture, salmonella would have to be found on
the eggs themselves before they would be barred from stores.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee's version also would force the Food and Drug
Administration to pay the cost of egg testing and prevent states
from requiring more tests than the federal agency. The measure was
approved 10-5 and attached to an annual spending bill for the FDA
and the Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many in the egg industry are already testing. If you look at
what's happening with the incidence of salmonella, it's
declining,'' said Ken Klippen, a spokesman for United Egg
Producers.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's plan, which also would require a warning
label for egg cartons, is supposed to reduce salmonella cases by
half in five years.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated one in every 20,000 eggs is infected with
salmonella enteritidis, a significant source of food poisoning
since the 1980s that can cause diarrhea, fever, abdominal cramps,
headache, nausea and vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   Salmonella illnesses associated with raw or undercooked eggs
soared in the 1980s and 1990s, reaching a peak of 3.6 cases for
every 100,000 people in 1996. The rate dropped to 2.2 cases per
100,000 people in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''Year after year the egg industry goes to the appropriations
committee to try to turn back public health improvements,'' said
Caroline Smith DeWaal of the Center for Science in the Public
Interest, a public advocacy group. ''Eggs remain at the top of the
list of foods that are causing foodborne outbreaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed label says ''eggs may contain harmful bacteria
known to cause serious illness.'' Producers say it is unduly
alarmist and will scare consumers from eggs. The House measure
urges but would not require FDA to soften the warning.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey, a Wisconsin Democrat who supports the
administration's plan, said the industry-backed measure was a
''political fix to a scientific problem.'' FDA officials declined
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The spending bill does include $5 million that the
administration requested for its egg safety initiative. The
Senate's version of the spending bill, which was approved by the
Senate Appropriations subcommittee on agriculture later Thursday,
omitted the $5 million but would not require FDA to alter any of
its proposed rules.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the egg amendment, the House bill also would make
some changes sought by the meat industry in a new USDA rule that
allows schools to provide soyburgers, tofu and other soy produces
in school meals.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would require children to be told when products
have large amounts of soy in them, and the soy would also have to
be fortified with iron and zinc. Cattle producers say beef will get
a bad reputation if kids don't like meat products that have soy in
them.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Food and Drug Administration:
http://www.fda.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
