<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fortified Salt Could Help Anemics  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA ROSS, AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Scientists have developed a new technology to
fortify ordinary table salt with iron -- an advance experts say
could help overcome the severe anemia afflicting more than half the
population in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Experts hope adding iron to salt will improve health in
developing nations as effectively as fortifying salt with iodine.
The United Nations children's agency estimates the introduction of
iodized salt has spared millions of children every year from mental
retardation.
</P>
<P>
   Salt is considered a good vehicle for providing nutrients
because it is one of the only dietary staples used in all regions
of the globe, and people worldwide consume about the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   The technology to add both iron and iodine to salt, developed by
the interagency group the Micronutrient Initiative and the
University of Toronto, is to be presented next week to scientists
and salt experts at a conference in The Hague, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd like this to be on the shelves a year from now,'' said
Venkatesh Mannar, the Micronutrient Initiative's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   But Werner Schultink, UNICEF's senior adviser on micronutrients,
said he believes a global program could be a few years away.
</P>
<P>
   The fortified salt would not significantly improve the health of
people in the developed world because their diet is more varied and
includes iron-rich meat and products such as breakfast cereals and
baby food that are already fortified with iron.
</P>
<P>
   In many developing countries, however, about 65 percent of
pregnant women suffer from extreme iron deficiency, a condition
known as Iron Deficiency Anemia, which can impair brain
development. Infants and teen-age girls also are affected.
</P>
<P>
   Global health agencies have had an iron-boosting program in
place for several years in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   The main approach has been to hand out iron and folic acid
tablets to pregnant women, who, when severely anemic, could go into
shock if they lose a pint of blood.
</P>
<P>
   ''That program has not been very successful in that iron
deficiency has not diminished,'' Schultink said, explaining that it
has been difficult to get the pills to the health centers and that
women often don't follow through on taking the tablets.
</P>
<P>
   The idea now is to supplement that program by blanketing the
whole population with fortified salt.
</P>
<P>
   Albion Laboratories Inc. of Clearfield, Utah, already has
fortified refined sugar with iron and is selling the product in
Brazil and Guatemala. But government regulations have inhibited the
sugar from being used in other countries, said Stephen Ashmead,
Albion's director of research and development.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted iron-fortified salt could face similar hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Mannar said that while regulations are an issue, he hoped
governments and salt producers will have confidence in the proposal
after the success of the iodine initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Introducing the new salt would be relatively easy if it can
piggyback on the production and distribution networks already in
place for iodized salt, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel we can take advantage of this infrastructure to
introduce another micronutrient,'' Mannar said. ''We'd transfer the
technology and teach the salt producers how to incorporate the
iron.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding iron to salt would cost about 5 cents per 2.2 pounds of
salt, or about 15 cents per person per year, Mannar said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we can get iron to the population any better
way,'' he said. ''We hope to move from severe anemia to mild
anemia.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty with adding iron to iodized salt is that the iron
and iodine are chemically incompatible and react badly with each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Mannar's group devised a way to coat both the iron and iodine
particles separately to prevent them from coming into contact with
each other or with moisture in the packet. The coating then
disintegrates when it comes into contact with acid in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   People given the salt had no objections to the taste or color,
and tests showed their bodies had absorbed a sufficient amount of
iron.
</P>
<P>
   In studies Mannar conducted in Ghana, blood tests showed that
eight months after starting to eat the new salt, the incidence of
anemia dropped by 30 percent in children.
</P>
<P>
   In women with anemia, the iron-fortified salt prevented their
anemia from getting worse. Meanwhile, women who were eating salt
incorporating only iodine were more anemic eight months later.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: UNICEF site focusing on nutrition:
http://www.unicef.org/sowc98/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
