<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man caught cheating classic car collectors -- again  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROME, N.Y. (AP) -- A businessman who two years ago was convicted
of trying to sell antique vehicles he did not own has been charged
again with defrauding classic collectors, authorities said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Francis, 42, of Rome, was charged in Oneida County Court
with four counts of third-degree grand larceny.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've indicted him on new charges. Same kind of stuff,
different victims,'' said Assistant District Attorney Dawn Catera
Lupi. ''It doesn't appear that he learned his lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis, owner of Vintage Cars, placed ads in national car
magazines and on the Internet offering collectible cars for sale,
said Investigator David Nowakowski. He received tens of thousands
of dollars from people for vehicles that he never had to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ''What Mr. Francis did was to take advantage of these people's
passion for vintage cars, and their trust in the people in the
business,'' Nowakowski said.
</P>
<P>
   According to authorities, victims in the case sent money to
Francis by either wire transfer or certified check. They planned to
buy the vehicles sight unseen because the cars Francis advertised
were rare -- a common practice among collectors, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   But the victims waited more than a year in some cases without
seeing the cars or seeing their money again, Nowakowski said.
</P>
<P>
   Lupi said four people who testified before a county grand jury
paid Francis a combined total of $40,000 to $50,000. People
generally sent Francis between $5,000 and $10,000, officials said.
But Lupi said one person sent him $25,000. The victims identified
in the indictment were from New Jersey, Ohio, West Virginia and
Georgia, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lupi said the advertising encompassed a range of cars, from
Model T's to Ford pickup trucks from the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Francis even tried to sell someone else's car, the prosecutor
said. A man took a picture of a truck he wanted to sell and mailed
some copies to antique-car buyers. Francis got hold of one of the
pictures and used it in his own advertisement, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The man saw it and said, 'Wait a minute, that's mine,''' Lupi
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, local authorities brought felony charges against
Francis for the same type of scam involving victims in seven states
and Canada. The state filed a civil lawsuit against Francis
accusing him of false advertising and fraudulent business
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Francis was allowed to plead guilty to misdemeanor charges after
agreeing to pay restitution to the victims identified by local
authorities, said Lupi. Because he has a previous felony DWI
conviction, Francis will get state prison time if he is convicted
again, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we are basically at the point that we've gone down that
road (leniency) so now we are taking a stronger stand,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Dopp, a spokesman for Attorney General Eliot Spitzer,
said the civil charges brought by the state remain pending against
Francis, who has never paid the victims identified by the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
