<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Still Not A Big Draw On TV  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD FENDRICH, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was pretty much nowhere to go but up.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has attracted a handful more viewers for the NHL playoffs
than Fox did a year ago, and ESPN trumpets that its postseason
hockey ratings among men 18-34 have increased 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey has always faced the problem of attracting viewers across
the United States, largely because the sport has proved to be a
truly consistent draw only regionally.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's playoff hockey ratings have been 10.3 in Denver and 8.1 in
Pittsburgh as those cities' teams advanced to the conference
semifinals. But in Chicago, whose Blackhawks missed the playoffs,
the rating was just 1.5 in the nation's third-largest TV market.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike other major sports, hockey doesn't receive a boost
from the playoffs. Even though NBC's NBA playoff national ratings
are down to a 4.4, that's still nearly 30 percent higher than in
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Even NHL commissioner Gary Bettman acknowledges his game is not
ideal for wide appeal on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think you can watch hockey on television, but you can't
generate the same excitement on TV as you can in the stadium,''
Bettman said. ''That's a problem, and when we solve it our ratings
will go up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Walt Disney Co., which owns ABC and the ESPN networks, anted
up $600 million in August for a five-year deal with the NHL. That
was a significant hike over the league's old package, but Disney's
plan to cross-promote hockey on ABC and ESPN has yet to produce big
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, whose broadcast rights are costing about double what Fox's
did, is averaging a 1.7 national rating in the playoffs, up 0.1
from what Fox had over a comparable period last year. The rating is
the percentage of the nation's TV households tuned to a broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's playoff coverage has averaged a 0.84 national cable
rating through Wednesday, down from a 0.87 in 1999, and a 20
percent plunge from 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ABC and ESPN are quick to point to their rising numbers among
men 18-34, saying that's what advertisers are promised they will
reach. ABC is up 31 percent in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's the number we really care about,'' ABC Sports vice
president Mark Mandel said. ''We've always said we and ESPN are
going to be promoting hockey to try to attract that demographic.''
</P>
<P>
   That group dipped last year on ESPN to a 0.81, but is up to a
1.23.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a relatively difficult demo to reach -- 18- to
34-year-olds are tough to get on TV, men especially,'' said Ron
Fredrick, acting managing director of national broadcast for
MindShare, an advertising agency.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's regular-season ratings averaged a 1.3, down from Fox's 1.4
a year ago and about 30 percent off what Fox got in 1996, prompting
the network to consider changes for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ABC might put its games only on Saturdays -- it aired the NHL
also on Sundays this season -- and add a game to its schedule,
according to Dan Margulis, ABC Sports director of sports
programming.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not even finished with Act I of a five-act play,'' NHL
chief operating officer Jon Litner said, referring to the length of
the current deal. ''More people than last year are watching. That's
a foundation, and we need to grow that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NEWS: The heavyweight title bout between Lennox
Lewis and Michael Grant on Saturday night generated 375,000 buys --
at $44.95 apiece -- on TVKO, HBO's pay-per-view arm. That represents
a drop-off from Lewis' fights against Evander Holyfield: Their
first bout generated 1.2 million buys, the second 850,000. HBO
shows Lewis-Grant on Friday at 10 p.m. ET and PT. ... Count Jim
Rome out of the ''Monday Night Football'' announcer sweepstakes.
Rome signed a multiyear contract to remain as host of ''The Last
Word with Jim Rome,'' weekdays on Fox Sports Net.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   WHAT'S ON: Don't miss Jim McKay's last Kentucky Derby. After
26 years on ABC, the Run for the Roses moves to NBC for 2001.
Coverage starts at 4:30 p.m. ET on target -- a fight between spectators is
glamorized and fewer than 10 minutes focus on participants' lack of
preparation for life after basketball -- it is entertaining watching
''Captain Nappy,'' ''The Future'' and other players.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   CHANGING CHANNELS: The Understatement of the Week Award goes
to TNT's Doug Collins, who said, ''And Sacramento feels they have a
chance for the win,'' over replays of Kings players bumping chests
and slapping palms with 3:18 left and the Kings ahead 91-80 at htroit on
Wednesday to go to the Atlanta Braves' attempt to win their 16th
straight (which was in the second inning). It would have been nice
to hear what rookie Chris Drury -- the same Chris Drury who pitched
his team to the 1989 Little League World Series title -- thought
about scoring the deciding goal, without having to wait more than
two hours for SportsCenter or ESPN2's NHL Tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
