<HEADLINE> Cardinal Did Not Talk About Cancer  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Although cancer killed Cardinal John O'Connor,
the ''C'' word was first used publicly only hours after his death.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was the cardinal's choice,'' said his spokesman, Joseph
Zwilling. ''He handled it the way he wished it to be handled.''
</P>
<P>
   But many experts said talking about cancer encourages people to
undergo tests, and they were upset that a public figure such as
O'Connor would take such an old-fashioned approach.
</P>
<P>
   ''Increased public awareness helps drive home the message that
early detection saves lives, and the more people know, the better
prepared they will be to learn about cancer,'' said Dan Klotz,
spokesman for the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   In October, while inaugurating a new cancer-treatment facility,
the cardinal was asked whether he had the disease.
</P>
<P>
   He replied that he would not use the word ''cancer'' to describe
the tumor that had been removed from his brain weeks earlier
because his doctors had not used it.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one has used it,'' O'Connor said then. ''I haven't been
using it. They told me I had a brain tumor. They took it out. And
now they're using the X-ray treatment to assure there's nothing
else.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Zwilling refused to discuss why the cardinal
decided not to talk about cancer. He said that although O'Connor
was aware he had the disease, ''he was determined not to stop for
this. He wanted to continue being the archbishop of New York for as
long as he was physically able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   And he never hid the fact that he was sick, Zwilling said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was very public, he was not afraid at all to come into St.
Patrick's Cathedral with no hair, bloated from the treatments that
he was receiving,'' said Zwilling, adding that the cardinal
celebrated Mass while occasionally stumbling or slurring words.
''He knew what was going on, he never denied it or tried to
contradict it.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Chicago's late Cardinal Joseph Bernardin used his
own deadly cancer as a platform. Two weeks before his death from
pancreatic cancer in 1996, he was still working with cancer
patients while speaking about his own battle.
</P>
<P>
   ''When public figures do talk bout their health, it increases
public awareness,'' said Klotz, of the cancer society.
</P>
<P>
   He cited Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's recent disclosure that he has
prostate cancer. After the announcement, calls to the cancer
society's toll-free number increased by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, ''talking about cancer is a very personal
decision, and certainly one that should not be judged in any way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1910 </TRAILER>
