<HEADLINE> Clinton Embraced in the Heartland  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- On Bill Clinton's two-day roadshow in the
American heartland, the theme was innovation in education but the
atmosphere was that of a lovefest for a lame duck president heading
into his final months.
</P>
<P>
   Just days after he spoofed himself as a forlorn, forgotten
leader, Clinton basked in the adulation of Iowa teen-agers who
screamed and wept as if he were a rock star and a governor who
suggested that ''President Leno'' consider late-night comedy as a
career move.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between Washington and the Clinton of this trip was
sharpened by a six-minute video depicting him as lonely, isolated
and on the downslide -- a tape he showed at the White House
Correspondents Association's black-tie dinner last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The tape was shown repeatedly on television as he journeyed
through Kentucky, Iowa, Minnesota and Ohio to push his education
reform package.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is my suggestion for a career after politics: a
late-night talk show,'' Iowa Gov. Tom Vilsack told Clinton
Wednesday night. ''Just think of what fun you will have in that
opening monologue every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's White House staff was uncomfortable Thursday at any
suggestion that he was using the tape and a breakneck travel
schedule -- he is away part of nearly every week for the next two
months -- to put Clinton in the midst of adoring crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't set his schedule based on his need to see people,''
spokesman Joe Lockhart said. As for the video, the spokesman
scoffed at the media's ''need to analyze this and find some deeper
meaning'' about the president's mood.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't seem concerned about such scrutiny. Before
boarding Air Force One on Wednesday for his flight to Kentucky,
Clinton turned to his wife, Hillary, in their limousine and held up
a brown paper lunch bag. In the video, a lunch bag-clutching
Clinton chased the first lady's limousine as it sped down the White
House driveway.
</P>
<P>
   It made for levity on a trip that otherwise was so light on news
that, at one point Lockhart and some aides considered putting a
biology lab specimen -- a cat in a bag of formaldehyde -- into a high
school locker for Clinton to find. They abandoned that plan just
moments before Clinton walked up.
</P>
<P>
   The president seemed distracted at times while touring
classrooms and delivering speeches. He was most alert when standing
waist-high in kindergartners in Owensboro, Ky., or signing
autographs and posing for pictures for more than a half-hour at St.
Paul's City Academy, the nation's first charter school.
</P>
<P>
   In Davenport, Iowa, Clinton lingered before a trio of squealing
girls -- one of whose hair was dyed Easter-egg pink -- chatting and
posing for photos. He signed a photo of himself for the pink-haired
girl; when he walked away, all three girls had tears streaming down
their cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Clinton sat slump-shouldered as he answered questions
at length during an Internet chat on ChannelOne.com. He had just
finished sharing memories of his sixth-grade teacher and education
during a simpler era when time caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could do this all day, but we're out of time,'' said
moderator Tracy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Staring at a backlog of questions on his computer screen,
Clinton replied: ''These are great questions. I wish that they all
had yes/no answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, Clinton finished his tour at an elementary
school in Columbus, Ohio, where reading and other scores are on the
rise. He seemed sleepy, but rallied to exchange a few jokes with
others on the dais.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton smiled warmly when the school's principal told him in
closing, ''you're a great president, and whoever follows you is
going to have a hard time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1924 </TRAILER>
