<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giants 7, Mets 2  </HEADLINE>
By ROB GLOSTER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Bill Mueller's bases-loaded triple
highlighted a raucous, six-run eighth inning and the San Francisco
Giants completed a four-game sweep of the New York Mets, winning
7-2 Thursday and spoiling Mike Piazza's return.
</P>
<P>
   The big inning also featured a bench-clearing scuffle, though no
punches were thrown.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco finished off its first four-game sweep of the Mets
since 1962. The Giants, who have won 10 of 12, outscored New York
32-11 in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Reed (3-1) overwhelmed the Giants in the first seven
innings, allowing one run and three hits.
</P>
<P>
   But Reed walked Armando Rios to start the eighth and allowed a
single by Rich Aurilia. One out later, pinch-hitter Felipe Crespo
singled to tie it at 2 and knock out Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Cook relieved and, before throwing a pitch, balked the
runners to second and third. On his second pitch, he hit Marvin
Benard in the shoulder and the two had to be separated. Both
benches emptied and there was some pushing and shoving, but no
punches were thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Cook and Benard again exchanged words when Cook was taken out of
the game before throwing another pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller then tripled off Armando Benitez to clear the bases. One
out later, Jeff Kent hit a two-run homer, his eighth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Rodriguez (2-0) pitched one inning for his second victory
in less than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza celebrated his return to the starting lineup with a
two-run homer and two other hits. Piazza, who had missed five
straight starts because of injury, hit his sixth homer and added a
double and single -- and also stole a base.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, whose only appearance since April 28 had been when he
pinch-hit a double in the Mets' 8-5 loss to the Giants in 11
innings on Wednesday, was sidelined with a bruised right wrist and
a hyperextended right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' first run came on an RBI double by Benard.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco starter Kirk Rueter, who has beaten every NL team
except the Mets, allowed two runs on three hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Giants claim it was their first four-game sweep of the
Mets, but the Mets' media guide says the Giants swept the Mets in a
four-game series at the Polo Grounds on June 1-3, 1962. ... Reed
has worked at least seven innings in each of his six starts this
season. ... Mets LF Rickey Henderson, who ranks third on the career
walks list, walked three times in four plate appearances against
Rueter. ... The Mets fell to 5-1 in games Reed has started this
season. ... Piazza had his 13th double of the season. He began the
day tied with Colorado's Jeff Cirillo for the league lead. ... The
Giants have a four-game winning streak at home after starting 1-7
at their new Pacific Bell Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
