<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo, U.N. Sign Cooperation Pact  </HEADLINE>
By GLENN McKENZIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- Congo's government agreed Thursday to
cooperate with U.N. plans to deploy a 5,500-member observer force
to monitor a shaky cease-fire in this war-battered central African
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was struck during a rare visit by seven U.N. Security
Council members to the capital, Kinshasa. The mission's leader,
U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke, said he was cautiously
optimistic about the deal, but warned that this week's killings and
kidnappings of U.N. staff in Sierra Leone could affect the Congo
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Under the vaguely worded Status of Forces Agreement, Congo's
government agreed to help ensure the safety and free movement of
the U.N. observers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement had been a major sticking point for both the
United Nations and Washington. In the past Congo has denied U.N.
monitors already in the country permission to travel to some
battlefronts and mining regions. Congo also has refused to
guarantee the welfare of U.N. staff.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Abdoulaye Yerodia and U.N. force chief Kamel
Morjane, of Algeria, signed the deal, while Holbrooke and Congo
President Laurent Kabila looked on.
</P>
<P>
   Congo's government, which depends extensively on foreign allies
for its military strength, has asked that the U.N. force be
deployed swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   But just hours before signing the deal, Yerodia dismissed U.N.
concerns for the safety of its observer troops as ''a little bit
annoying when a war is on.'' Yerodia also warned that U.N. troops
would still have to apply for permission to travel in
government-held areas.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said the expanded U.N. force could be deployed by
August, but that it depended partly on whether Congo complied with
the new agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The recent cracks in Sierra Leone's peace accord, which was
signed last year, also would likely affect Washington's view of
peacekeeping in Africa, Holbrooke said. Four peacekeepers are
missing and presumed dead, and 50 more are being held hostage by
the West African country's Revolutionary United Front, U.N.
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Leone's war is generally regarded as much less
complicated than the Congo conflagration, but the 11,100-strong
U.N. mission slated for Sierra Leone is more than twice the size of
the force proposed for Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Some political observers doubted the United Nations can help end
the tangled war in the vast central African country, which has
bountiful mineral wealth but almost no roads or communication
infrastructure. Kabila's government, five foreign armies and
numerous rebel and ethnic-based militias are fighting for power,
territory and riches.
</P>
<P>
   Although Congo and its military backers -- Zimbabwe, Angola and
Namibia -- along with the rebels' main allies -- Uganda and Rwanda --
all signed the cease-fire accord last year, the first significant
lull in fighting began only two weeks ago after the second
cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Congolese military spokesman Leon Richard Kasonga
said he had received reports that the rebels advanced last week
into loyalist territory in central and eastern Congo ''in an
attempt to gain more ground'' ahead of the U.N. deployment. The
rebels gave no immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed 5,537 member force -- including 500 monitors and
about 3,700 ''sharp end'' combat troops -- falls short of a full
peacekeeping mission, which has yet to be authorized. Between
10,000 and 25,000 troops -- and possibly more -- would be required to
enforce peace under combat conditions, some U.N. estimates say.
</P>
<P>
   The military observers, however, will be authorized to use force
to defend themselves and to ''protect civilians under imminent
danger of their lives,'' said U.N. officer Col. Steve Gagnon, of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The continent's regional powers -- Nigeria and South Africa --
have both offered troops to the expanded U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting Security Council delegation was to leave Friday for
Zambia, and later to fly to Zimbabwe, Uganda and Rwanda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1943 </TRAILER>
