<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore on Cardinal's Death  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Statements of presidential candidates on Cardinal John O'Connor:
</P>
<P>
   ''Laura and I are saddened to learn that our American family has
lost one of the premier religious leaders of our time. I was
honored to have had the opportunity to meet Cardinal O'Connor and
was profoundly inspired by his faith and his tireless work on
behalf of the poor and defenseless. The Cardinal was a man of
profound spiritual depth and human compassion. We have lost an
eloquent voice for human life and human dignity, and a champion for
the least among us. The Cardinal's life and works were a daily
reminder that, in some of his favorite words from Pope John Paul
II, 'There can be no love without justice.' Our prayers are with
the people of New York, the Cardinal's faith family across America
and the Church for its great loss.'' -- Republican presidential
candidate George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tipper and I were deeply saddened to learn of the passing of
one of this nation's most prominent leaders of faith -- Cardinal
John O'Connor. Never wavering in his devotion, Cardinal O'Connor
not only ministered to millions of Catholics in New York, but also
served as a powerful voice for the poor and the homeless all over
the world. Along with his love of God and his fellow man, Cardinal
O'Connor served his country with uncommon distinction. From the
jungles of Vietnam to our most mighty battleships, Cardinal
O'Connor was there attending to the needs of our men and women in
uniform. After he retired from military service as a rear admiral,
Cardinal O'Connor took his leadership to the Archdiocese of New
York -- where he will be long remembered by the countless numbers of
New Yorkers who were touched by his words and his works. His
lifetime of selfless commitment to others will remain his greatest
legacy and his enduring inspiration. Our thoughts and prayers go
out to all who loved him.'' -- Democratic presidential candidate Al
Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
