<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Steinhauer, Turner Lead Philips  </HEADLINE>
By JIM VERTUNO, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- A little course knowledge and a five-minute
lesson paid off early at the Philips Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Sherri Steinhauer, who used to play the Onion Creek Club as a
student at the University of Texas in the early 1980s, and Sherri
Turner, a 16-year pro who hasn't won since 1989, each shot a
5-under-par 65 Thursday to share the first-round lead.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Ward and Cindy Figg-Currier, who live in Austin and
occasionally play the 6,101-yard course, and Michele Redman, were
two strokes back.
</P>
<P>
   ''Back in college, I used to love to come out here and play,''
Steinhauer said after a round that included six birdies. ''It seems
like I really like the back nine.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Steinhauer equally split her six birdies on the front
and back nines. Starting her round at No. 10, she rolled in a
35-foot uphill putt on the par-3 17th to start a string of three
consecutive birdies. She was bogey-free over her final nine holes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best part of my game today was my putter. The greens were
a little tricky,'' said Steinhauer, who started the tournament
ranked second on the tour in birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Turner won the 1988 LPGA Championship but recorded her last
victory at the 1989 Hawaiian Ladies Open. She began her round with
three straight birdies.
</P>
<P>
   She broke the string with a bogey on No. 4 before moving to four
under with birdies on Nos. 12 and 15. After missing a 5-footer for
bogey on 16, She recovered to finish the round with two birdies for
a share of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Turner missed the cut last week at the Chick-Fil-A Charity
Championship and sought the advice of 20-year friend Rosey
Bartlett, who is caddying this week for Missie McGeorge.
</P>
<P>
   A five-minute lesson on Wednesday -- ''it took about two
swings,'' she said -- changed her setup position and made all the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last week was so frustrating. I had really lost my
confidence,'' Turner said. ''Every player out here will tell you
that if you lose your confidence it can be hard to get it back.
I've been around long enough to know that sometimes all it takes is
one good round of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Meg Mallon was four under through 15 holes before an errant tee
shot went left into the line of trees on the 545-yard par-5 7th.
After her second shot buried in a patch of clover off the fairway,
a frustrating double-bogey dropped her back into a pack of golfers
at 68.
</P>
<P>
   Tough pin placements surprised many of the players.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a lot of what we call Sunday pins. They were pretty
creative for a Thursday,'' said Ward, who battled a shaky driver
for most of the round.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Akiko Fukushima of Japan finished at 69.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament is a tribute to former Austin resident Harvey
Penick, considered one of golf's greatest instructors. His pupils
included two-time Masters champion Ben Crenshaw; U.S. Open winner
Tom Kite; Kathy Whitworth, winner of 88 tournaments; Mickey Wright;
and Betsy Rawls. Penick died in 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 1947 </TRAILER>
