<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Subway pusher gets maximum 25 to life for killing Kendra Webdale  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A mentally ill man who killed a young woman by
pushing her in front of a subway train last year was sentenced
Thursday to 25 years to life in prison by a judge who called him
''a dangerous man.''
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Carol Berkman imposed the sentence
on Andrew Goldstein, 30, a schizophrenic who was convicted March 22
of second-degree murder in the death of Kendra Ann Webdale, 32, of
Fredonia, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe, based on the evidence at trial, the probation
reports, and the testimony of psychiatrists at trial, that Mr.
Goldstein is dangerous,'' Berkman said as she sentenced the
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Just before sentencing, Goldstein apologized to Webdale's
parents, causing Patricia Webdale, the victim's mother, to gasp and
then weep. The attack, Goldstein said, resulted from an
uncontrollable psychotic episode.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to apologize to the parents of Ms. Webdale and
say that if I had taken my medication that whole thing would never
have happened,'' he said. ''It's been a horrible nightmare since
this incident began.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein was convicted after a five-week trial of killing
Webdale by pushing her off the subway platform in front of an
oncoming ''N'' train at the Broadway and 23rd Street station on
January 3, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to the court, Webdale's mother, Patricia, said she
finds it difficult to sleep at night or concentrate at work because
she is thinking about her slain daughter. ''I always have Kendra on
my mind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I mourn the cruel and inhuman way she left this world,'' Mrs.
Webdale said, weeping and looking at Goldstein. ''I cannot not
visit my daughter in either a mental institution or a prison. I
visit her at the cemetery.''
</P>
<P>
   Asking Berkman to mete out the maximum sentence, Assistant
District Attorney William Greenbaum said the defendant is indeed
mentally ill, but he is also smart enough to use his disability to
manipulate others.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbaum said Goldstein uses his mental illness as a shield and
an excuse for his bad acts, which included attacks on at least 13
people plus the murder of Webdale.
</P>
<P>
   Every time he attacked someone -- usually because he had been
sexually rebuffed, or needed a place to live -- Goldstein would say
he was sick and needed to go to a hospital, Greenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only connection between his mental illness and the
destruction of Kendra Webdale's life is that he figured that
because he's mentally ill, he could get away with it,'' Greenbaum
told Berkman.
</P>
<P>
   But Goldstein's lawyer, Kevin Canfield, told the judge that his
client is insane. ''We know who the cold-blooded killers are,'' he
said. ''This man is not one of them. He is mentally ill.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The jury, I believe, acted out of fear when they convicted
Andrew,'' Canfield said. He said Greenbaum, by saying Goldstein
used his mental illness as to manipulate others, gave the jury
''something to hang their hats on.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He belongs in an institution, not a prison,'' Canfield said.
He told Berkman that in most civilized countries, this case would
never have gone to trial, and if Goldstein had been in a hospital
as he should have been, the killing would not have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Because Goldstein attacked Webdale while refusing to take his
anti-psychotic medicine, the case led to a law last year that
allows violent mental patients to medicated by force. It is called
''Kendra's Law.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pleased the Webdale afmily has received the justice they
have sought for so long,'' Gov. George Pataki said in a statement.
''Out of this tragedy came Kendra's Law, which will help people
with mental illness while protecting New Yorkers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 1951 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
