<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School construction bill advances  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Suburban and rural New Jersey school
districts would receive at least 40 percent state funding for all
new projects, under the latest version of a school construction
bill approved by the Senate Education Committee on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But a plan to partially reimburse districts for old projects was
temporarily shelved by committee members.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands in the Senate, the $15 billion school construction
bill would fully fund the replacement or renovation of crumbling
school buildings in the state's 30 so-called special needs
districts, and pay for 40 percent or more of new projects in all
other districts.
</P>
<P>
   The committee passed the measure, S-200, by a 4-0 vote with one
abstention. It now heads to the Senate Budget Committee, which is
expected to consider it next week.
</P>
<P>
   The full Senate is poised to vote on the bill May 18, with the
Assembly to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But what form the bill will finally take is still unclear.
Substantial differences remain between Senate and Assembly
versions.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to reimburse districts for old projects raised alarms in
the Statehouse on Thursday. An amendment to include 18 percent
state funding for projects commenced before 1998 will be considered
later, sponsors said.
</P>
<P>
   According to supporters, the 18 percent add-on would tack on
another $420 million to the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman said she is ''very concerned'' about the
increasing price tag.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is going to become huge and potentially become a strain on
the budget,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It does raise concerns that we might not have sufficient
resources to do what is required by the court,'' said David Sciarra
of the Education Law Center, which sued the state on behalf of the
poor schools.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins said he wonders where lawmakers
will draw the line.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a question about how far back you go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Strickland of the Garden State Coalition of Schools, said
her group of middle class districts would welcome the additional
help, as long as the state is on sound financial footing.
</P>
<P>
   Education Committee Chairman Robert J. Martin, R-Morris, said
committee members could not agree how far back in time the aid
formula would go.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by Sen. Bill Gormley, R-Atlantic, would also
encourage economic development around new school buildings in six
unnamed pilot cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 1952 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Soccer Team To Open Play  </HEADLINE>
By LANDON HALL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- After three weeks of intense training, the
U.S. women's soccer team is ready to give an early glimpse of the
squad that will be on the field at the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans open play Friday night in the four-team U.S. Cup,
a tournament won by Team USA the first six years of its existence.
South Korea and Canada play in the early game, followed by the
United States against Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any time we compete for something, it's very important to
us,'' said midfielder Kristine Lilly, who will play in her 200th
game with the national team if the Americans reach Sunday's
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ''We play to win, no matter if we're playing a friendly, a
not-so-friendly, whatever you want to call it,'' she said. ''I
think that's why we've been so successful, because we play
everything that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The games are the first for the U.S. team since it opened
residency camp in Chula Vista, Calif., on April 17. Most of the
stars who won last year's stirring World Cup are here, including
Mia Hamm, Brandi Chastain and Briana Scurry. An exception is
Michelle Akers, who had shoulder surgery and should return in early
summer.
</P>
<P>
   New coach April Heinrichs has stressed fundamentals in practice,
and has been scrutinizing the youngsters who are vying for three
open spots on the 18-player Olympic roster.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're embarking on the end of our experimental phase, so we're
giving some looks to some of the younger players,'' said Heinrichs,
who replaced Tony DiCicco as national coach in January. ''We really
want to start building toward a focus on performance in the next
month. Right now the focus has been on setting standards,
introducing new concepts and getting back to the basics.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Cup has been lopsided in favor of the Americans. They
are 18-0-0 in the tournament and have outscored their opponents
79-8. This is the first year the event has been held in just one
city. The venue, Civic Stadium, also has been kind to Team USA,
which beat Canada 4-2 last June before 23,325 fans in the sendoff
match for the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Heinrichs, captain of the U.S. team that won the 1991 World Cup,
has been tough, but is responsive to the players. On Wednesday,
sensing the team was exhausted from its workouts, the coach gave
the players a day off.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really good, because the coaching staff is not expecting
us to be at Olympic level right now,'' said Tiffeny Milbrett, who
is from the Portland area, as is teammate Shannon MacMillan. ''It's
just the start of the small steps that we have to go through to
reach the peak form that we want to get to for Sydney.''
</P>
<P>
   Lilly, 28, played her first game for the United States at age
16. This weekend she could become the first U.S. player, man or
woman, to reach 200 ''caps,'' so named for the old tradition of
giving players hats for appearing in a game for their country.
Teammate Mia Hamm is next with 187 caps. The man with the most
appearances is German star Lothar Mathaeus, who has 146 caps.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's amazing to see what's happened with the game of soccer,
the way it's grown in popularity and support,'' Lilly said. ''What
hasn't changed is why we play. I think the greatest thing is that
people have finally caught on to it and love it like we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 2004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000504.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1998 Silver Medalist Sheer Retires  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. (AP) -- Gordy Sheer, who teamed with Chris
Thorpe to win a doubles luge silver medal at the 1998 Nagano
Olympics, announced his retirement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll miss the friendship, competition, training and
representing the United States at the highest level of
competition,'' said Sheer, of Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   Sheer, 28, began sliding with Thorpe, of Marquette, Mich., in
1988. They competed in three Winter Olympics and became USA Luge's
career leaders with 26 international medals over the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   They also won the overall World Cup gold medal in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think winning an Olympic medal in one day of competition is
a great achievement, but winning the overall World Cup gold medal
showed that Chris and I were consistent throughout an entire
season,'' Sheer said.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Rossi, executive director of USA Luge, said Sheer will be
missed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wish him well in his future pursuits but count on him to
stay close to the sport and in some way help the next generation of
sliders,'' Rossi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
