<DOCNO> APW20000504.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DiFrancesco presses $4B for transportation despite Whitman'sconcern  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Senate President Donald DiFrancesco is
moving forward with his plan to provide $4 billion over four years
for highway and rail projects.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how much money to divert from the general state
budget to use for transportation projects and for how many years to
permit this diversion.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Transportation committee approved DiFrancesco's bill,
S-16, Thursday, making it ready for a vote in the full Senate.
DiFrancesco said the governor's budget proposal for the 2000-2001
fiscal year starting July 1 would be amended to conform with his
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are road, bridge and tunnel-dependent,'' DiFrancesco said.
''We all know this is very critical to our state. I don't think
anyone disagrees with that.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the text of DiFrancesco's bill, his program diverts
$260 million in general revenue in the next fiscal year and
increases that draw in phases to $460 million by the 2004-2005
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But this is on paper. Most of the funding for highway and rail
projects comes from gasoline taxes, most of which are set aside by
the state constitution for transportation purposes. The problem is
that legislative staff and Gov. Christie Whitman's Treasury
department disagree on how much gas tax revenue will be coming in
for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said if the dig into general revenues is too deep, she
will not support the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Her current $21.3 billion budget proposal is actually in
agreement with DiFrancesco's plan on how much to spend over the 12
months of the next fiscal year. It is for the three years beyond
that they hit a fiscal fork in the road.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some parameters being put on the legislation that
put some concern on cost,'' Whitman said. ''We are looking and
working with the treasurer to make sure this is the best way to
bring the program forward, and whether it is sustainable in the
future. That's a concern that we have to have.''
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco staged a news conference Thursday with
transportation advocates to promote his plan, and he told reporters
that Whitman would support it. But when asked about it later, the
governor was cooler to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Both agree on the level of spending, $1 billion in new projects
each year for four years, to draw down matching federal dollars.
Both also agree that paying for a larger and larger share of the
work in cash, thus reducing the amount of money that has to be
borrowed using long-term bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman even agrees that in the forthcoming fiscal year they
will provide $699 million to the Transportation Trust Fund. Most of
it will be funded with gas tax collections, and the remaining
amount, anywhere from $250 million to $340 million, will be drawn
out of general revenues.
</P>
<P>
   It is the period from the 2001-2002 fiscal year to the 2004-2005
budget where the spending deal begins to break down.
</P>
<P>
   Both also agree on one more thing -- Whitman's proposal in 1998
to increase the 10.5 cent per gallon gas tax by 4 cents to finance
the Transportation Trust Fund is no longer in discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't need to raise taxes,'' DiFrancesco said. ''Have you
seen gas prices lately?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
