<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Announces New Bombing Exercises  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS HAWLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Hundreds of federal agents swept
through the U.S. Navy's prized Atlantic training ground Thursday,
removing 216 protesters without serious incident to end their
yearlong occupation of the bomb-strewn range.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy wasted no time in announcing new bombing exercises on
Puerto Rico's Vieques Island, which had been put on hold by the
protests.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said the Navy planned to resume training
within two weeks using dummy bombs, according to an agreement
reached between President Clinton and Puerto Rican Gov. Pedro
Rossello in January.
</P>
<P>
   Vieques residents, meanwhile, will vote on whether the Navy
should leave the island in 2003. A date for the referendum has not
been set.
</P>
<P>
   The resumption of training is a prerequisite for the transfer of
$40 million in economic aid for Vieques called for by the January
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by helicopters and ships, 200 FBI agents and 100 U.S.
Marshals swept across Puerto Rico's Vieques Island at dawn,
detaining the activists, several lawmakers, a bishop and nuns.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Attorney General Janet Reno said all 12 protest
sites were cleared and that there would be no charges against the
demonstraters unless they assaulted federal officers or returned to
range.
</P>
<P>
   ''All indications are that the protesters have handled
themselves in a peaceful and dignified manner,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Some protesters tried to run away when agents arrived, but
''that was a short-lived exercise,'' said FBI agent Dave Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin said that 216 people
had been removed from the base, including 64 from the main gate
area and the remainder from 12 camps inside. They were taken to
Roosevelt Roads Naval Station, which administers the nearby Vieques
range.
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, about 100 had been released and more were
being freed periodically.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin said no agents were injured in the raid and it was
believed all protesters were off the range.
</P>
<P>
   ''Compatriots, compatriots! We are winning and Vieques is going
to be free of the Navy,'' veteran Independence Party leader Ruben
Berrios -- who had not left the range for a year -- told cheering
supporters after his release.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening, hundreds of residents waving Puerto Rican
flags gave a heroes' welcome to dozens of the detained who returned
by boat to Isabel II, Vieques' biggest town.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can bet that we're going back,'' said protester Rega Miro,
26. ''Because of what we've done, every day the movement will grow
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Miro said the protesters were treated well and that the Navy
tried to get them to sign papers promising they would not return to
the bombing range. They refused, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators invaded the live-fire range -- used by the Navy and
U.S. allies to train for every major conflict since World War II --
after two stray bombs killed civilian security guard David Sanes
Rodriguez, 35, on April 19, 1999. The Navy said Sanes was the first
fatality in 60 years of exercises on Vieques and that the range is
vital to national security.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents charge Navy exercises have damaged their health, coral
reefs, fishing grounds and endangered species and have stunted
development on the Vieques, where the Navy employs only 100 local
people and unemployment is 18 percent, compared to Puerto Rico's
average of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello, who also wants the Navy to leave, said he was
''happy'' with the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of the Elian Gonzalez raid in Miami and its aftermath,
both sides in Vieques expressed relief at the lack of violence in
Thursday's operation.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we approached some camps, agents wore helmets and visors
because of the intelligence (about potential resistance) from those
camps. But once we realized the threats didn't exist, the helmets
came off,'' said Deputy Assistant FBI Director Jim Weber, who
commanded the removal operation.
</P>
<P>
   But protests erupted at Roosevelt Roads and elsewhere in the
main island of Puerto Rico as the Navy announced its plans to
resume Vieques training. Hundreds converged on the historic
district of Old San Juan late Thursday for a demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in San Juan, baton-wielding riot police on horseback
stared down about 800 shouting demonstrators blocking the gates to
the U.S. Army's Fort Buchanan. About 30 people chanted ''Yankees go
home'' at the Army's Fort Allen in the southern town of Juana Diaz.
Other protests shut down the University of Puerto Rico's main
campus and in western Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-Navy activists also threatened demonstrations at colleges
and cities on the U.S. mainland.
</P>
<P>
   A raid to clear the base had been expected since Monday, when
three U.S. warships arrived in the Vieques area. Some 200 U.S.
Marines set up a security perimeter Thursday at the range, and the
Coast Guard turned back 21 boats offshore.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. Thursday, range security was transferred from the
Justice Department to the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department said the operation was carried out ''with
the full support of the government of Puerto Rico and with the help
of police of Puerto Rico.''
</P>
<P>
   Agents were armed with pistols and assault rifles but were not
seen to have stormed into the camps. Unlike the Miami raid to
snatch 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, officers urged protesters to
leave voluntarily. But many held out their hands to be handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   The raid began at 5:15 a.m., when agents arrived at a camp
outside the range's main gate in vans with their lights turned off.
They were backed up by glum-looking Puerto Rican riot police.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you do not leave promptly, we will have to remove you,'' a
marshal said over a megaphone. Within minutes, helicopters swept
overhead toward the camps in the interior.
</P>
<P>
   Some agents seemed embarrassed, and one Puerto Rican FBI agent
was almost in tears as he handcuffed protesters, said Illinois
Congressman Luis Gutierrez, who was detained as was New York
Congresswoman Nydia Velazquez. Both are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are trying to be extremely kind and generous and
courteous, but I think they understand that they are wrong,'' a
handcuffed Gutierrez said.
</P>
<P>
   Several nuns sang as they waiting to be handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Bishop Alvaro Corrada del Rio said he and 42 other
church representatives were also detained.
</P>
<P>
   The raid came despite calls from some prominent Americans --
including first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and World Council of
Churches officials -- to avoid a confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president is pleased that the operation moved forward in a
peaceful fashion,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Navy Atlantic Fleet: http://www.atlanticfleet.navy.mil
</P>
<P>
   Links to Vieques activist groups: http://www.viequesvive.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
