<HEADLINE> 10 Sought in Fatal Guatemala Attacks  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUATEMALA CITY (AP) -- Police arrested nine suspects in the
beating deaths of a Japanese tourist and a Guatemalan bus driver
and are searching for 10 more people identified as having
participated in the attack, authorities said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Five men and four women were arrested in raids Wednesday on
several homes in the tiny village where the crime occurred, said
Gerson Lopez, spokesman for the Guatemala National Civil Police
Force. The 10 other suspects being sought include eight men and two
women.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said the 19 suspects were either leaders or active
participants in the crowd of about 500 that beat to death tourist
Tetsuo Yamahiro, 40, Saturday in Todos Santos Cuchuman, 96 miles
northwest of Guatemala City, near the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   The mob, armed with sticks and stones, also beat to death the
tour's bus driver Edgar Castellanos, 35, in the village, where
rumors have been spreading that foreigners come to the area to
steal children.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers doused the driver's body in gasoline and burned it
in front of the horrified visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Three others from the tour group of some 35 Japanese suffered
minor injuries during Saturday's attack. Two Guatemalan police
officers who attempted to stop the lynching were also injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
