<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schenectady boy who lost most of his bladder to receive $12million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCHENECTADY, N.Y. (AP) -- A boy who lost most of his bladder
during an outpatient surgery in 1996 will receive some $12 million
over the next 40 years in an out-of-court settlement negotiated
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Joan and Vincent Jabonaski of Schenectady sued Dr. Walfredo
Samson, a pediatric surgeon who died four years ago, after bringing
their 4-month-old son Vincent to him for removal of an umbilical
polyp.
</P>
<P>
   According to the family's attorney, John J. Massaroni of
Schenectady, Samson mistakenly cut away most of the boy's bladder
during the procedure and sent him home. His parents rushed him back
to St. Peter's Hospital, where the procedure was performed, the
next day, and he was transferred to Albany Medical Center hospital
for emergency surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors there built him a new bladder out of parts of his
intestines, but Massaroni said the boy has suffered complications
since then, including chronic infections and daily need for
catherization to drain the bladder.
</P>
<P>
   St. Peter's Hospital, which the family also sued, will pay about
$70,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
