<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bush Tout Education  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Al Gore brought to the crucial Midwest a plan to
require teacher certification, testing -- and, where there's
failure, firing -- as a condition of receiving federal education
dollars, while George W. Bush promoted his $3-billion proposal to
expand charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   Their nominal focus Thursday on issues dear to swing voters,
however, was all but drowned out by their volley of barbs.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with reporters after his education speech at a Mission
Viejo, Calif., elementary school, Bush vented mounting frustration
with Gore's attacks on his experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's amazing that a person running for president of the United
States would look people in the eye and say I've never submitted a
budget as governor and continue to say so when I did,'' the GOP
Texas governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Gore, who has tried to portray Bush as inexperienced,
reached dramatically into his pocket after a Chicago conference of
medical journalists and produced for reporters what he said was
Bush's 1995 budget -- 2{ pages folded in fours.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you think that's a budget, maybe I could convince you it's
a duck,'' Gore said. On Wednesday, Bush aides presented reporters
with the Texas governor's much more voluminous budget materials for
his other years in office. In a most unusual budget battle, Bush's
campaign has distributed stacks of documents, several inches thick,
that appear to be budget submissions by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In his presentation, Gore put a health-care twist on his mantra
that Bush is ''smug.'' Dismissing Bush's proposal to give $2,000
tax credits to help poor families pay for health insurance, Gore
said: ''I do not believe that we can be satisfied with the smug
assumption that our health care challenges will simply take care of
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   To reporters, Gore denied he meant anything personal by his
recent repetition of words like ''smug'' and ''arrogant'' to
criticize Bush. ''Vigorous discussion of the substance of the
issues is healthy for our democracy,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stuck to issues in his public remarks, pushing anew a
proposal offered earlier in the campaign -- a Charter School
Homestead Fund that he said would support $3 billion in loan
guarantees for charter schools during its first two years,
providing enough money for 2,000 schools -- double the existing
number.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to fan the spark of charter schools into a flame,''
Bush said. Charter schools are public schools that are given high
levels of flexibility in the way they conduct class. In exchange,
these schools are expected to produce high test scores from
students.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has broadly called for tripling the number of charter
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher quality was on deck for Gore's daylong visit Friday to
Holt High School outside Lansing, Mich., and an address to the
state teachers' union convention.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsed by the American Federation of Teachers and the National
Education Association, the nation's largest teachers' unions, Gore
trod more gingerly on the question of firing bad teachers than on
testing teacher competence.
</P>
<P>
   According to a preview given to The Associated Press, Gore would
establish an $8 billion, 10-year fund for previously proposed,
across-the-board salary increases of $5,000 for qualified teachers.
Gore would make the fund available only to school districts who,
''in the context of due process protections ... quickly remove
those teachers who really should be removed from the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal does not specify how such teachers should be
identified, but requires ''quick, intensive efforts to help them
improve'' before they are fired and higher standards for tenure,
including proven student performance.
</P>
<P>
   A separate $8 billion, 10-year fund would provide signing
bonuses, scholarships and college aid aimed at recruiting 1 million
new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks prepared for Friday's appearance, Gore promised: ''I
will ensure that there is a fully qualified, well-trained teacher
in every single classroom, everywhere in this nation by the end of
the next four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also would establish new prerequisites for the Title 1
money aimed at poor children and given to states:
</P>
<P>
   --By 2004, states must make sure every teacher is fully
certified, with middle and high school teachers additionally
required to demonstrate expertise in the subject they teach. The
Gore campaign said one in four secondary school teachers now lack a
minor in their main teaching field and too many teachers are
installed under ''emergency'' certificates, which means they do not
meet state standards for certification.
</P>
<P>
   --New teachers must pass ''rigorous assessments, including tests
of their subject matter and teaching proficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   --Elementary school teachers must be tested to ensure they know
how to teach reading.
</P>
<P>
   National standards for these assessments would be developed
through an unspecified ''independent, non-governmental effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gore proposed denying a slice of Title 1 funds to
schools whose student performance falls short.
</P>
<P>
   Separately in California, Bush's campaign said it expected to
raise $3.5 million Thursday at a fund-raiser at the home of Brad
Freeman, Bush's California finance director.
</P>
<P>
   Gore raised about $ 1 million at a pair of dinners in Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
