<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miami Mayor Blasts Fired Manager  </HEADLINE>
By CATHERINE WILSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Mayor Joe Carollo lashed out Thursday at the city
manager he fired last week, accusing the manager of racism and
saying that his appeal of his ouster was only worsening the city's
civic chaos.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo fired Donald Warshaw for refusing to fire the police
chief -- who had not informed the mayor in advance about the armed
federal raid to seize Elian Gonzalez from the home of his Miami
relatives on April 22. The police chief himself quit hours after
Warshaw was fired.
</P>
<P>
   A judge granted an injunction Tuesday blocking Warshaw's firing.
The ruling came after Warshaw presented sealed material alleging
Carollo ordered him to have several city commissioners
investigated.
</P>
<P>
   With Warshaw sitting quietly in his usual seat at commission
meetings about 20 feet away, Carollo said the injunction issued at
Warshaw's request ''was not valid.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You cannot have a kangaroo court,'' the Cuban-American mayor
said. ''This might happen in Cuba but never in an American city.''
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for Carollo has filed a motion seeking to dissolve
the order, saying it was ''causing a paralysis in the operation of
the city.'' And the mayor vowed to name a new city manager Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every hour that this man stays as manager, it puts the city in
jeopardy,'' Carollo said. ''He is trying to destroy everything he
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Carollo also accused Warshaw of having ''some of the palace
guards'' protect a ''Banana Republic'' sign that protesters had put
in front of City Hall on Monday night. The sign was gone the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was orchestrated. Those people were getting protection from
this manager,'' the mayor said. ''That was an extreme racist act.''
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw did not address Carollo's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ''These two gentlemen are using all the weapons they have for an
all-out war,'' Commissioner Tomas Regalado said after the meeting.
''The sensible thing to do will be just to move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
