<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fraternity Death Prompts Indictments  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINSVILLE, Ga. (AP) -- Four University of Georgia freshmen
were indicted on manslaughter charges Thursday in the case of a
student who died in a car wreck while handcuffed and blindfolded in
the cargo hold as part of a fraternity prank.
</P>
<P>
   Ben F. Grantham III, 20, of St. Simons Island, was killed March
30 when the sport utility vehicle he was riding in flipped over and
crashed into a tree.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, David Penn of Marietta, and three surviving
passengers were charged with involuntary manslaughter as well as
vehicular homicide. Vehicular homicide carries up to 15 years in
prison; involuntary manslaughter can bring up to 10.
</P>
<P>
   The four survivors were pledges of Alpha Tau Omega; Grantham was
a full member. Authorities have said the pledges traveled from
Athens into rural Oconee County with Grantham in the back of Penn's
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers estimate that Penn reached speeds of 45 mph or more
before the vehicle careened off the gravel road.
</P>
<P>
   University officials have said Penn was driving up to 90 mph.
Tests of Penn's blood alcohol level were negative.
</P>
<P>
   Also indicted were Stephen Ashley McNally of Richmond, Va.;
Gregory Scott Lakas of Lawrenceville, and Robert Walter Dailey of
Dalton.
</P>
<P>
   Penn's lawyer, Ed Tolley, said the wreck was an unfortunate
accident but ''not criminal behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Tolley said a sudden change from asphalt to gravel, along with
the design of Penn's truck, were prime causes of the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were all friends; they were just playing,'' Tolley said.
''This was traditional, historic behavior by this fraternity.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Harry Gordon said the case was a prank among
friends that turned tragic.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is based on the boys causing Ben Grantham's death by
driving recklessly,'' Gordon said. ''As tragic as it was, it
shouldn't have happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the accident, the fraternity has voted to dissolve its
charter. Penn was suspended from the university for a year and 11
other students implicated in the prank but not directly involved in
the accident have faced sanctions in university conduct court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
