<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Mediator Enters Mideast Talks  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A U.S. mediator tried Thursday to sort out the
latest crisis in Israeli-Palestinian talks after the Palestinians
complained that Israel offered them chunks of land in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip rather than connected territory for their future
state.
</P>
<P>
   The envoy, Dennis Ross, also met with the leader of a key
political party that has resisted making territorial concessions
and holds the key to approval of any agreement Prime Minister Ehud
Barak works out with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians said Israel offered a map of three disconnected
cantons, two in the West Bank and one in the Gaza Strip, amounting
to about two-thirds of the territory. It would mark the first time
Israel has outlined its offer for what they have indicated would
become a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's office denied that maps were presented to the
Palestinians at the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians demand all the West Bank and Gaza for their
state. They said the unacceptable map offer created a crisis, and
walked out of the talks in the southern Israeli resort of Eilat.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, who was taking part in the negotiations, later met with
Barak. Neither side commented on the meeting. Ross planned a
meeting with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ross and U.S. Ambassador Martin Indyk also met with Labor and
Welfare Minister Eli Ishai, head of Shas, an Orthodox Jewish party
representing Israelis of North African origin, to discuss the
implications of handing territory to the Palestinians. Shas, the
second-largest party in Barak's coalition, is hesitant to back
concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Ishai said they discussed how the peace process relates to
Israel's security interests. Citing security and religious reasons,
Shas leaders are dragging their feet over peace moves, also
concerned that their hard-line constituency would not back handing
over West Bank territory to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Ross usually confines his meetings to Israeli leaders directly
involved in the negotiations, like Barak and Foreign Minister David
Levy. His session with Ishai underlined the significance of Shas
support for a peace deal. Without Shas, Barak would face difficulty
gaining parliamentary approval.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven years since Israel and the Palestinians signed
their first agreement, the talks have sputtered from crisis to
crisis instead of increasing confidence as envisioned by the step
by step approach to peace.
</P>
<P>
   Signing their last interim peace accord on Sept. 4 in the
Egyptian resort of Sharm el-Sheikh, the two sides set target dates
of May for a framework and September for signing a peace treaty.
Ross said they need six to eight more weeks to negotiate the
framework.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
