<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressCharles Banfe:
<TEXT>
<P>
   MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) -- Charles Banfe, a longtime airline
pilot, Stanford University instructor and adventurer who twice flew
small planes solo around the world, died March 17 of pneumonia. He
was 82.
</P>
<P>
   He taught business, technology and airline management courses at
the Stanford business school for 20 years, and was a pilot for Pan
American Airways for 37 years.
</P>
<P>
   Banfe piloted planes from the time of the China Clipper to the
Boeing 747. One of his most famous passengers during his career was
Charles Lindbergh, whom he invited up to the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   Banfe's first solo trip around the world was in 1958. His second
circumnavigation, in a twin-engine Beechcraft Bonanza, was to
celebrate Hawaiian statehood in 1960.
Laurie C. Battle:
</P>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Former U.S. Rep. Laurie C. Battle, who
represented Birmingham's old 9th District in the post-World War II
years and made a run for governor in 1958, died Tuesday. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat, Battle was a staunch anti-communist who served four
terms from 1947 to 1955. He is known for the Battle Act, which
banned U.S. aid to countries doing business with the former Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   After four terms in the House, Battle ran for the Senate but
lost in the primary. In 1958, he ran for governor but lost in the
Democratic primary.
Brack Curry:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Brack Curry, an Associated Press reporter and
editor for 45 years, died Wednesday of a heart ailment. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Curry had worked as an international affairs editor in the
Washington bureau for 17 years before his retirement in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He began his journalism career in Dallas, Texas, in 1941, and
was posted at AP bureaus in New York, London, Berlin and Bonn. He
also served as chief of AP's Scandinavian services, in charge of
coverage for Sweden, Norway, Finland and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   Curry covered a wide range of foreign policy, defense and
political issues while in Washington and received plaudits from
editors around the world for his skilled chronicling of U.S. news
for AP's international subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   Curry is survived by his wife, Nadine Curry, of Alexandria.
Terry Moore:
</P>
<P>
   AMARILLO, Texas (AP) -- Terry Moore, an Amarillo Globe-News staff
writer and columnist who was honored for accounts of his battle
with lung cancer, died Wednesday. He was 32.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Moore won first place in the Class AAA division for
General Column Writing at the Texas Associated Press Managing
Editors' annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In his columns, Moore wrote of his wife, Suzy, and her courage.
He also shared with readers his pain at the thought of leaving sons
Ben, 10, and 6-year-old Brett without a father.
</P>
<P>
   Moore joined the Globe-News as a part-time sports clerk in
January 1996. He became a full-time sports writer in August 1996
and was named outdoors writer in November of that year.
</P>
<P>
   Moore worked as a sportscaster for radio station KSLV in Monte
Vista, Colo., from 1991 to 1994, and then worked for the Valley
Courier newspaper in Alamosa in 1994-95.
Seymour Sudman:
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) -- Seymour Sudman, a professor at the
University of Illinois and a pioneer in the field of survey
research, died Tuesday from complications following a stroke. He
was 71.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Sudman won the highest honor given by the American
Association for Public Opinion Research. He also was a fellow of
the American Statistical Association.
</P>
<P>
   A pioneer in survey sampling and the design of survey
questionnaires, he was the author or a co-author of such classics
in the field as ''Applied Sampling'' (1976), ''Asking Questions''
(1982), ''Polls and Surveys'' (1988), and ''Thinking About Answers:
Application of Cognitive Processes to Survey Methodology'' (1996).
He was particularly fascinated with how the wording of questions
affected poll results.
</P>
<P>
   From 1962 to 1968, he was the director of sampling and senior
study director at the National Opinion Research Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 2128 </TRAILER>
