<HEADLINE> Notes From Thursday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Yankees:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK: 2B Chuck Knoblauch was examined at Beth Israel North
hospital by team physician Dr. Stewart Hershon and hand specialist
Dr. Susan Scott. Additional tests consisting of a bone scan were
normal. He's day-to-day with a mild sprain of his left wrist.
Angels-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Scott Spiezio's three RBIs Thursday were a season high.
... Vaughn has hit 32 homers against Baltimore, tied with Albert
Belle for second among active players behind Jose Canseco (34). ...
SS Gary DiSarcina missed a second straight game with tightness in
his right shoulder. ... The Angels have homered in 10 straight
games.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: The Orioles activated RHP Scott Erickson off the
disabled list and optioned RHP Gabe Molina to Triple-A Rochester.
Erickson will make his season debut Friday in New York. ...
Mussina's 4 1-3 innings against Anaheim on Thursday was his
shortest stint of the season. ... C Willie Morales (elbow injury)
left for Florida for a rehab assignment. He was placed on the
15-day disabled list on April 17.
Indians-Blue Jays:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: C Sandy Alomar, on the 15-day disabled list with a
pulled right hamstring, began a rehab assignment in Winter Haven on
Thursday. He caught four innings and was 1-for-4. ... RHP Bartolo
Colon, on the 15-day disabled list with a pulled left oblique
muscle, will make a rehab start for Triple-A Buffalo on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: Utility INF Craig Grebeck has been experiencing back
spasms since a minor car accident last weekend. He's day-to-day.
... Toronto manager Jim Fregosi expects the Indians to break out of
their hitting slump. ''They've played only 24 games, so I don't
think that's a true indication of their offense,'' Fregosi said.
Rangers-Devil Rays:
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: OF Gabe Kapler, injured running the bases in the series
opener Tuesday night, was placed on the 15-day disabled list --
retroactive to May 3 -- with a torn right quadriceps muscle. INF
Kelly Dransfeldt was recalled from Triple-A Oklahoma to fill the
roster opening. ... DH Rafael Palmeiro wasn't in the starting
lineup for the fourth time in five games because of a slight left
hamstring strain. Manager Johnny Oates said Palmeiro and 2B Luis
Alicea, who left Wednesday night's game because of tightness in his
left calf, could return Friday for the start of a weekend series
against Oakland. ... LHP Doug Davis is scheduled to make his first
start Sunday against the Athletics. RHP Mark Clark, who beat the
Devil Rays on Wednesday night, is moving to the bullpen for at
least the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: RHP Ryan Rupe (0-4, 9.68 ERA) was optioned to
Triple-A Durham. RHP Cory Lidle was recalled from Durham and will
work out of the bullpen. RHP Bryan Rekar will take Rupe's spot in
the rotation and is scheduled to make his first start of the season
Sunday at Boston. ... LHP Tony Saunders, who missed most of last
season after breaking his pitching arm, is throwing off a mound and
progressing toward facing hitters in batting practice. ... Manager
Larry Rothschild and pitcher Dwight Gooden delivered a $2,000 check
and about $6,500 worth of baseball equipment to the Belmont Heights
Little League in Tampa. The youth group lost about $5,000 worth of
food and equipment in a burglary. Gooden once played for Belmont
Heights on a team that also featured Gary Sheffield and Derek Bell.
Tigers-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: Manager Phil Garner said the spacious new ballpark back
home might actually end up being a hitters' park once the summer
winds set in. ''It might be like Colorado,'' he said. That might
help persuade Juan Gonzalez to sign an extension. ... Garner is
serving the next-to-last game of his eight-game suspension for the
Tigers' brawl with the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Second baseman Todd Walker, struggling at the plate
and in the field, was optioned to Triple-A Salt Lake City on
Thursday. Walker, who hit .316 in 1998 and .279 last year, is
batting .234 with two homers and eight RBIs in 77 at-bats this
year. The Twins brought up infielder Jay Canizaro to take Walker's
place. Canizaro hit .356 with nine double, two triples, six homers
and 32 RBIs in 27 games for Salt Lake City.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Pirates-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Right fielder Brian Giles is the latest to complain
about the Busch Stadium grass. He slipped and ripped a huge divot
trying to plant his feet and make a throw on Fernando Vina's double
in the first. A large strip across right field had to be replaced
because it was unsightly, and several players have complained about
the footing. ''It's like running on egg shells,'' Giles said.
''It's like running on ice out there.'' ... The Pirates are 5-4
since Jason Kendall moved from leadoff to third in the order,
although the replacement leadoff men are a combined 3-for-33 since
the switch. ... Thursday was the first of four consecutive day
games for the Pirates. ... Pirates pitchers had two walks, and none
before the eighth, after totaling 23 passes the previous three
games.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Reliever Darren Holmes, released April 21 by the
Arizona Diamondbacks, signed a contract Thursday and was in
uniform. He said he could have pitched, even after two days of
auditions. ''Hey listen, I pitched five years in Colorado, all
right? I'm used to it.'' ... Thomas Howard, a switch-hitter, batted
left-handed against left-hander Jason Christiansen on Wednesday
night. Howard is primarily a pinch hitter and has only 24 at-bats,
and he hit left-handed to help him concentrate. ''I've been too
anxious up there,'' he said. ... Cardinals pitchers had gone 42
innings without allowing a home run before Brian Giles and Kevin
Young connected off Pat Hentgen in the sixth Wednesday. ...
Outfielder Eric Davis wasn't getting caught in the hoopla over the
McGwire vs. Griffey matchup that starts Friday night in Cincinnati.
''They can put 5 million people in the stands and it won't affect
what's going on between the lines,'' Davis said. ''They're not
going to draw us offsides.''
Astros-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Roger Cedeno is 10-for-12 in stolen bases. He was
picked off at first base in the first inning and was caught
stealing at third base in the ninth. Cedeno, who finished second in
the NL with 66 steals last season, is one theft shy of 100 for his
career. ... Jeff Bagwell was hitting just .174 (4-for-23) before
Thursday's game when he went 2-for-4 with three RBIs. ''Bagwell was
in a little mini-slump but that never lasts long with him,''
manager Larry Dierker said. ... The Astros avoided being swept by
the Cubs for the first time since May 22-24, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Right-handed reliever Matt Karchner was optioned to
Triple-A Iowa on Thursday to make room on the roster for Ismael
Valdes. Karchner (1-1) was demoted for the second time this season.
He was on the opening day roster until April 10 when he was
optioned to Iowa after going 0-1 with a 9.53 ERA in six games. In
two outings since returning April 25, he has pitched 2 2-3
scoreless innings. ... WGN-TV broadcaster Steve Stone was
hospitalized Thursday with kidney stones. ... CF Damon Buford
extended his hitting streak to eight games with a single in the
second inning. He is batting .364 (12-for-33) during this stretch.
Reds-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: While not saying he was misquoted, RHP Paul Byrd
said his comments Wednesday night were misinterpreted. After
Philadelphia's 5-2 victory, Byrd said the city, the fans and the
media are negative. He stressed Thursday that he did not have a
problem with the fans, but only wants his teammates to stay
positive despite their 9-18 start. ... For the second straight
game, Mike Lieberthal fell into the dugout while chasing a foul
pop. He didn't hang on to either, but Rico Brogna caught the ball
off Lieberthal's glove Wednesday. ... Reliever Carlos Reyes refused
his assignment to Triple-A Scranton Wilkes-Barre. The Phillies have
10 days to trade or release him.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Dmitri Young extended his career-best hitting streak
to 12 games with a first-inning double. ... The 21 hits were the
most allowed by Cincinnati pitching this season. It was the most
hits the Phillies had since getting 22 against San Diego last
August. ... Jason Boyd made his Phillies debut. He struck out two
in one inning.
Mets-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: RHP Bobby Jones, who has been on the disabled list
since April 17 with a strained right calf, will rejoin the Mets on
Monday in Pittsburgh after making a rehab start at Triple-A Norfolk
the previous day. ... OF Darryl Hamilton flew to New York on
Thursday and will have surgery within the next week on his left big
toe. ... C Mike Piazza, who went 2-for-3 Thursday against Giants
starter Kirk Rueter, is hitting .500 (8-for-16) this season against
lefties.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: When Jeff Kent ended Wednesday's 8-5 San
Francisco win with a three-run homer in the bottom of the 11th, a
game that opened with New York's Jon Nunnally homering, it marked
just the seventh time since 1990 a game has started and ended with
a homer. ... OF Ellis Burks missed his sixth straight start with a
slight strain to his left quadriceps. He pinch hit for the second
straight game Thursday, taking a called third strike in the eighth.
Diamondbacks-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Milwaukee's Geoff Jenkins entered Thursday night's
game tied for the NL home run lead with 11. ... The Brewers' 4-1
victory Wednesday night over Arizona was only their second of the
season against a left-hander. ... In 19 innings of relief, the
Brewers' David Weathers has held batters to a .175 average.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Randy Johnson is scheduled to start Friday night
against San Diego. He was 6-0 in April with a 0.91 ERA, the third
pitcher in history to win six before May 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
