<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Subway Pusher Gets 25 Years to Life  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A mentally ill man who killed a woman by pushing
her in front of a subway train was sentenced Thursday to 25 years
to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Just before he was sentenced, Andrew Goldstein apologized to the
family of Kendra Ann Webdale, and blamed his failure to take his
medication for schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a horrible nightmare since this incident began,''
Goldstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, 30, was convicted of second-degree murder for killing
Webdale last year. He pushed the 32-year-old woman off a subway
platform into the path of a train.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe, based on the evidence at trial, the probation
reports, and the testimony of psychiatrists at trial, that Mr.
Goldstein is dangerous,'' Justice Carol Berkman said as she
sentenced the defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Because Goldstein attacked Webdale while refusing to take his
anti-psychotic medicine, the case led to a state law last year --
''Kendra's Law'' -- that allows violent mental patients to be
medicated by force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
