<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guilty Plea Expected in Pa. Mob Case  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Mob turncoat Ralph Natale is expected to
plead guilty in federal court to a criminal career that spanned
three decades and included murder, extortion, gambling and drug
distribution, according to court documents filed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Natale is believed to be the highest-ranking mobster ever to
cooperate with prosecutors. He has been assisting the investigation
into mob activities in Philadelphia and southern New Jersey since
last summer when he was arrested on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   His help led to the indictment in March of his reputed
successor, Joseph ''Skinny Joey'' Merlino, and 10 others on charges
of murder, attempted murder, racketeering, extortion, and illegal
gambling. A 19-count indictment in March of Camden Mayor Milton
Milan also alleged Natale and mob associates paid bribes and gave
lavish gifts to Milan.
</P>
<P>
   The papers filed Thursday in U.S. District Court by U.S.
Attorney Michael Stiles implicate Natale, 66, in two murders from
the 1970s and the slayings of five others in the 1990s. A plea
hearing was scheduled for Friday morning, although federal
prosecutors would not comment on the case Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The filing accused Natale of orchestrating a racketeering
conspiracy that included murder, extortion, illegal gambling, drug
trafficking, stolen cars, loan sharking and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Natale's attorney, Marc Neff, did not return calls seeking
comment Thursday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
