<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, May 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Navy Announces New Bombing Exercises
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The Navy wasted no time today in announcing new
bombing exercises on Puerto Rico's Vieques Island, which had been put on hold by
protests. Pentagon officials said the Navy planned to resume training within two
weeks using dummy bombs, according to an agreement reached between President
Clinton and Puerto Rican Gov. Pedro Rossello in January. Hundreds of federal
agents swept through the U.S. Navy's prized Atlantic training ground today,
removing 216 protesters without serious incident to end their yearlong
occupation of the bomb-strewn range.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Variations of 'ILOVEYOU' Virus Evolve
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- New variations of the software virus that seduced computer
users with an e-mail note proclaiming ''ILOVEYOU'' were already circulating by
this evening, including one disguised as a joke with an e-mail attachment
reading ''Very Funny.'' The virus has crippled government and corporate computer
networks around the world. In another malicious twist, the virus was designed to
destroy several types of increasingly popular computer files, including those
storing pictures, video and music.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Livingstone New London Mayor
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Exit polls show Londoners picked Ken Livingstone as their
first elected mayor. The British Broadcasting Corp. polls projected Livingstone
as the winner with 51 percent, followed by the Conservative Party's Steve
Norris. Notorious for his leftist views, Livingstone ran the capital's
metropolitan government before it was disbanded in 1986 by Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's government. Under his administration, the Greater London
Council had declared the city a nuclear-free zone, supported gay rights and cut
subway fares.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fraternity Death Prompts Indictments
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WATKINSVILLE, Ga. (AP) -- Four University of Georgia freshmen were indicted
on manslaughter charges today in the case of a student who died in a car wreck
while handcuffed and blindfolded in the cargo hold as part of a fraternity
prank. Ben F. Grantham III, 20, of St. Simons Island, was killed March 30 when
the sport utility vehicle he was riding in flipped over and crashed into a tree.
The driver, David Penn of Marietta, and three surviving passengers were charged
with involuntary manslaughter as well as vehicular homicide. Vehicular homicide
carries up to 15 years in prison; involuntary manslaughter can bring up to 10.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fortified Salt Could Help Anemics
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Scientists have developed a new technology to fortify ordinary
table salt with iron -- an advance experts say could help overcome the severe
anemia afflicting more than half the population in the developing world. Experts
hope adding iron to salt will improve health in developing nations as
effectively as fortifying salt with iodine. The United Nations children's agency
estimates the introduction of iodized salt has spared millions of children every
year from mental retardation. Salt is considered a good vehicle for providing
nutrients because it is one of the only dietary staples used in all regions of
the globe, and people worldwide consume about the same amount.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Greenspan Warns Banks On Risks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said today that
banks may be turning complacent about risks in the technology-flavored economy.
In a speech to a banking conference, Greenspan called such behavior by banks --
fueled by the record-breaking economic expansion -- ''somewhat disquieting.'' He
warned that banks must not become overconfident in their ability to manage
risks, especially as they venture into new types of financial activities.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 67; Nasdaq Up 12
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks drifted to a mixed finish today after a report of
slowing productivity growth intensified worries that the Federal Reserve will
raise interest rates by as much as a half-percentage point later this month. The
Dow Jones industrial average was down 67.64 at 10,412.49 and the Nasdaq
composite index was up 12.93 at 3,720.24. On the NYSE, advancing issues
outnumbered decliners 1,637-1,299.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Angels Beat Orioles 8-5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Scott Spiezio drove in three runs and Mo Vaughn hit his
second homer in two games as the Anaheim Angels pounded nemesis Mike Mussina and
beat the Baltimore Orioles 8-5 today. Tim Salmon also homered for the Angels,
who hit eight homers in winning two of three from Baltimore. Darin Erstad, the
AL batting leader, went 0-for-5 and failed to reach base for the first time in
28 games this season. Coming off a 138-pitch effort against Texas on Saturday,
Mussina retired the first five batters. But he yielded five straight hits in the
fourth inning and left in the fifth with Baltimore trailing 6-5.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</SUBHEAD>
