<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Drug Cases Dismissed in L.A.  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA DEUTSCH, AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The number of criminal convictions tossed out
because of a police scandal increased to more than 80 when six more
cases were dismissed Thursday and the city attorney notified 234
defendants their cases are being reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Larry Fidler, who has been in charge of
dismissing tainted cases, said the imprisonment of innocent people
is ''horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   ''But there is an overwhelming issue here which is the
credibility of the criminal justice system and that's not going to
go away,'' Fidler said.
</P>
<P>
   The corruption probe at the Los Angeles Police Department's
Rampart division centers on allegations that officers falsified
reports, beat, framed and even shot innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cases thrown out Thursday was the conviction of
Russell Newman, who served nearly seven years of a 12-year sentence
for selling cocaine. His lawyer, Matthew Kaestner, said outside
court that the only witness against Newman at his trial was
disgraced ex-officer Rafael Perez, who claimed Newman sold him
cocaine. The case was tried in 1992, a period before Perez claimed
he had become involved in framing defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Newman filed an affidavit saying he never sold drugs to Perez.
The district attorney's office sought dismissal of Newman's
conviction because of Perez's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, cooperating with police to lighten his punishment for
stealing cocaine, was a principal figure in most of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, City Attorney James Hahn sent letters to defense
lawyers for 234 people in misdemeanor cases that may be tainted by
the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cases involve situations where it appears that the
prosecution rested solely on officers who have been charged or are
currently under investigation,'' Hahn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
