<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge: Reveal Defense in Calif. Slay  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Defense lawyers for a white supremacist must
disclose next month whether they will present a mental illness
defense when he goes on trial charged with firing on a Jewish
community center and then killing a postman.
</P>
<P>
   With the trial of Buford O. Furrow set for Nov. 14, his lawyers
contended they were not required to state their intentions
regarding a psychiatric defense this far ahead of trial.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge Richard Paez said Thursday the defense
must not only tell the government if it plans such a defense but
also is required to disclose the names of expert witnesses it plans
to call and the opinions they will offer.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow is charged with killing letter carrier Joseph Ileto just
hours after he allegedly wounded three boys, a teen-age girl and a
woman at the North Valley Jewish Community Center. He has pleaded
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered Furrow's lawyers to submit their plans by June
26, the deadline for a round of pretrial filings in the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
