<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Withdraws From SLA Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- An attorney who has represented a former
Symbionese Liberation Army member since her arrest said Thursday
that she is leaving the defense team because of a medical problem.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Jordan notified Judge James Ideman that an ailment known
as trigeminal neuralgia will not permit her to participate in a
long, arduous trial. She said her client, Sara Jane Olson, has
asked noted San Francisco attorney Tony Serra to take her case.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan said her illness, the result of surgery long ago, causes
her extreme pain in her face.
</P>
<P>
   Olson, 53, is charged with the attempted pipe-bombing of police
cars in Los Angeles 25 years ago. She was a fugitive until her
arrest last year in St. Paul, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   The judge has ruled that prosecutors can introduce evidence
dealing with the history of the SLA, the kidnapping of heiress
Patty Hearst and other uncharged crimes, a decision the defense
said would lengthen the trial to many months.
</P>
<P>
   Ideman has not yet ruled on Jordan's request to withdraw from
the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
