<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton blasts Giuliani on Helms, Elian hearings  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLATTSBURGH, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton attacked Senate
rival Rudolph Giuliani on Thursday for saying he would vote to keep
Jesse Helms as chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
and over his call for congressional hearings on the Elian Gonzalez
case.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Giuliani postponed a new round of TV commercials in
deference to the death of Cardinal John O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today is a time for all New Yorkers to reflect on John
Cardinal O'Connor and what he meant to us all,'' said Bruce
Teitelbaum, Giuliani's campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised O'Connor as a ''champion of the rights of
working people,'' and said she planned to attend his funeral
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani announced last week that he is suffering from treatable
prostate cancer and has said he is uncertain if he will be able to
continue in the Senate race. On Thursday, Gov. George Pataki told
reporters that he has ruled out running for Senate whether or not
Giuliani stays in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love my job as governor,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Giuliani's cancer announcement, Clinton had
dropped her criticism of the mayor. That self-imposed embargo ended
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very disappointed the mayor would continue to politicize
this little boy's future and this case which is properly in the
courts,'' the first lady told reporters in answer to a question
about the mayor's call Wednesday night for hearings on the Gonzalez
case. ''I do not believe further hearings in the Congress are
called for.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss dismissed
Clinton's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mrs. Clinton has taken so many divergent and contradictory
positions on the fate of this boy, we're sure that come next week
she'll be calling for hearings also,'' Glover Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   At a televised college forum from Rochester, the New York City
mayor also said Wednesday that if he were in the Senate he would
vote to keep the conservative Helms as chairman of the powerful
Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the big differences between me and the mayor is that I
would not vote to make Jesse Helms the chairman,'' Clinton said.
''We've had a lot of problems with the chairman pertaining to votes
on issues that have been lying dormant in his committee for many
years.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Glover Weiss said, ''Just as the mayor believes
that wide diversity in communities is a strength, he believes that
diversity in political parties is healthy too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 2243 </TRAILER>
