<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 23:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, May 4, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
'ILOVEYOU' Virus Hits Computers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Federal Bureau of Investigation quickly opened a
criminal investigation into the ''ILOVEYOU'' virus today, while computer
security firms scurried to post software on their Web sites to scan for the bug
and remove it from infected machines. The virus targets computers running on
Microsoft's Windows operating system, attacking the Outlook e-mail program and
the Internet Explorer browser, both of which are also made by Microsoft. It
spreads like most e-mail viruses, arriving as a seemingly friendly message,
infiltrating a person's computer address book and sending copies of itself to
contacts listed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel Retaliates for Lebanon Attack
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli warplanes struck at Lebanese power stations
and a guerrilla stronghold early Friday, retaliating for Hezbollah rocket
attacks on Israel that left one dead and 26 injured, witnesses and the Israeli
military said. There was no immediate word on casualties from the israeli
airstrikes. Large parts of the capital and northern and eastern Lebanon were
plunged into immediate darkness after the raids. Israel confirmed the airstrikes
and said were in retaliation for the Thursday's Katyusha rocket attacks. The
Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas had said their cross-border shelling was to avenge
civilian casualties from Israeli raids Wednesday in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Albright Warns Iran on Jews' Trial
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright warned Iran on today
that the outcome of its trial of 13 Jews on spy charges could have international
repercussions. The 13 Jews face death sentences on charges of spying for Israel.
Three have confessed, but the State Department has questioned whether the trial
conforms with worldwide standards of due process. Albright, whose own Jewish
roots became known when she was named secretary of state, said the treatment of
Jews is an accurate barometer of democracy, that where Jews are endangered,
other groups are targeted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Livingstone New London Mayor
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Exit polls show Londoners picked Ken Livingstone as their
first elected mayor. The British Broadcasting Corp. polls projected Livingstone
as the winner with 51 percent, followed by the Conservative Party's Steve
Norris. Notorious for his leftist views, Livingstone ran the capital's
metropolitan government before it was disbanded in 1986 by Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's government. Under his administration, the Greater London
Council had declared the city a nuclear-free zone, supported gay rights and cut
subway fares.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Navy Announces New Bombing Exercises
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The Navy wasted no time today in announcing new
bombing exercises on Puerto Rico's Vieques Island, which had been put on hold by
protests. Pentagon officials said the Navy planned to resume training within two
weeks using dummy bombs, according to an agreement reached between President
Clinton and Puerto Rican Gov. Pedro Rossello in January. Hundreds of federal
agents swept through the U.S. Navy's prized Atlantic training ground today,
removing 216 protesters without serious incident to end their yearlong
occupation of the bomb-strewn range.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rare Planetary Grouping Obscured
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Five planets, the sun and the crescent moon arerouping
together in the sky for what would be a rare celestial spectacle if it were not
completely obscured by the sun's glare. Astronomers say Friday's planetary
pileup will mark the tightest alignment of Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn
and the moon since 1962. For centuries, doomsayers have predicted the end of the
world whenever an unusual alignment occurs. But astronomers say the planet has
never reacted to such an event.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 67; Nasdaq Up 12
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks drifted to a mixed finish today after a report of
slowing productivity growth intensified worries that the Federal Reserve will
raise interest rates by as much as a half-percentage point later this month. The
Dow Jones industrial average was down 67.64 at 10,412.49 and the Nasdaq
composite index was up 12.93 at 3,720.24. On the NYSE, advancing issues
outnumbered decliners 1,637-1,299.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Blue Jays Beat Indians 8-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- David Wells pitched eight strong innings and the Toronto Blue
Jays sent the Cleveland Indians to their fifth straight loss, 8-1 tonight. In a
matchup between two of the AL's top left-handers, Wells (5-1) looked a lot
sharper than Chuck Finley (3-1). Wells won his fourth straight decision,
improving to 12-3 lifetime against the Indians. Wells allowed one run -- it
wasn't earned -- and seven hits. He struck out six and walked three. The Indians
were without manager Charlie Manuel, who will have surgery Friday to reattach
his colon. He had eight inches of his colon removed in February when it ruptured
during spring training.
</P>
