<HEADLINE> Report Pushes TB Fight  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD, AP Medical Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tuberculosis has reached an all-time low among
Americans, but the nation is at risk for an epidemic resurgence
without aggressive steps, say new recommendations. They urge, among
other things, treating immigrants who carry the lung infection but
aren't yet sick.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's report by the Institute of Medicine expresses concern
the nation could repeat a mistake: When tuberculosis dropped
markedly in the 1970s, Congress eliminated funding for TB control.
By the late 1980s, the disease was on an upswing and deadly
drug-resistant strains had emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Progress resumed recently and TB dropped to an all-time low of
18,631 cases in 1998, but health workers can't become complacent
again, the report warned.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, TB kills between 2 million and 3 million people
annually, making it a continuing threat here. Some 41 percent of
all new TB cases in this country are among immigrants from
high-risk countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a real opportunity,'' said report co-author Dr. C.
Patrick Chaulk of the Annie Casey Foundation. ''There's no way we
can ever think about getting TB under control in this country
without addressing ... poor countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuberculosis is an airborne disease spread mostly through close
contact by people with active infections. Many people unknowingly
harbor dormant TB -- they have no symptoms but are at risk for
suddenly getting sick and then spreading TB. The good news is that
antibiotics can cure them before that happens.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating TB in the United States would require identifying
and curing people with latent infections, says the IOM panel, which
recommended starting with immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Today, prospective immigrants get a chest X-ray to check for
active TB, and anyone who is sick must be treated before a visa is
granted. The new recommendation urges that prospective immigrants
from high-risk countries also undergo a TB skin test to detect
latent TB.
</P>
<P>
   People with latent TB could still come to the United States,
Chaulk stressed, but they would be required to get treatment,
available at low cost from U.S. health departments, before
receiving a permanent residency card.
</P>
<P>
   Such a program could test 250,000 people a year and prevent
2,100 cases of TB, the report said. It would cost about $23
million, less than the cost of treating those same people if their
TB flared, Chaulk said.
</P>
<P>
   An Immigration and Naturalization Service spokeswoman said the
agency would consider the report.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective immigrants are used to health tests, said Cecilia
Munoz of the National Council of La Raza, an Hispanic advocacy
group. ''As long as it doesn't represent an excessive burden in
terms of time or cost or keeping people out who aren't a threat ...
I don't imagine it will make a huge splash,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also recommended:
</P>
<P>
   --Tripling federal research spending, to $280 million, to develop
better TB tests, treatments, even a vaccine, that could fight the
disease worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   --Administering TB skin tests in prisons, also high-risk areas.
</P>
<P>
   --Urging health centers to launch foreign-language TB education
programs that encourage testing and treatment of latent infection.
An estimated 7 million foreign-born people with latent TB reside in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute of Medicine is part of the National Academy of
Sciences, a congressionally chartered agency that advises the
federal government on scientific issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 2312 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
