<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rigali will not replace Cardinal O'Connor in New York  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID SCOTT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- St. Louis Archbishop Justin Rigali is not
headed to New York to take over for Cardinal John O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving from Rome in St. Louis Thursday evening, Rigali said he
had been told by contacts inside the Vatican that he is not the
choice of Pope John Paul II to succeed O'Connor, who died Monday
night after a long fight with brain cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm in a position to say, quite categorically, at this time I
very definitely will remain the archbishop of St. Louis and I am
not going to New York,'' Rigali said, moments after stepping off a
plane at St. Louis-Lambert International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ''Through my contacts at the Holy See, I know I'm not going to
New York,'' the 65-year-old Rigali said.
</P>
<P>
   Rigali believes the pope has already selected O'Connor's
replacement, suggesting the decision was made before the cardinal's
death Wednesday. He expects an announcement soon, he said, because
the Vatican doesn't want to leave New York without a leader for an
extended period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people of New York are thinking very much in terms of
their loss, in terms of how they have lost a great friend, a great
pastor, someone who has really loved them,'' Rigali said.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome this week for a meeting of the Papal Foundation, Rigali
said he learned of O'Connor's death early Thursday morning. He did
meet with the pope while in Rome, along with several American
bishops, on Tuesday. At that time, the topic of a successor was not
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Los Angeles, Rigali is one of seven children. He
attended parochial schools and seminaries in California and was
ordained a priest in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   He left the U.S. for the Vatican and began a career as a
diplomat. He became the head of the Vatican diplomatic school and
served as the papal translator. When John Paul II talked to Mother
Teresa, Rigali stood beside them translating.
</P>
<P>
   Rigali described O'Connor as a great friend. During Rigali's
time in Rome, he and O'Connor had a standing date for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ''On (his) frequent visits to Rome, which may have been once a
month, he gave me the great honor of reserving the first evening
after his arrival to have dinner with me,'' Rigali said. ''That
gave me the opportunity to be with him numerous times.''
</P>
<P>
   Rigali had never led a parish when he was appointed archbishop
of St. Louis in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Rigali's name has appeared on the short list of
candidates for positions in the church. When the Chicago
archdiocese's Cardinal Joseph Bernardin died, Rigali was mentioned
as a possible successor.
</P>
<P>
   Rigali hosted the visit of the pope to St. Louis in 1999 -- the
only such visit to a single diocese in the United States during
John Paul's 21-year pontificate.
</P>
<P>
   If Rigali were appointed to the New York post, he would become
the first St. Louis archbishop to leave to lead another diocese.
All of Rigali's predecessors -- dating back to the 1820s -- stayed in
St. Louis for life. Three were named cardinals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-04-00 2325 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
