<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-04 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Ex-Rebels Deny Hostages  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDRA ZAVIS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Sierra Leone's feared ex-rebels
insisted Thursday they were holding no hostages, even as
international leaders condemned their attacks this week on U.N.
peacekeepers in which an estimated 92 people were captured,
including four who are presumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   The violence -- a major blow to nation's already fragile peace
process -- erupted Monday as the United Nations tried to take
control of security from a Nigerian-led West African intervention
force that was preparing to leave Tuesday after helping end Sierra
Leone's 8-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel Revolutionary United Front blamed U.N. peacekeepers
for the clashes, claiming they were forcibly disarming RUF fighters
-- a charge U.N. officials denied.
</P>
<P>
   ''Disarmament is voluntary, it should not be done by force,''
RUF spokesman Eldred Collins said,adding that six rebel fighters
were killed in the clashes.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes began Monday when RUF rebels began seizing U.N.
staff in three towns -- Makeni and Magburaka in central Sierra Leone
and Kailahun in the east -- after the United Nations refused to hand
over 10 rebel fighters who had come to a U.N. disarmament center to
turn in their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials initially reported seven peacekeepers were killed
in the fighting, but revised down the estimated death toll Thursday
to four missing and presumed dead. Casualty figures could fluctuate
still with the fluidity of the situation, U.N. officials stressed.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel leader Foday Sankoh, who pledged Wednesday to ''release
any hostages if held,'' continued to deny Thursday that the RUF had
seized any U.N. workers at all.
</P>
<P>
   But the United Nations says the RUF seized at least 92 U.N.
staff -- including unarmed military observers, armed peacekeepers
and civilian personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, U.N. officials put the number of hostages at 69. But
later Thursday, U.N. spokeswoman Marie Okabe told a press
conference in New York that a 23-man unit of an armed Indian
battalion was reported to be surrounded Thursday by RUF rebels in
Kuiva, near Kailahun in eastern Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council and Secretary-General Kofi Annan have
condemned the attacks and blamed Sankoh for them. Annan on Thursday
lobbied African leaders to exert pressure on the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Annan said the United Nations was seeking to
mobilize a rapid-reaction force to move into Sierra Leone to
reinforce the 8,700-member U.N. mission that has come under attack
by rebels of the Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Britain and France have been approached, but
so far none have committed any troops or logistical help, Annan
told reporters. Britain and the United States both ruled out any
ground troops on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. spokesman Philip Winslow, speaking in Freetown, called the
detention of the U.N. personnel ''unlawful'' and noted that the
general amnesty included in a shaky July peace accord does not
extend to crimes committed after the deal was signed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The people who have done this will be held accountable for
their actions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The French Foreign Ministry on Thursday called it ''inadmissible
that the forces and personnel of the United Nations, who are only
deployed in Sierra Leone to assure the implementation of the Lome
peace accord, should be targeted by some of the parties there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenyan President Daniel Arap Moi said the death of Kenyan
peacekeepers was ''of great concern and deep sorrow to him.'' The
statement did not say how many Kenyans were killed.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher called
Sankoh's actions ''outrageous and crimnal.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Britain called for the U.N. peacekeeping force to be
increased quickly to its full strength.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. mission, called UNAMSIL, was dispatched in January to
oversee the cease-fire and July peace agreement between rebels and
the government that ended a bloody eight-year civil war. When
created, the mission was given an authorized strength of 11,100,
but so far only 8,500 peacekeepers have been deployed. The rest of
the troops were expected to arrive by July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-04-00 2341 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
